{"_id":"2jhFmGAS3oOntIAW","name":"Vehicles - Trailers","content":"<p><strong>Source <a title=\"Trailers\" href=\"https://docs.google.com/document/d/1EPdMWRFoQcH9SgBecKxU4q6k523FThdzcZ7BVcg9mrM/edit?usp=sharing\">Trailers</a></strong></p>\n<p>For vehicles that have enough power to pull more than their own weight, one of the easiest ways to drastically increase their utility is by towing a trailer. Like parasite vehicles, trailers are not able to move under their own power - in fact, they are considered separate from parasite vehicles because they are entirely unpowered. In order to move, an external force must act upon them. Usually, this is another vehicle pulling them, or gravity.</p>\n<p>Like other vehicles, trailers have a <strong>Size</strong>, <strong>Classification</strong>, <strong>Weight</strong>, and <strong>Cost</strong>. They additionally have a <strong>Capacity</strong>, which is the maximum weight the trailer is able to tolerate. They are able to support @Compendium[tsl-content.tsl-rules.LdfNkCeMnbYzUwaX]{Hardpoint} modifications, and unless otherwise specified in their entry, they have one Hardpoint equal to their Size just as any other vehicle by default.</p>\n<p>A vehicle is only able to haul trailers of the same or lower Classification, even if it has enough power to haul it. A vehicle may haul (or, at least, attempt to) haul as many trailers as it has the power to move - they can be hooked up to the same prime mover in a chain of trailers called a “road train.” Hooking up a trailer to a vehicle requires 1 minute for Steamhorse or Auto trailers, and 15 minutes for Heavy trailers. Unless otherwise specified, trailers can be assumed to be Open-Top vehicles.</p>\n<p>A vehicle that could ordinarily power itself can be towed while in an unpowered state - in these cases, the unpowered vehicle is treated as a trailer of its size and classification.</p>\n<p>Being meant for utility, each type of trailer is designed around a specific purpose, and may have special rules as a result.</p>\n<table border=\"1\">\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\" colspan=\"6\">Trailers</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Trailer</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Size</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Class</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Weight</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Capacity</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Cost</td>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Auto Carrier</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Colossal</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Heavy</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">24,000 lbs.</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">30,000 lbs.</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">750 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Box</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Huge</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Auto</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">2,700 lbs.</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">5,000 lbs.</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">115 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Bus-Body</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Gargantuan</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Heavy</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">12,500 lbs.</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">24,000 lbs.</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">600 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Chariot</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Large</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Steamhorse</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">450 lbs.</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">500 lbs.</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">110 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Dump</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Gargantuan</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Heavy</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">10,560 lbs.</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">35,000 lbs.</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">475 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Flatbed (Auto)</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Huge</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Auto</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">1,800 lbs.</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">4,800 lbs.</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">75 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Flatbed (Heavy)</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Colossal</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Heavy</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">13,500 lbs.</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">48,000 lbs.</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">350 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Hopper Bottom</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Gargantuan</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Heavy</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">12,000 lbs.</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">40,000 lbs.</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">425 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Livestock</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Colossal</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Heavy</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">18,500 lbs.</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">30,000 lbs.</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">380 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Lowboy</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Colossal</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Heavy</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">13,500 lbs.</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">60,000 lbs.</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">450 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Rickshaw</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Large</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Steamhorse</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">375 lbs.</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">1,000 lbs.</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">10 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Siege Weapon Carriage, Class 1</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Large</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Steamhorse</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">280 lbs.</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">3,500 lbs.</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">45 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Siege Weapon Carriage, Class 2</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Huge</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Auto</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">3,500 lbs.</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">15,000 lbs.</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">215 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Tank</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Gargantuan</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Heavy</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">10,000 lbs.</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">54,210 lbs.</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">650 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Van</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Colossal</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Heavy</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">17,000 lbs.</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">45,000 lbs.</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">500 gp</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p><strong>Auto Carrier:</strong> Back when Odium was still seen as the next frontier, rigs would transport personal and utility vehicles all around the continent using these specialized trailers. This two-layer trailer has strong metal ramps and hydraulic lifts to carry vehicles stacked atop one another without risking damage to them. Auto-carrier trailers are broken into four Huge Hardpoints by default, with each intended to hold a single Auto.</p>\n<p><strong>Box:</strong> These small, enclosed trailers offer an affordable solution for an Auto pilot to transport cargo. It has one Door at the rear of the trailer, and has 675 cubic feet of cargo space.</p>\n<p><strong>Bus-Body:</strong> If there are no buses available, these trailers are a great option for transporting people in relative comfort. This Hard-Top people-mover looks for all the world like a Bus with the pilot seat and engine removed. They have a Crew Capacity (no pilot or operator required in the trailer itself) equivalent to that of a Bus - 15 rows of 4 seats.</p>\n<p><strong>Chariot:</strong> These standing carts were traditionally pulled by horses, but the enterprising steamhorse pilot has started attaching them to their hogs as well. The chariot comes with a set of extensions that allow the steamhorse to be controlled from the chariot, allowing them to pilot the vehicle from the chariot rather than the steamhorse.</p>\n<p><strong>Dump:</strong> These trailers are used to transport loose cargo such as soil, building materials, or grain. They can lift from the front (near the rig pulling it), with a raising door at the back lifting to allow the material to be poured out of the rear of the trailer. If its Capacity is exceeded, the hydraulic lift will not be able to dump the load. Lifting the trailer and fully dumping the load takes 1 minute. Dump trailers have 650 cubic feet of cargo space.</p>\n<p><strong>Flatbed:</strong> These long, flat trailers make it easy to haul awkward cargo that can’t easily fit into other trailer types. This makes them one of the most flexible trailers available.</p>\n<p><strong>Hopper Bottom:</strong> These specialized trailers act much the same as dump trailers, and are often used for the same type of cargo. The primary difference is that they dump their loads through a hatch at the bottom, which always allows them to unload their cargo - even when overloaded. They have 650 cubic feet of cargo space, and can unload their cargo in 5 rounds.</p>\n<p><strong>Livestock:</strong> So-called because they are typically used to transport cattle, livestock trailers are often repurposed as mobile semi-armored platforms for infantry to shoot from. They are multi-tiered Hard-Top trailers with many slots cut into the side, allowing ranged weapon users a number of “murder-holes” to shoot out of while still providing decent cover.</p>\n<p><strong>Lowboy:</strong> These highly-specialized flatbed trailers are designed to carry extremely heavy loads more efficiently. They feature a low-swept deck that lies below the axles, which results in a 25% reduction in the felt Load on the pulling vehicle for cargo on the trailer. Another benefit that really only shows itself out in the wastes is that the low profile doesn’t allow climbing or driving underneath the trailer.</p>\n<p><strong>Rickshaw:</strong> These two-wheeled passenger wagons are pulled behind a ground Steamhorse. When attached, it increases the vehicle’s Crew Capacity by adding an extra row of +2.</p>\n<p><strong>Siege Weapon Carriage:</strong> These wheeled carriages are designed to make it easy to transport a siege weapon, then quickly set it up for use and pack it up for transport again. They are typically dragged behind a vehicle by their tail - a long, heavy piece of metal used as a counter-weight. While siege weapons are not usually fired while being transported, brave crews have proven it both possible and effective.</p>\n<p><strong>Tank:</strong> There is but one option to transport loose liquids by road - these large, cylindrical Hard-Top trailers can hold 6,500 units of liquid of any sort safely while under pressure. They are capable of holding flammable or other unsafe liquids as well as potable liquids, though the latter might not remain so without a thorough cleaning between hauls. </p>\n<p><strong>Van:</strong> Perhaps the most common trailer type, these massive enclosed box-style trailers can hold 3,950 cubic feet of cargo safely inside their Hard-Top structure. They have one Door in the rear, loading and unloading through the back.</p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"In2xLaPZGv8dRTFr":3},"flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.3YGaRa5LhyuHr6J5"}}}
{"_id":"5PRsKcEsizUcwGyz","name":"Vehicles - Body Descriptions","content":"<p><strong>Body:</strong> The cost for a vehicle Body is listed in the appropriate tables based on type and classification below. Unlike the other components, there are no base costs or modifiers for vehicle Bodies - the price listed is the final price. <br />        <strong>Crew Capacity </strong>is the arrangement and number of seats for the vehicle. They are presented as a list of numbers, each number representing a seat in the vehicle that can accommodate that number of passengers. Multiple rows of seats are represented by a + character separating each row. The sum total of these numbers represents the total number of occupants the vehicle can support. For example, a Crew Capacity of 3+3 would represent two seat rows, each seating three occupants, for a total crew capacity of six. Any additional occupants beyond this number cannot gain the benefits of being seated, such as being able to fasten a safety harness or access the vehicle controls.<br />        The <strong>Doors </strong>figure represents the number of doors the vehicle has that permit access in and out by crew. Typically, these doors are distributed evenly on the port and starboard (left and right) sides, with single remainders often situated at the rear of the vehicle or on the pilot’s side. Vehicles with zero doors have no inlet, usually requiring the occupants to jump in through the window. For this reason, vehicles with zero doors will usually also have an open top - if a vehicle has zero doors and a Hard Top, there is an additional 10 feet of movement required to enter the vehicle.<br /><strong>        Top </strong>states whether the vehicle has no top or a soft top (Open) or an enclosed cabin as part of the vehicle body (Hard). Occupants of vehicles with a Hard Top are protected from overhead area of effect attacks, and are considered to have total cover from above. They are also shielded from weather effects, such as rain or direct sunlight, as appropriate. Conversely, occupants of vehicles with an Open Top receive no protection from overhead attacks or weather effects, but all penalties on attack rolls and Armor Class from being in an enclosed space are halved.<br />        <strong>Weight </strong>is the total empty weight of an assembled vehicle in pounds. Additional modifications or other alterations that might affect weight will have their own weight attributes. The vehicle’s Weight does not include any potential cargo which, together with the vehicle’s Weight and the weight of all occupants, will contribute to the vehicle’s overall Load.<br />        <strong>Cargo Space</strong>, while not listed on the table, refers to the amount of total space the vehicle has dedicated to storing cargo. This is meant more as a guide for Game Masters to make judgment calls on what sort of content can fit in a vehicle, and unless otherwise specified, a vehicle is assumed to have 12 cubic feet of cargo space.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>        <strong>Ground:</strong> The cost for a Ground Body is listed on the table Ground Body Style Costs.</p>\n<p><em>        Barchetta:</em> The barchetta is a small open-top, two-seater racing Auto. Only recently has the term begun to see use in the automobile industry - typically, the term is for small personal boats. There is little chance of confusion, however, given the low quantity of boats in The Sundered Lands.</p>\n<p>        Barchettas have 0 cubic feet of cargo space.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p><em>        Big Axle:</em> One of the most insane vehicles ever devised, the big axle is little more than two massive man-sized wheels held together with a platform sitting close to the ground. The driver, madman that they are, stands on the platform and connects the wheels himself by sticking his arms into holds on either side, effectively making themselves the wheel.</p>\n<p>        Due to its bare-bones structure, the big axle has a base Armor rating of just 5 (from the large wheels on either side) and has no hit point value - instead, all damage it receives is done to its pilot as if the pilot themselves were the vehicle’s body. Its Armor Class is equal to its pilot’s Armor Class, but with a size penalty equal to the big axle’s. It provides cover to its pilot only from the sides, cannot be flipped, provides a 5% reduction in the vehicle’s Turning, and is capable of zero-axis pivot turns. The pilot of a big axle must use two arms and two legs to pilot the vehicle at all times.</p>\n<p>        Big axles have 0 cubic feet of cargo space.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p><em>        Buggy:</em> The buggy, sometimes called the dune buggy or the sandrail, is a bare-bones Auto body that has stripped away everything that isn’t absolutely necessary in order to minimize weight and maximize speed. Often, this means no body paneling, and thus no armor.</p>\n<p>        Due to their stripped-down build, buggies have a base Armor rating of 0, 10 Hit Points, and provide no cover to occupants, but provide a 5% bonus to the vehicle’s Speed and a 5% reduction in the vehicle’s Turning (minimum -1).</p>\n<p>        Buggies have 0 cubic feet of cargo space.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p><em>        Bus:</em> The bus is a large Auto designed to move a large number of passengers. Their seating arrangement features not only rows like other body styles, but in vertical columns as well. The Crew Capacity for this vehicle is listed as 1+(4x15). This represents the pilot in a seat by themselves, plus 15 rows seating 4. In the case of the bus, the seats of 4 are split into 2 seats, each seating 2 passengers, on either side of an aisle permitting crew to walk from the entire length of the vehicle.</p>\n<p>        The doors of a bus are also atypical. Instead of a door next to the pilot’s seat, the folding double-door is instead opposite the pilot, and is opened by the pilot with a lever. The second door is situated all the way at the back, and is used only as a second exit in case of an emergency. Some buses will also have hatches along the top, though these are not counted as true doors, and can only be opened from the inside.</p>\n<p>        Buses have 100 cubic feet of cargo space.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p><em>        Coupé:</em> The coupé is a sporty Auto, meant for fun and comfortable driving both in the city and on the country roads of Arlenia. In the much less pleasant Odium, it has instead found its place as a more solid, focused sprinter for scavengers who need something that can stand up to punishment and provide protection to its occupants than the more flexible but less protective Phaeton.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p><em>        Day Cab Rig:</em> If a rig is traveling only a short distance, the preferred choice is the day cab rig. Unlike the sleeper cab rig truck, the day cab rig truck has no attached cabin for resting while the vehicle is parked. The cabin is small and uncomfortable for resting, and the back wall is directly behind the seats, making it impossible to recline the seats. Anyone who sleeps in a day cab rig is automatically fatigued the next day.</p>\n<p>        Day cab rigs have 0 cubic feet of cargo space.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p><em>        Double-Decker Bus:</em> If a bus can efficiently transport many passengers, then maybe stacking two buses on top of each other is even better. This does lead to a more complex Crew Capacity, being listed as 1+(2x(4x15)). As with the bus, the bottom floor is a lone pilot and 15 rows seating 4, divided into 2 seats which each support 2 occupants on either side of a walkway that runs the length of the vehicle. The double-decker bus will also have a small staircase or ladder leading to the second floor, which is a duplicate of the first floor (minus the pilot).</p>\n<p>        The first floor of a double-decker bus is always a Hard Top, but the second floor can either be an Open Top or Hard Top. This is determined at the time of purchase or discovery, and cannot be changed except through modification.</p>\n<p>        Double-decker buses have 100 cubic feet of cargo space.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p><em>        Open-Wheel:</em> When an Auto Body is built with the intent of creating the most optimized racing vehicle for paved tracks, the result is the Open-Wheel. These vehicles are notable for having the wheels unprotected by the body, and for having only a single occupant (the pilot) situated in the direct center of the narrow, streamlined body.</p>\n<p>        Open-Wheel vehicles gain a 5% bonus to Speed, but suffer double penalties and reduce all Integrity Resistance by 1 when dealing with any sort of difficult terrain or while “off-roading.”</p>\n<p>        Open-Wheel vehicles have 0 cubic feet of cargo space.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p><em>        Phaeton: </em>The Phaeton is an open touring Auto meant for long-distance driving in style. They are heavy and have comfortable seats, which allows occupants to drive long distances without becoming tired or sore from the body moving constantly to react to inconsistencies in the road. In Odium, this trait makes them ideal vehicles for shooting while on the move. Occupants of a Phaeton have all penalties for attack rolls to fire on targets outside the vehicle halved.</p>\n<p>        Phaetons can also be purchased in the Double Phaeton and Triple Phaeton configurations using the Extra Seating (Phaeton) modification.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p><em>        Pickup:</em> The Pickup, or “ute” as it is more commonly known in Odium, is a utility vehicle meant to transport small amounts of cargo and personnel. The flexibility and low cost of the Pickup makes it an invaluable and treasured vehicle in Bastion, where they can be seen even driving through the tight streets of the Steamgrates and Industria to perform vital tasks. The crew cabin of a Pickup is a Hard Top, but the cargo bed is Open Top, leaving its cargo vulnerable to weather, attack, and theft.</p>\n<p>        Pickups have 72 cubic feet of cargo space, but their open cargo bed permits them to carry more cargo uncontained by a roof.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p><em>        Putter Pony:</em> The putter pony is a small, single-occupant steamhorse meant for short-distance traveling in tight, compact areas. They are a common sight in the Steamgrates and on The Slants, pulling small carts full of goods or transporting clients as a form of motorized rickshaw. They tend to have weak engines and are rarely seen outside of Bastion, as they cannot reliably outrun or defend against the considerable threats of Odium.</p>\n<p>        Putter ponies have 0 cubic feet of cargo space.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p><em>        Quad:</em> The quad is similar to the steamhorse in its uses and capabilities, but differs from them in one key aspect - the quad has twice as many wheels. This gives them certain advantages in a number of situations, particularly in applications that require greater stability than what a steamhorse can provide. Quad pilots receive a +2 bonus on Pilot skill checks to maintain control on difficult terrain, and on any skill checks or saving throws made to prevent a wreck.</p>\n<p>        Quads have 0 cubic feet of cargo space.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p><em>        Roadster:</em> The Roadster is a two-seat Auto with an open top and a slim frame, making it an ideal vehicle for hit-and-run tactics out in the wastes. These are frequently used to get up close on a prey vehicle and allow the passenger to board, then get away before suffering too much damage.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p><em>        Sedan:</em> The sedan is what immediately comes to mind when one thinks of an Auto. Four doors, two rows of seats, and occupants separated from the engine separated from the cargo bay. These vehicles see frequent use by scavenger guilds as an efficient people mover, and are sought out by wanderers of the wastes for the extra space to store companions or gear.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p><em>        Sleeper Cab Rig:</em> Unlike a day cab rig, the sleeper cab rig truck is ideal for long hauls across the wastes and trips lasting longer than a single day. These huge trucks have an extension to their body, called a sleeper berth, that includes a small cabin, allowing the pilot and possibly even other passengers to sleep in relative comfort and safety. Some of these machines can sit at even the upper limits of the Heavy classification, bordering on becoming Ultras. A curtain or small door separates the seating from the sleeper cabin, preventing any nosy oglers on the outside from seeing if the truck is occupied.</p>\n<p>        Sleeper cab rigs have sleeper berths which permit passengers to sleep peacefully in motion for any length of time, regardless of their Suspension Dependency. Their berths average around 155 cubic feet of space, but using them to store cargo would not permit sleeping in the berth, thus mitigating the benefit of having the sleeper berth in the first place.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p><em>        Steamhorse: </em>The original motorized bicycle, the steamhorse has transcended being just a vehicle and has become the focal center of a number of growing cultural movements all over the tsl-content. Few vehicles can match the flexibility and potential of the noble steamhorse, leading to there being a configuration or model available for just about anything. They can be seen in Bastion performing any task imaginable, and their agility and speed on any terrain make them a must-have for surviving out woop woop.</p>\n<p>        Steamhorses have 0 cubic feet of cargo space.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p><em>        Tank: </em>Rarely seen away from the Front, tanks are heavily-armored mobile fortresses that are terrifying to behold in battle. They are slow, cumbersome, and heavy - and tough and utterly unconcerned with nearly any obstacles in their path.</p>\n<p>        Tanks have a base Armor value of 30. As long as a tank’s chassis uses wheels, pedrail, tracks, or screws as locomotion, it is able to make a zero-axis pivot turn.</p>\n<p>        Tanks have 5 cubic feet of cargo space.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p><em>        Van: </em>Most simply put, the van is something like a snub-nosed, fully-enclosed Pickup. They are used to transport cargo as well as people, and they can be reconfigured on the fly depending on what role they might be serving at the time. Due to their cargo area always being enclosed, they are protected against weather and theft without needing a tonneau cover. This base flexibility comes at a price, though - they have far fewer options for modification than pickups.</p>\n<p>        Vans are able to remove their extra seating rows in order to increase their cargo space. By spending fifteen minutes, a technician with the proper tools can add or remove a row of seating, which in turn increases or decreases the Crew Capacity by 3, to a minimum Crew Capacity of 3 and a maximum of 3+3+3+3+3. For each row of seating removed, the van’s cargo space is increased by 60 cubic feet to a minimum of 200 cubic feet and a maximum of 500 cubic feet.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p><em>        Wagon: </em>The wagon (shortened from the more proper “station wagon”) is something of a cross between the van and the sedan. In addition to having the same seating arrangement as a sedan, the station wagon has an attached cargo space that is considerably larger than the sedan. The fifth door is the hatch, which exposes the cargo area and permits a particularly flexible character to climb into the crew area over the cargo (space permitting).</p>\n<p>        Wagons have 24 cubic feet of cargo space.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>        <strong>Aerial:</strong> The cost for an Aerial Body is listed on the table Aerial Body Style Costs.</p>\n<p><em>        Aerostat:</em> These smaller, softer cousins to the massive rigid airship offer an inexpensive but risky aerial transportation solution for those daring enough to ascend in one. These are best thought of as motorized hot air balloons, using a soft air bag filled with a lighter-than-air gas to float, with the engines powering propellers to move and turn. They are unarmored, and immediately start to fall if they take too much damage to their delicate balloons.</p>\n<p>        Aerostats have 5 Armor instead of the usual 15 for a Heavy classification vehicle. They are still considered Hard-Top vehicles, as their bodies are enclosed for the crew and cargo. Aerostats can go to Speed 0 without stalling, and are capable of hovering.</p>\n<p>        Aerostats have a notably smoother ride than other aerial vehicles, and permit passengers to sleep peacefully in motion for any length of time, regardless of their Suspension Dependency.</p>\n<p>        Aerostats are able to remove their extra seating rows in order to increase their cargo space. By spending fifteen minutes, a technician with the proper tools can add or remove a row of seating, which in turn increases or decreases the Crew Capacity by 2, to a minimum Crew Capacity of 2 and a maximum of 2+2+2+2. For each row of seating removed, the aerostat’s cargo space is increased by 50 cubic feet to a minimum of 200 cubic feet and a maximum of 350 cubic feet.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p><em>        Biplane:</em> These airplanes have two pairs of wings, stacked on top of one another. This gives them more surface area to provide lift, allowing them to turn more tightly and move at a slower speed without stalling. Introduced just before the beginning of the War, they have mostly lost their popularity in favor of much more advanced modern monoplanes. Still, many find them far too useful to give up on just yet.</p>\n<p>        Biplanes enjoy a 20% reduction in their Stall Speed, as well as a 10% increase in their Turning.</p>\n<p>        Biplanes have 3 cubic feet of cargo space.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p><em>        Gyrocopter:</em> These quick and quirky aircraft look much like a libellule at first glance, if not for the large propeller sticking up on a pole into the sky. This propeller works in tandem with the rudder that provides forward thrust, allowing it to hover in place once airborne. It’s this flexibility that sees them used most often by messengers or those delivering small, important items over short distances with terrain too rugged for ground vehicles. Some believe their further development will result in an aircraft that can take off and land vertically without sacrificing the speed of an airplane.</p>\n<p>        Due to their stripped-down build, gyrocopters have a base Armor rating of 0, 10 Hit Points, and provide no cover to occupants, but can go to Speed 0 without stalling, and are capable of hovering. However, they cannot gain any altitude when hovering, just maintain it and move on the same vertical plane.</p>\n<p>        Gyrocopters have 0 cubic feet of cargo space.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p><em>        Libellule:</em> Sometimes called cloud buggies, these small personal airplanes are considered by many to be the riskiest way to travel the skies. They manage to get and stay airborne mostly because they are so lightweight, typically because everything that isn’t absolutely essential has been stripped out of them, and because they are hardly larger than their pilot.</p>\n<p>        Due to their stripped-down build, libellules have a base Armor rating of 0, 10 Hit Points, and provide no cover to occupants, but provide a 5% bonus to the vehicle’s Speed and a 5% reduction in the vehicle’s Turning (minimum -1).</p>\n<p>        Libellules have 0 cubic feet of cargo space.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p><em>        Megaplane:</em> These scaled-up monoplanes are used for jobs too big for ordinary monoplanes - bombing runs, troop transport, passenger flights, large cargo hauls. They offer a reasonable option to fill the gap between the lighter, swifter monoplane and the monstrous Ultra-tier gigaplane.</p>\n<p>        Megaplanes are able to remove their extra seating rows in order to increase their cargo space. By spending fifteen minutes, a technician with the proper tools can add or remove a row of seating, which in turn increases or decreases the Crew Capacity by 2, to a minimum Crew Capacity of 2 and a maximum of 2+2+2+2+2+2+2. For each row of seating removed, the megaplane’s cargo space is increased by 75 cubic feet to a minimum of 200 cubic feet and a maximum of 650 cubic feet.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p><em>        Monoplane:</em> The quintessential aerial vehicle, monoplanes are the personal airplane seen in many a war film and poster swooping in to save the troops at the last moment. Whether it be scouting, bombing, dogfighting, or just to feel the freedom of flight, these versatile aircraft can do it all.</p>\n<p>        Monoplanes have 3 cubic feet of cargo space.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>        <strong>Aquatic:</strong> The cost for an Aquatic Body is listed on the table Aquatic Body Style Costs.</p>\n<p><em>        Barge: </em>This long, flat boat can be thought of as a self-propelled aquatic flatbed truck trailer. It’s best meant to transport cargo over water, and little else is as effective as a barge in this - even Ultras that perform the same task are essentially just barges on much larger scales.</p>\n<p>        Barges are listed as having a Crew Capacity of 1, and indeed, this is all that is required to operate the vessel. However, barges can support any number of crew moving about their deck - they simply can only offer the benefits of being seated and strapped in to their pilot.</p>\n<p>        Barges are Hard Top only for their wheelhouse, a small structure around the helm to protect the pilot from the weather. Some barges are also adapted to be used for other purposes, like house boats or makeshift battleships - they may have additional Hard Top enclosures as well.</p>\n<p>        Barges have 100 cubic feet of covered cargo space in their enclosed wheelhouses; otherwise, they can carry as much cargo as they can fit on their decks uncovered.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p><em>        Catamaran:</em> These unique boats have a distinct parallel hull design - instead of just one large hull, this ship is instead two hulls of equal size set beside each other and joined in the middle, so that water passes under the deck between the two hulls. The modern motorized catamaran is an adaptation of the Weheloan wa’a kaulua.</p>\n<p>        Catamarans have 0 cubic feet of cargo space.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p><em>        Dinghy:</em> Used for centuries as rowing tender for larger vessels, dinghies in modern times have an outboard motor that gives them speed and agility.</p>\n<p>        Dinghies have 0 cubic feet of cargo space.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p><em>        Runabout: </em>These small motorboats are well suited to carrying people across water comfortably. They’re often seen treating people to a relaxing day out on the water, but in places experiencing times of conflict, they serve the role of scouting craft and hit-and-fade striker craft.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p><em>        Skimmer:</em> These speedy little recreational watercraft are like steamhorses for the water. They are ridden by standing and holding onto a set of handlebars, though some may be driven seated and can seat extra passengers in a stack like steamhorses can. They frequently find their way into style competitions where pilots perform tricks.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p><em>        Thunderboat:</em> The fastest thing to be found on the water anywhere, thunderboats are specialized aquatic vehicles designed for one thing and one thing only: speed. These racing boats operate in a way not dissimilar to aircraft, with a special hull that forces water down as it travels, helping to lift the front of the boat out of the water and reduce drag.</p>\n<p>        Thunderboats have a 10% increase in both Speed and Turning. They have 0 cubic feet of cargo space.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p><em>        Yacht:</em> When one thinks of luxury watercraft, what usually springs to mind is the yacht. These ships come in all shapes and sizes, with some of the wealthiest individuals owning yachts that qualify as Ultras, but the most common yacht sits firmly in the Heavy class.</p>\n<p>        Yachts are listed as having a Crew Capacity of 1, and indeed, this is all that is required to operate the vessel. However, yachts can support any number of crew moving about their deck - they simply can only offer the benefits of being seated and strapped in to their pilot.</p>\n<p>        Yachts are Hard Top only for their cabins in the lower deck, which allow passengers on the vessel to sleep comfortably in an enclosed and safe space out of the weather. Yachts permit passengers to sleep peacefully in motion for any length of time, regardless of their Suspension Dependency.</p>\n<p>        Yachts have 100 cubic feet of covered cargo space in their enclosed cabins, though using it to store cargo prevents passengers from sleeping there; otherwise, they can carry as much cargo as they can fit on their decks uncovered.</p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"In2xLaPZGv8dRTFr":3},"flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.SdcXtZ7uPlcTlARj"}}}
{"_id":"8MAFpYXYpSpXieVu","name":"Vehicles - Transmission Descriptions","content":"<p><strong>Transmissions:</strong> The base cost for a transmission is listed on the table Component Costs - Transmission. Due to how the Engine and Transmission interact to determine the Speed and Torque values for the vehicle, a Transmission’s Power Transfer will always fall between 1 and 10. Some transmissions, however, are more flexible and are able to provide bonuses or even a range of Power Transfer stats depending on the situation.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>        <em>Manual:</em> The typical transmission attached to the overwhelming majority of vehicles in Bastion (and everywhere else), the manual is just that - a transmission that the driver must manually engage in order to change gears. A lever and a clutch pedal lead down to a metal case holding a series of gears, each of which engage with the rotating flywheel of the engine to provide power in a number of gear ratios to the drive shaft.</p>\n<p>        As the standard (also another name for them) for transmissions in Bastion, they provide no bonuses or penalties for their use.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>        <em>Sequential: </em>The sequential transmission is the next step up from a manual transmission. It still requires the driver to manually change gears, but rather than the driver having to manipulate the clutch and gear shift lever themselves, they simply indicate to the transmission when to change gears, and then the transmission does so by itself with much greater speed and efficiency than any human could. It comes with either a set of paddles on either side of the steering wheel, or a simple lever where the gear shift once was. Tapping a paddle or pushing the lever up or down instructs the transmission how to shift, allowing the driver to focus on other aspects of driving.</p>\n<p>        Pilots using a sequential transmission gain a bonus on all Pilot skill checks equal to their own Intelligence bonus, minimum 1. Additionally, the Transmission gains 1 point of Integrity Resistance.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>        <em>Horlogian: </em>If nothing else, the one thing that the horological engineers of Canton d’Horloge know more than anyone is gears. As an example of that expertise, they have developed the Horlogian Transmission, which is able to use a complex, finely-tuned series of gears and cogs to calculate the best times to shift and do so automatically, without any attention required by the pilot! These transmissions are notable for their complete lack of clutch or gear shift, replacing both with a small knob that tells the transmission whether it should travel forward, backward, neither, or just lock the transmission and prevent movement altogether.</p>\n<p>        Pilots using an horlogian transmission may always take 10 on Pilot skill checks, even if they are threatened or distracted. Additionally, the Transmission gains 1 point of Integrity Resistance.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>        <em>Spectrum:</em> Rather than stepping through a number of fixed gear ratios like other transmissions, a spectrum transmission uniquely is able to transition smoothly and seamlessly between a range of gear ratios. It does this with an uncommon pulley design - rather than a single-piece pulley disc, the pulleys in a spectrum transmission are instead two spinning cones that run alongside each other. To change gears, the cones either move closer together or further apart, effectively changing the “diameter” of the pulley for the belt that runs between them.</p>\n<p>        The spectrum transmission has a Power Transfer value and a Fluid value. As a standard action, the vehicle’s pilot can shift the transmission’s Power Transfer value up or down by a number of points equal to or less than the Fluid value, up to a maximum of the Fluid value’s distance from the base Power Transfer value. This change lasts until the pilot shifts the Power Transfer value again, or until the vehicle powers down - it will be at its base Power Transfer value again when it next powers on. A spectrum transmission’s Fluid value will always be at least 1, up to a maximum of 3.</p>\n<p>        To calculate the cost to purchase a spectrum transmission, find the cost of each value as a separate transmission and add them together. Then, find the result of 10 to the power of the spectrum transmission’s Fluid value, multiply that by the Fluid value, and add it to the original sum.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>        <em>Torque Converter:</em> Less a transmission and more a hydraulic coupling, the torque converter uses fluid to spin the drive shaft and transfer power to the wheels. The flywheel has an attached impeller, which throws a thick, viscous fluid against a fan on the drive shaft, turning the force of the thrown liquid into rotational energy as the fins of the fan deflect the liquid. In more complex units, additional discs in between can stage up the liquid to smoothly stage the increased rotation, creating a machine that is practically always at its ideal torque level. While the torque converter is an incredible piece of machinery, the effect is lost on vehicles of tremendous weight, thus limiting its use.</p>\n<p>        The torque converter has a Power Transfer value and a Fluid value. The lower of the two values is used when calculating the vehicle’s Speed; the higher of the two values is used for calculating the vehicle’s Torque. To calculate the cost to purchase a new torque converter, find the cost of each value as a separate transmission and add them together. Then, multiply that amount by the difference between the two separate Power Transfer values. This will be the cost in gp.</p>\n<p>        Torque converters are limited in their use to Steamhorses and Autos.</p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"In2xLaPZGv8dRTFr":3},"flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.2JniNSwRsFbTACqW"}}}
{"_id":"BkbGzqTSjkqWK7yy","name":"Dueling","content":"<p>Some, such as the nobility of Antquanettian-based societies and the samurai of Ijozora, believe strongly in the defense and maintenance of their honor (or, at least, the perception of their honor in the eyes of others). The most common way of defending that honor when one feels it has been besmirched is with the duel: a dramatic face-to-face confrontation in which each party attempts to force the other to submit to their demands or be subject to possible severe injury or even death.</p>\n<p>The process of conducting a duel is highly formalized in most cultures. Since duels are occasionally fatal to one or even both duelists, they are rarely provoked by minor insults or passing arguments. Each culture that utilizes dueling as a concept has a different process and tradition for how duels are carried out.</p>\n<p><strong>Antquanette and Arlenia:</strong> Only those holding a noble rank, by birth or otherwise, may challenge another (who must also be of noble rank) to a formal duel. Commoners will sometimes duel if they own suitable weapons, as will non-nobles of high repute, but it is technically illegal. Commoners may duel legally only if the initiator is challenging a man who has had carnal relations with his wife - he is allowed to retaliate against the man who has violated her.</p>\n<p>Most authorities will stop a duel between commoners if they know about it (not that this stops them from occurring), but the fear of backlash from the well-to-do keeps them from interfering with duels between the non-noble upper echelon. That said, most wealthy individuals will hold a noble rank anyway, typically given by the king and granting them entrance into a specific order. Only nobles may duel with pistols, as only nobles are permitted to own or carry handguns (and, in fact, they must carry a smoothbore dueling pistol at all times), except in Ataraxia, where anyone can legally own and carry a pistol, and on the outskirts of the Wanderer’s Desert, where everyone does anyway.</p>\n<p>To initiate a duel, the offended party must directly challenge the offending party, either verbally or in writing, in private or in public. The challenged can decline, but being a duel for honor, doing so sullies the challenged's honor and reputation, and implies to outsiders that the offending party's insults or claims against the offended party are baseless.</p>\n<p>When challenged to a duel, the challenged is permitted to select which weapon will be used. They may decide to fight with pistols or with swords. The pistols must be muzzle-loading, single-shot smoothbore pistols that satisfy the regulations. Swords must be fencing-style swords, such as a rapier. The challenged may make other suggestions outside of these two standard avenues to satisfying both parties' honor, but they are rarely suggested or accepted.</p>\n<p>Both parties are assumed to perform the duel themselves, but either party can propose the use of champions to replace them. In suggesting it, they open the other party to the option as well. If the offer to use a champion is declined, then neither may use champions and must settle the duel themselves. Once both parties have agreed to use a champion, the option cannot be revoked.</p>\n<p>All details are agreed upon by both parties before the duel takes place. It is scheduled, a location is chosen, their assistants and/or champions are announced, as well as the intermediary or judge. Whether an esoteric healer is present to tend to wounds afterward is also decided upon, and is considered the standard - though it may happen every once in a while, duels are not actually meant to be to the death.</p>\n<p>At any point, the one who delivered the first offense may issue an apology, written or spoken, public or private. The offended, should they accept, is expected to call off the duel, their honor being satisfied, and offer any apologies for insults they made in retort. The offended can refuse to accept the apology, but this is considered ungentlemanly when the apology is genuine.</p>\n<p><strong>Ijozora:</strong> The many complex cultural intricacies of Ijozoran high society make it difficult to avoid insulting someone in a way that might be taken as an attack against their honor. Thankfully, the warrior elite of Ijozora tend to be calm and collected, and refuse to allow a minor slight to drive them to emotional outbursts.</p>\n<p>When an Ijozoran samurai has been deeply wronged, however, and decides to challenge the offender to a duel, it is typically to an iaijustsu duel. Iaijutsu is the Ijozoran art of quick-draw sword combat, and the best Ijozoran samurai practitioners of this art are able to draw their sword so quickly that their opponent is slain before the eye even registers the movement.</p>\n<p>To initiate a duel, a samurai must first get his lord’s permission to issue the challenge. Since his life and body belongs to his lord, the lord must consent to a duel that could mean the loss of his property. If his lord agrees, the samurai seeks out his enemy and formally requests a duel, stating the reason for the challenge and precisely naming the terms of victory.</p>\n<p>If the second samurai is willing to fight the duel, he must ask his lord’s permission to accept. The challenged samurai may himself refuse to accept the duel, though this is not a particularly honorable course of action. His lord may refuse permission, or may name another samurai to accept the duel in place of the challenged samurai. Assuming permission is granted, the challenged samurai has the right to name the place where the duel will occur (always a public place, with witnesses from both sides), as well as the time (no more than one year in the future). If circumstances prevent one samurai from appearing at the appointed time for the duel, his lord may name a samurai to fight in his place.</p>\n<h2>Dueling Rules</h2>\n<p>After all of the organization has been accomplished and the time for the duel has arrived, the weapons for the duel are inspected by an intermediary (if that was part of the terms for the duel) to ensure that they adhered to the rules set forth by culture, terms of the duel, or both.</p>\n<p><strong>Hit Points:</strong> In a duel, hit points work differently than they do in normal combat. The duel is a tense, potentially fatal moment of lightning-fast and all-out combat between the participant duelists. Unfortunately, the highly abstracted hit points system in Pathfinder and other d20-based games do not support this well - it’s hard to create an environment of tension and fear for the outcome of a duel when a single attack will almost never threaten the life of a character after a certain level and, thus, number of hit points have been accrued.</p>\n<p>In a duel, all damage dealt is instead treated as Constitution damage. This creates a situation where it is highly possible for a single attack by any combatant to threaten the life of another combatant, regardless of either’s level or class. However, they are still able to improve their defensive qualities during a duel - each combatant gains an amount of “temporary hit points” equal to their ranks in the @Compendium[tsl-content.tsl-skills.qM2ju0s0DE1aSAiU]{Duel} skill. Before they take Constitution damage from an attack in a duel, these “temporary hit points” must first be depleted. These “temporary hit points” will henceforth be referred to as “dueling hit points.”</p>\n<p>A duel has two phases: the stand-off, and the strike. During the stand-off, the duelists face each other and study each other’s equipment, stance, and demeanor to assess their skill. The strike phase marks the beginning of the duel proper, wherein they make attacks against one another until either the duel is won, or is called off.</p>\n<p>Some duels, such as iaijutsu duels or the sort of pistol duels fought in the outskirts of the Wanderer’s Desert, see the opponents starting the duel with their weapons sheathed. In order to participate meaningfully in these types of duels, both duelists must have the Quick Draw feat. Spending a move-equivalent action to draw a weapon in the strike phase of a duel would almost certainly prove fatal. Specialized duelists master the @Compendium[tsl-content.tsl-skills.qM2ju0s0DE1aSAiU]{Duel} as well.</p>\n<p><strong>Stare Down:</strong> In the first round of a duel, the two duelists stand a few steps apart and appraise each other, looking for signs of their opponent’s skill, training, and reflex in their ready posture. Many duels go no further: one duelist concedes victory to the other, recognizing a clearly superior opponent. Conceding in this manner is not seen as dishonorable.</p>\n<p>When the duelists assume their stance, they each make a @Compendium[tsl-content.tsl-skills.qM2ju0s0DE1aSAiU]{Duel} check. The check result determines how much information they discern about the other duelist (per the Size Up use of the @Compendium[tsl-content.tsl-skills.qM2ju0s0DE1aSAiU]{Duel} skill), as well as how much bonus damage their first strike will deal (per the Bonus Damage use of the @Compendium[tsl-content.tsl-skills.qM2ju0s0DE1aSAiU]{Duel} skill).</p>\n<p><strong>Strike:</strong> After both duelists attempt their @Compendium[tsl-content.tsl-skills.qM2ju0s0DE1aSAiU]{Duel} checks, they draw their weapons and strike. Each duelist rolls an initiative check, gaining a circumstance bonus on the check equal to their ranks in the @Compendium[tsl-content.tsl-skills.qM2ju0s0DE1aSAiU]{Duel} skill. If they so choose, they may forego the initiative check to instead treat their @Compendium[tsl-content.tsl-skills.qM2ju0s0DE1aSAiU]{Duel} check result as their initiative check result.</p>\n<p>The first round of a duel’s strike phase is essentially a surprise round: each combatant can take only a standard action (usually an attack) in addition to drawing the weapon (a free action, assuming each duelist has the Quick Draw feat). With a successful hit, the winning duelist deals the bonus damage achieved through his earlier @Compendium[tsl-content.tsl-skills.qM2ju0s0DE1aSAiU]{Duel} check result, in addition to normal (or critical) weapon damage. The loser, if he is still standing, may choose to withdraw or continue with their attack. However, since they lost initiative and their opponent went first, they are no longer striking a flat-footed foe, and as such does not receive his @Compendium[tsl-content.tsl-skills.qM2ju0s0DE1aSAiU]{Duel} check bonus damage.</p>\n<p>If the difference of the initiative check results are less than 5, the initiative is treated as a tie, and the attacks are resolved at the exact same time. Both combatants are considered flat-footed, and both are entitled to bonus damage equal to their @Compendium[tsl-content.tsl-skills.qM2ju0s0DE1aSAiU]{Duel} check result (should they otherwise satisfy the necessary requirements to benefit from this bonus damage).</p>\n<p>After the initial round of the duel, the two duelists can continue fighting in normal combat, if both survive. Unlike normal combat, however, they may not take full attack actions - they are limited instead to standard action attacks only. They no longer receive any bonus damage dice to their attack rolls unless the circumstances under which @Compendium[tsl-content.tsl-skills.qM2ju0s0DE1aSAiU]{Duel} checks may be attempted somehow arise again in the course of the fight (the combat ends and one or the other returns his weapon to its sheath).</p>\n<p>Once either combatant withdraws from the duel, or a clear winner is declared, it is considered to be over. If their opponent continues attacking after the duel has been stopped in this manner, it is typically seen as highly dishonorable and (usually) an attempt to murder the opponent. This is occasionally seen in the form of the loser attacking the winner out of anger, when their back is turned. Each culture handles this differently, according to their own laws and customs.</p>\n<p><strong>Duel Bonus Damage in Normal Combat</strong>: You can use your @Compendium[tsl-content.tsl-skills.qM2ju0s0DE1aSAiU]{Duel} check bonus damage in normal combat too, but only when you are attacking a flat-footed opponent and you draw your weapon in the same round you strike. This means that a character with Quick Draw can use @Compendium[tsl-content.tsl-skills.qM2ju0s0DE1aSAiU]{Duel} in a surprise round. A character without Quick Draw cannot strike an opponent in a surprise round if he begins the round with his weapon sheathed. </p>\n<p>In a normal first round of combat, a character whose initiative is higher than his opponent’s can draw a weapon, move to the opponent, and attack using @Compendium[tsl-content.tsl-skills.qM2ju0s0DE1aSAiU]{Duel}, as long as he has either Quick Draw or a base attack bonus of +1 or higher (so that he can draw his weapon while he moves).</p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"In2xLaPZGv8dRTFr":3},"flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.OWIMA7ObdkKr07hO"}}}
{"_id":"CAQJi8Q3QI47tvSD","name":"Firearms Rules","content":"<p><strong>Source</strong> <a title=\"Firearms\" href=\"https://docs.google.com/document/d/1uUsLDWtoPz5SObt5OA39o66524wCfRB8YHJqkMzpIZ8/edit?usp=sharing\">Firearms</a></p>\n<p>This section details the rules for firearms and their accessories.</p>\n<h2 style=\"border-bottom:1px solid var(--color-underline-header)\">Firearms in the World</h2>\n<p><a title=\"Firearm Availability\" href=\"https://www.d20pfsrd.com/equipment/Weapons/firearms/#Firearms_in_Your_Campaign\">Firearm availability</a> and pricing is based on region. They are considered <strong>Commonplace</strong> in the regions of Redlyn and Odium - early firearms cost 25% in these regions, and advanced firearms will cost the listed price. Some regions will see <strong>Emerging Guns</strong> (the Ijozoran tanegashima or the Baluuric jezail), with most of the rest seeing the burgeoning technology of firearms tangentially from outside visitors (<strong>Very Rare Guns</strong>), or not at all (<strong>No Guns</strong>).</p>\n<h2 style=\"border-bottom:1px solid var(--color-underline-header)\">Firearm Rules</h2>\n<p><strong>Firearm Proficiency:</strong> Early firearms are treated as martial weapons. Martial weapon proficiency, granted either by class, by taking the Martial Weapon Proficiency (early firearms) feat, or by taking the Exotic Weapons Proficiency (firearms) feat, allows the character to use all appropriate firearms (except siege firearms) without penalty. A nonproficient character takes the standard -4 penalty on attack rolls with firearms, and a nonproficient character who loads a firearm increases all misfire values by 4 for the shots they load.</p>\n<p>Even though the Martial Weapon Proficiency (firearms) and Exotic Weapon Proficiency (firearms) feats grant a character proficiency with some or all non-siege firearms, anytime the character takes a feat that modifies a single type of weapon (such as Weapon Focus or Rapid Reload), the character must still pick one specific type of firearm (such as musket, axe musket, blunderbuss, pistol, or double pistol) for that feat to affect.</p>\n<p><strong>Capacity:</strong> A firearm’s capacity is the number of shots it can hold at one time before needing to be reloaded. When making a full-attack action, you may fire a firearm as many times in a round as you have attacks, up to this limit (or the weapon’s limit, if applicable), unless you can reload the weapon as a swift or free action while making a full-attack action.</p>\n<p><strong>Type:</strong> All firearms do both Bludgeoning and Piercing damage unless stated otherwise in their entry.</p>\n<p><strong>Range:</strong> Early firearms have a maximum range of five range increments. Advanced firearms have a maximum range of ten range increments.</p>\n<p><strong>Loading a Firearm:</strong> A character needs at least one hand free to load one-handed and two-handed firearms. In the case of two-handed firearms, the character holds the weapon in one hand and loads it with the other - they only need to hold it in two hands to aim and shoot the firearm. Loading siege firearms requires both hands, and one hand occasionally manipulates a large ramrod (which can be wielded as a club in combat). The Rapid Reload feat reduces the time required to load one-handed and two-handed firearms (unless otherwise stated in the weapon’s entry), but this feat does not reduce the time it takes to load siege firearms.</p>\n<p>Loading any firearm provokes attacks of opportunity, unless the reload takes only a swift or free action. Other rules for loading a firearm depend on whether the firearm is an early firearm or an advanced firearm.</p>\n<p><span style=\"font-family:var(--font-primary);font-size:var(--font-size-14);white-space:pre\"> </span><em>Early Firearms:</em> Early firearms are muzzle-loaded, requiring bullets or pellets and black powder to be rammed down the muzzle. If an early firearm has multiple barrels, each barrel must be loaded separately. It is a standard action to load each barrel of a one-handed early firearm and a full-round action to load each barrel of a two-handed early firearm.</p>\n<p><span style=\"font-family:var(--font-primary);font-size:var(--font-size-14);white-space:pre\"> </span><em>Advanced Firearms:</em> Advanced firearms are chamber-loaded. The wielder of an advanced firearm may reload a number of rounds on each reload (move) action across all held firearms equal to one-half their Base Attack Bonus (rounded down) plus their Dexterity modifier. Weapons that can be drawn as a free action during a reload may also be reloaded during a reload action, even if they are not held.</p>\n<p>Regardless of action type, a player may make only one reload action per round. Some weapons have special reloading rules that differ from the rules above; details are listed in each weapon’s entry.</p>\n<p><strong>Misfires: </strong>If the natural result of a character’s attack roll falls within a firearm’s misfire value, that shot misses, even if the shot would have otherwise hit the target. Additionally, the shot threatens a chance at a misfire. To confirm whether or not the weapon misfires, the character makes another attack roll. If the natural result of the attack roll once again falls within the firearm’s misfire value, then the result is indeed a misfire. Otherwise, the weapon does not misfire - the attack simply misses. The ammunition expended on a misfire is lost.</p>\n<p><span style=\"white-space:pre\"> </span><em>Early Firearms:</em> If an early firearm misfires, it gains the broken condition. While it has the broken condition, it suffers the normal disadvantages that broken weapons do, and its misfire value increases by 4 unless the gun wielder has gun training in the particular type of firearm (see the Gunslinger class). In that case, the misfire value increases by only 2 instead of 4. If an early firearm with the broken condition misfires again, it explodes. When a non-magical firearm explodes, the weapon is destroyed. Magical firearms are wrecked, which means they can’t fire until they are fully restored (which requires either the make whole spell or the Gunsmithing feat). When a gun explodes, pick a corner of the square it occupies - the explosion creates a burst from that point of origin. Each firearm has a burst size noted in parentheses after its misfire value. Any creature within this burst (including the firearm’s wielder) takes damage as if it had been hit by the weapon - a DC 12 Reflex save halves this damage. This DC increases by +2 if the weapon is of masterwork quality, and by an additional +2 per magical enhancement bonus to attack and damage rolls of the weapon.</p>\n<p><span style=\"white-space:pre\"> </span><em>Advanced Firearms:</em> Advanced firearms can misfire, but when they do, they simply miss. Misfires do not bestow the broken condition on advanced firearms, and a further misfire does not cause advanced firearms to explode.</p>\n<p>One cannot misfire on a critical hit confirmation roll. If a character rolls a misfire when attempting to confirm a critical hit, it is treated as a normal result of the die (which may or may not confirm the critical hit).</p>\n<p><strong>Ammunition:</strong> Firearm ammunition takes two forms: either black powder and shot (either bullets or pellets) or cartridges. Unlike other types of ammunition, firearm ammunition is destroyed when it is used, and has no chance of being retrieved on a miss. No part of a cartridge can be reused to create new cartridges. Firearm ammunition cannot be treated with poison or oils, unless the character is using a pitted bullet.</p>\n<p><strong>Concealing Firearms:</strong> Like light weapons and hand crossbows, one-handed firearms are easy to conceal on one’s person. Some smaller firearms (like the coat pistol) can grant bonuses to conceal a weapon on one’s person.</p>\n<p><strong>Inappropriately Sized Firearms:</strong> A character cannot make optimum use of a firearm that is not properly sized for them. A cumulative -2 penalty applies on attack rolls for each size category of difference between the character’s size and the size of the firearm. If the character is not proficient with the firearm, a -4 non-proficiency penalty also applies. The size of a firearm never affects how many hands one needs to use to shoot it, the exception being siege firearms and Large or larger creatures. In most cases, a Large or larger creature can use a siege firearm as a two-handed firearm, but the creature takes a -2 penalty for using it this way because of its awkwardness.</p>\n<p><strong>Minimum Strength:</strong> Some firearms, such as the anti-materiel rifle and the big iron revolver, state in their entry that they have a minimum required Strength score. This means that the wielder must have a Strength score equal to or exceeding the listed number. If the user does not, they take a -8 penalty on the attack roll made with the weapon. Regardless of whether they succeed or fail, they drop the weapon immediately after the attack, as they are incapable of controlling the weapon’s intense recoil.</p>\n<p><strong>Bucklers:</strong> A character can use a one-handed or two-handed firearm without penalty with a buckler equipped.</p>\n<p><strong>Fire While Prone:</strong> Firearms, like crossbows, can be fired while their wielders are prone.</p>\n<p><strong>Firearms, Black Powder, and Water</strong>: Black powder becomes useless when exposed to water, but powder horns and cartridges protect black powder from exposure. A character cannot normally load or fire an early firearm underwater without magical aid. Advanced firearms can be fired underwater unless their entry states otherwise, but are subject to the usual penalties for attacking with a ranged weapon while underwater.</p>\n<p><strong>Deflecting and Snatching Bullets:</strong> The Deflect Arrows feat and the Snatch Arrows feat can be used to deflect bullets and slugs, but not pellets shot from a scatter weapon. Neither of these feats can be used to deflect siege firearm attacks.</p>\n<p><strong>Suppressing Fire:</strong> Occasionally, it is more advantageous to keep an enemy pinned down than to try and shoot them directly. For these situations, shooters may choose to lay down suppressing fire as a full-round action. One or more shooters can concentrate fire on an area the size of a sphere, with a radius of 5 feet per participating shooter. The furthest point in the area of suppressing fire must be within the first range increment of all participants’ weapons. Any enemy within this area must make a Will saving throw to resist being pinned down, with a DC equal to one-half the result of a ranged attack roll made by the suppressing shooter, rounded down. This attack roll can include racial bonuses, bonuses for a masterwork or magic weapon, or circumstance bonuses, but not bonuses from temporary magic spells (such as the true strike spell). Only one shooter makes the roll, regardless of how many shooters are participating, but each participating shooter may use a special aid another action to grant the primary shooter a +2 bonus on the roll.</p>\n<p>On a success, the enemy is unaffected and can continue acting normally. On a failure, the enemy is pinned down and forced to stay behind cover relative to the shooters, unless a greater immediate threat presents itself should they not move from behind cover. This imparts a -2 penalty on attack rolls, saving throws, skill checks, and ability checks. They may try to flee the area via the quickest route available to them if there is no cover available or if that is a shorter distance than the nearest suitable cover. Affected enemies within the area may attempt another Will saving throw as a move action at the start of their turn every round until they succeed or until the suppressing fire ends. Once a character has succeeded, they cannot be subject to that bout of suppressing fire again, but must save against future suppressing fire attempts, even if made by the same enemy during the same combat.</p>\n<h2>Firearm Descriptions</h2>\n<p>There are two general categories of firearms: early and advanced. Firearms are further divided into one-handed, two-handed, and siege firearms. As the category’s name implies, one-handed firearms need only one hand to wield and shoot. Two-handed firearms work best when using two hands while shooting them. Two-handed firearms can be shot with one hand at a -4 penalty on the attack roll. Siege weapons are typically mounted on some sort of platform, movable or otherwise, and have greater power but additional drawbacks.</p>\n<p><strong>Automatic Weapon Quality:</strong> A weapon with the automatic weapon quality is capable of firing multiple rounds with a single trigger pull. This grants the shooter extra attacks with the weapon - whenever making an attack with this weapon, the user may make one additional ranged attack, with all attacks that round suffering a -2 penalty to attack rolls.</p>\n<p>A shooter using an automatic weapon can lay down suppressing fire as a standard action without the assistance of other shooters. They may choose the size of the area to suppress, up to a maximum radius of 10 feet per point of their Dexterity bonus, minimum 10 feet. Additionally, they can choose to expend additional ammunition to increase the likelihood that the enemy remains pinned down - the Will saving throw DC to resist the effects of being pinned down increases by +1 for every round the shooter chooses to expend.</p>\n<p>Automatic weapons can also fire blindly and have a greater chance of hitting a protected or unseen target than precision weapons. If the wielder of an automatic weapon knows the location of an enemy within the weapon’s first range increment, but the wielder is subject to a miss chance against the target, the wielder may “spray and pray,” spending triple the amount of ammunition per shot attempted. This reduces the target’s miss chance by half. Even if the shooter hits, they are only considered to have hit once per shot, despite using triple the ammunition. Precision damage cannot be applied to successful attacks made during a spray and pray action. The wielder must have the available ammunition loaded into their weapon prior to making this choice - they cannot take a reload action in the middle of a “spray and pray” shot. If taken, a spray and pray attack must be applied to all firearm attacks taken in a turn.</p>\n<p><strong>Cut Weapon Quality:</strong> A weapon with the cut weapon quality can be modified to become a one-handed weapon by sawing off a significant portion of the barrel and stock. Doing so increases the misfire range by 2 and requires a Strength score of 13 to wield effectively. Attempting to use the weapon one-handed without the required Strength bestows a -4 penalty to attack rolls, increases the misfire range by an additional 2, and requires a DC 12 Strength check each time - failure means the user automatically misses on their attack and drops the weapon.</p>\n<p>Weapons with the cut weapon quality can be purchased in their typical two-handed form and cut down later, or purchased in their one-handed cut form at no additional cost. Once in their cut one-handed form, they cannot be restored to their two-handed form. </p>\n<p>Weapons with the cut weapon quality still require two hands to reload, unless their entry states otherwise.</p>\n<p><strong>Destructive Weapon Quality:</strong> A weapon with the destructive weapon quality is designed to wreak maximum destruction upon its target. Ranged weapons with the Destructive weapon quality do full damage against objects, and nullify an object’s immunity to critical hits. When rolling for damage, any die roll that naturally results in the maximum value for that die may be rolled again, with both results added to the total damage dealt for that attack. If that roll results in the maximum value for the die as well, it may be rolled again - this continues until no dice have come up on their maximum roll result.</p>\n<p><strong>Scatter Weapon Quality:</strong> A weapon with the scatter weapon quality can shoot two different types of ammunition. It can fire normal bullets that target one creature, or it can make a scattering shot, attacking all creatures within a cone. Cannons with the scatter weapon quality only fire grapeshot, unless their descriptions state otherwise.</p>\n<p>The range listed for a Scatter weapon determines its normal range increment distance when firing normal bullets. When making a scattering shot, the size of the cone area it affects is equal to half its range increment.</p>\n<p>When a scatter weapon attacks all creatures within the cone, it makes a single attack roll to determine whether the attack possibly misfires or scores a critical hit. If no misfire occurs, each creature within the cone must make a Reflex saving throw (DC 12 for one-handed firearms, DC 15 for two-handed firearms, DC 18 for siege firearms). This DC is increased by +2 if the weapon is of masterwork quality, and an additional +2 for each magical enhancement bonus to attack and damage rolls. With a success, they take half damage. Effects that grant concealment, such as fog or smoke, or the blur, invisibility, or mirror image spells, do not foil a scatter attack. To confirm a critical hit, the attack is made against the Armor Class of the creature in the cone with the highest Armor Class. On a confirmed critical hit, the weapon deals its critical hit damage to all creatures in the affected area subject to damage, instead of normal damage. If the natural result of the attack roll falls within the misfire value, the weapon suffers a misfire as normal. If a scatter weapon explodes on a misfire, it deals triple its damage to all creatures within the misfire radius.</p>\n<p>When a scatter weapon uses a scattering shot attack on a single target within 5 feet, it can forfeit the cone area attack to instead be treated as if it has the Destructive quality when rolling damage against that target.</p>\n<p>Weapons with the scatter quality are not able to apply precision damage to their targets when making a scattering shot.</p>\n<p><strong>Early Firearms: </strong>Early firearms are typically matchlock, wheellock, or flintlock weapons, and require more finesse and care to use than advanced firearms. Early firearms are muzzle-loaded, requiring a bullet and powder (or other special alchemical substances) to be shoved down the barrel before the weapon is fired. Early firearm ammunition can be loaded from a cartridge, but that cartridge is made of soft material (like paper or cloth) that is torn open so that the contents may be shoved down the barrel. Unlike advanced firearm cartridges, these cartridges do not protect the black powder inside from being exposed to water.</p>\n<p><strong>Advanced Firearms:</strong> Advanced firearms are more reliable and accurate than early firearms. The ammunition of an advanced firearm takes the form of metal (usually brass) cartridges that are loaded into a chamber rather than shoved down the barrel.</p>\n<h2>Siege Firearms</h2>\n<p>Siege engine firearms are large firearm weapons, temporary structures, or pieces of equipment used for damaging structures, vehicles, or large numbers of infantry at once.</p>\n<p>All siege firearms are at least size Large devices and often much larger. Unless stated otherwise in an individual siege firearm’s description, all siege firearms use the following rules.</p>\n<p><strong>Proficiency:</strong> Firearms which count as siege weapons require their own special proficiency. In addition to being proficient with the type of technology in which that firearm is classified (early or advanced), the user must also have the Exotic Weapon Proficiency (siege engines) feat in order to be considered proficient. So, for example, a character with proficiency in all martial weapons (such as a fighter) and the Exotic Weapon Proficiency (siege engines) feat is considered proficient with all early siege firearms. However, only a character that has both the Exotic Weapon Proficiency (advanced firearms) and Exotic Weapon Proficiency (siege engines) feats can be considered proficient with advanced siege firearms. The penalties for nonproficiency do not stack for each lacking aspect of proficiency - if you are nonproficient, you are simply nonproficient, no matter how unqualified you are.</p>\n<p><strong>Crew:</strong> The sheer size and complexity of a siege firearm often necessitates a crew for its use. One person of that crew is the crew leader. Usually the crew leader targets or controls the firing of a siege firearm; sometimes the crew leader does both. Often the crew leader is required to take actions and make specific checks in order for a siege firearm to function. The rest of the crew members are required to spend actions and make checks in order for a siege firearmto function.</p>\n<p>The number of members in a crew assumes Medium creatures. A siege firearm can be crewed by Small creatures, but it takes double the crew to do the same job. If Large or larger creatures serve as crew members, each Large creature counts as four crew members, a Huge creature counts as eight Medium creatures, a gargantuan creature counts as 16 Medium creatures, and a colossal creature counts as 20 Medium creatures.</p>\n<p><strong>Magical and Masterwork Siege Engines:</strong> Siege firearms can be masterwork, increasing their Craft DC by 5 and costing an additional 300 gp. A masterwork siege firearm can be enchanted at twice the cost for a normal magical weapon. The enhancement bonus of a siege firearm applies on attack rolls and targeting checks (in the case of indirect ranged siege firearms), and in the case of magical siege firearms, the enhancement bonus also applies on damage rolls.</p>\n<p><strong>Defense and Hit Points:</strong> All siege firearms are objects. A siege firearm has a Dexterity of 0 (–5 penalty) and a further penalty based on its size. Each type of siege firearmhas its own hardness and hit points.</p>\n<p><strong>Moving Siege Engines:</strong> Siege firearms have a speed. The speed of a siege firearm is the distance it can be moved if its full crew makes a move action to move it. Some siege firearms have a speed of 0. If this is the case, the siege firearm must be disassembled before movement is possible, or else mounted on a vehicle. Siege firearms that are atop or mounted on vehicles move with those vehicles.</p>\n<p><strong>Ranged Attacks:</strong> Unless otherwise mentioned in their description, siege firearms have the Destructive special quality.</p>\n<p><strong>Critical Hits:</strong> When a direct-fire siege firearm scores a critical hit, it confirms the critical hit and deals critical hit damage just like any other weapon. If an indirect-fire siege firearm rolls a natural 20 on its targeting check, it can also score a critical hit. The crew leader must reroll the targeting check to confirm the critical. If the confirmation targeting check is successful, the attack is a critical hit, and the siege firearm multiplies its damage by its critical multiplier.</p>\n<p><strong>Range:</strong> Any attack at more than the distance listed in a siege firearm’s entry is penalized for range. Beyond this range, the attack or targeting check takes a cumulative –2 penalty for each full range increment (or fraction thereof) of distance to the target. Some siege firearms have a minimum range for effectiveness. If that is the case, the minimum range will be listed in the siege firearm’s description.</p>\n<p><strong>Type:</strong> All siege firearms deal bludgeoning and piercing damage, unless otherwise specified in their descriptions.</p>\n<p><strong>Aim:</strong> This column gives the number of full-round actions (or move actions if the crew leader has the @Compendium[pf-content.pf-feats.WXjodyIsjwT90iDe]{Master Siege Engineer} feat) required to aim a siege firearm. If the siege firearm is being controlled by less than its normal crew complement, the number of actions it takes for the crew to aim the siege firearm is doubled. Additionally, this column will say whether a siege firearm is direct (D) or indirect (I) fire.</p>\n<p><strong>Large Wielders:</strong> Large and larger creatures can wield an appropriately-size siege firearm as a two-handed weapon. They are still required to take the necessary reload and aim actions to use the weapon properly.</p>\n<h2>Explosives</h2>\n<p>Instead of using gas expansion to launch a directed projectile, explosives use the sheer concussive force of ignited powder to cause tremendous damage to an area. Many of these explosives can be thrown at targets, and doing so is similar to throwing a splash weapon (such that splash weapon feats can be used with explosives unless otherwise specified). Like a thrown splash weapon, thrown explosives require no weapon proficiency. Explosives cannot deal precision-based damage. Unless otherwise specified, an explosive is destroyed after it has been detonated and cannot be recovered. Like a thrown splash weapon, explosives are not considered ammunition, but rather a (consumable) weapon in their own right.</p>\n<p>Misfires work slightly differently for explosives. Explosives all have a default misfire value of 1, and are always considered to have the broken condition for the purpose of determining the effects of a misfire. If an attack roll with an explosive threatens a misfire, but does not confirm it, the explosive fails to go off - it is simply a dud.</p>\n<p>All explosives are considered to have the Destructive weapon quality, unless otherwise noted in their description.</p>\n<p>Any explosives or pressurized canisters (such as hellbelcher tanks or a vehicle fuel tank) caught in the blast radius of an explosive also detonate, adding half their total damage dice rounded down as additional damage to the explosion each, and set off any explosives in their blast radius in a chain reaction. If those explosives are carried by another character, that character is subject to a DC 10 Reflex save to prevent their explosives from detonating. Additionally, any flammable material (vehicle fuel, unprotected black powder, etc) that takes fire damage may ignite or explode, potentially causing other explosives in their blast radius to explode as well.</p>\n<p> </p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"In2xLaPZGv8dRTFr":3},"flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.z0A41QYrn7u0kYCh"}}}
{"_id":"D2zl7PkUSmoJrSjm","name":"Vehicles - Modifications","content":"<p><strong>Source <a title=\"Modifications\" href=\"https://docs.google.com/document/d/1QUKzUh9_71pNYbKiJlhsUqVtXeFmbqT92wM2SmRqI44/edit?usp=sharing\">Modifications</a></strong></p>\n<p>Vehicle modification is nothing new. It's been around since the earliest days of the wheel. So, while personalizing a vehicle with upgrades and modifications can (and does) happen everywhere, scavengers and waste wanderers in Odium live and die by their vehicles. The choices they make about the conditions and build of their vehicles could mean the difference between coming home and becoming another lost soul claimed by the harsh, uncaring desert.</p>\n<h2>Modifications</h2>\n<p>A list of all possible modifications are available below. They are organized into three categories:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[tsl-content.tsl-rules.cvTJ1IK4BAfMIS5a]{Body Upgrades}</strong>, which upgrade aspects of a particular type or classification of vehicle</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[tsl-content.tsl-rules.gcrFxNyQBhz73nt8]{Component Upgrades}</strong>, which upgrade specific components on all vehicles</li>\n<li><strong>@Compendium[tsl-content.tsl-rules.XPgM9BpPuT9fraXU]{Universal Upgrades}</strong>, which upgrade any vehicle that meets the prerequisites</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Modifications have a number of attributes.</p>\n<p><em>Prerequisites</em>, the conditions that must be met in order for a vehicle to be considered compatible with a modification.</p>\n<p><em>Effect</em>, the combination of benefits and penalties the vehicle receives after installation is complete. This is expressed in the write-up for the modification, and does not appear in the table.</p>\n<p><em>Weight</em>, the weight added to the vehicle after the modification is installed.</p>\n<p><em>Install Difficulty</em>, the @Compendium[pf1.skills.L6LEhHRrn53cMuhE]{Craft} check DC to install the modification correctly.</p>\n<p><em>Install Time</em>, the amount of time it takes to install the modification correctly.</p>\n<p><em>Cost</em>, the price to purchase the parts to apply the modification. To have it installed by a technician, this cost is doubled.</p>\n<p>Each modification can be purchased only once, unless otherwise stated in its entry.</p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"In2xLaPZGv8dRTFr":3},"flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.43G5vdKoRSGW0B3u"}}}
{"name":"Vehicles - Chassis Descriptions","content":"<p><strong>Chassis:</strong> The base cost for a chassis is listed on the table Component Costs - Chassis. The cost for chassis that exceed a Brakes rating of 10 is, like the rest of the Brakes ratings, 50 gp per point of Brake. Chassis also have several different considerations: its <strong>Drive</strong>, whether the vehicle provides power to just one set of wheels or to all of them; its <strong>Locomotion</strong>, what it sits on that makes it move.</p>\n<p><strong>        Drive:</strong></p>\n<p>        <em>Front-Wheel/Rear Wheel Drive: </em>Vehicles with front-wheel or rear-wheel drive apply the power to only one set of wheels. This makes them cheaper and easier to manufacture than the all-wheel drive, making it the standard for the industry.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>        <em>All-Wheel Drive:</em> Vehicles with all-wheel drive apply power to all of the wheels equally, giving them better launching and off-roading capabilities. These are often seen on trucks that frequently find themselves off the beaten path, as well as on the top-of-the-line racing Autos. They are almost never seen on steamhorses, though some of the extremely advanced experimental models may implement them.</p>\n<p>        All-wheel drive vehicles enjoy a +50 bonus to Torque, and reduce the base modifiers for difficult terrain by half.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>        <strong>Locomotion:</strong></p>\n<p><em>        Wheels: </em>Do these need an explanation?</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>        <em>Rail:</em> Despite being easily the most limiting method of locomotion for vehicles, rail has stuck around for centuries because it is simply the best at what it does. Rail is ideal for transporting a tremendous amount of cargo over great distances, especially if the terrain is relatively flat. The only problem is that you’re limited in where you can go to where rail lines have already been built, unless of course you intend to construct some yourself.</p>\n<p>        Rail provides very little friction, so it takes longer to stop for rail vehicles than it does for any other vehicle type. Regardless of the vehicle’s Stopping stat, rail vehicles have a Stopping maximum of 1. However, rail vehicles reduce their felt Load to 1/10th of its actual effect, allowing them to carry far more cargo than they typically could.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>        <em>Pedrail: </em>Perhaps the strangest method of locomotion once is likely to see, pedrail served as the precursor to the far superior tracked vehicle. They consist of wheels with a series of feet connected to pivots, which allowed the feet to pivot and always stay flat against the surface they were climbing. This makes them excellent choices for inexpensive climbing solutions over difficult terrain and slopes of loose earth.</p>\n<p>        Vehicles outfitted with pedrail wheels reduce the base modifiers for difficult terrain by half, but their Top Speed has a permanent maximum of 1. They can always turn on their own axis.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>        <em>Prop:</em> The locomotion of choice (and, in fact, the only choice) for aerial vehicles, propeller-driven vehicles put their engines to work spinning a number of propellers or cyclorotors instead of wheels. This pushes air towards the back of the vehicle and propels it forward. For aerial vehicles, this air moves across the wings to create zones of differing air pressure and provide lift. For ground vehicles, they simply offer a way to provide thrust without having to deal with the mechanical challenge of putting the engine’s power to the wheels.</p>\n<p>        Vehicles outfitted with props can interact with the rules for headwinds, tailwinds, and crosswinds in the Vehicles on Difficult Terrain section above, though Ground vehicles don’t have to worry about stalling out. Aerial vehicles must use props, else they cannot maneuver in the air (and in most cases, can’t even become airborne in the first place). Props are also very loud compared to other forms of locomotion, granting anyone making a Perception check to hear them a +10 circumstance bonus to the check.</p>\n<p>        Incidentally, all aquatic vehicles are also propeller-driven, but aquatic vehicles don’t interact with the chassis component in the same way that aerial or ground vehicles do, and have their own propulsion and braking rules.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>        <em>Tracks:</em> Made famous by the great war machines overseas, tracked vehicles can go just about anywhere. Instead of wheels, their engines turn a large drive sprocket that moves a large metal linked track that typically runs the length of its body on either side. These tracks provide a tremendous amount of traction, giving them sufficient grip no matter the terrain.</p>\n<p>        In order to run on tracks, a vehicle must have an All-Wheel Drive Chassis. Vehicles outfitted with tracks ignore all difficult terrain modifiers, but their Top Speed is permanently halved. However, they can move up to their Top Speed in reverse. Vehicles outfitted with tracks can always make zero-axis pivot turns.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>        <em>Screw:</em> These crazy contraptions are one of the rarer methods of locomotion, but they’re growing in popularity due to their utility. Rather than wheels or tracks, screw vehicles employ two massive pontoons that run the length of their body on either side. These pontoons have a wedge that spirals up the pontoons, like an enormous screw. These pontoons allow them to travel in ways that no other vehicle can.</p>\n<p>        In order to run on screws, a vehicle must have an All-Wheel Drive Chassis. Vehicles outfitted with screws ignore all difficult terrain modifiers, but their Top Speed has a permanent maximum of 1. However, they can move up to their Top Speed in reverse, as well as laterally from side to side. Additionally, their pontoons allow them to float, making them amphibious vehicles that can move with equal adeptness on both land and sea.</p>","folder":null