n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:33.6887%\"><strong>Type</strong></td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:15.565%\"><strong>Modifier</strong></td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:32.8358%\"><strong>Type</strong></td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:17.9104%\"><strong>Modifier</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:33.6887%\">Steam</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:15.565%\">-10%</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:32.8358%\">Manual</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:17.9104%\">--</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:33.6887%\">Guzzolene</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:15.565%\">--</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:32.8358%\">Sequential</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:17.9104%\">+50%</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:33.6887%\">Deezul</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:15.565%\">+5%</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:32.8358%\">Horlogian</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:17.9104%\">+100%</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:33.6887%\">Arcanomotor</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:15.565%\">+50%</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:32.8358%\" rowspan=\"2\">Spectrum</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:17.9104%\" rowspan=\"2\">See entry</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:33.6887%\">Crystal Engine</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:15.565%\">+50%</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:33.6887%\">Elemental</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:15.565%\">+75%*</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:32.8358%\" rowspan=\"2\">Torque Converter</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:17.9104%\" rowspan=\"2\">See entry</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:33.6887%\">Tourbillon</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:15.565%\">+150%</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:49.2537%\" colspan=\"2\"><strong>Suspension</strong></td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:50.7463%\" colspan=\"2\"><strong>Chassis</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:33.6887%\"><strong>Type</strong></td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:15.565%\"><strong>Modifier</strong></td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:32.8358%\"><strong>Drive</strong></td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:17.9104%\"><strong>Modifier</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:33.6887%\">Mechanical</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:15.565%\">--</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:32.8358%\">Front-/Rear-Wheel Drive</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:17.9104%\">--</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:33.6887%\">Hydraulic</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:15.565%\">+20%</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:32.8358%\">All-Wheel Drive</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:17.9104%\">+50%</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:33.6887%\">Pneumatic</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:15.565%\">+50%</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:32.8358%\"><strong>Locomotion</strong></td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:17.9104%\"><strong>Modifier</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:33.6887%\">Esoteric</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:15.565%\">+100%</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:32.8358%\">Rail</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:17.9104%\">-25%</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:33.6887%\"><strong>Dependency</strong></td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:15.565%\"><strong>Modifier</strong></td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:32.8358%\">Wheels</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:17.9104%\">--</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:33.6887%\">Fully Dependent</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:15.565%\">--</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:32.8358%\">Pedrail</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:17.9104%\">+25%</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:33.6887%\">Mixed Dependency</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:15.565%\">+50%</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:32.8358%\">Prop</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:17.9104%\">+35%</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:33.6887%\" rowspan=\"2\">Fully Independent</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:15.565%\" rowspan=\"2\">+100%</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:32.8358%\">Tracks</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:17.9104%\">+40%</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:32.8358%\">Screw</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:17.9104%\">+100%</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<blockquote>\n<p>* Elemental engines also require an elemental creature to bind to the engine, which has its own costs to acquire that are not included in this calculation. The buyer can choose to outsource such a task to another party, purchase one at market, or provide the elemental themselves.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<h3><strong>Buying an Assembled Vehicle</strong></h3>\n<p>For those unable to build a vehicle themselves using scavenged or purchased parts, the option may be available to purchase a fully assembled vehicle instead. In this case, the collective value of the vehicle components are treated as the raw materials. Thus, an assembled vehicle is always twice the collective value of the chosen components.</p>\n<p>This is true of any sort of labor being performed on a vehicle, as well. When paying for a black thumb to install a modification or swap out a component on a vehicle, its cost is always twice the value of that modification or component. If the purchaser provides the modification parts or components themselves, the labor value for the install is equal to the market value of that modification part or component.</p>\n<h3><strong>Modifications</strong></h3>\n<p>One of the many advantages of motorized vehicles over the living mounts of the past is their high degree of customizability. Just about every vehicle available has a huge list of possible modifications, add-ons, upgrades, and other alterations available to fine-tune it for the exact sort of work its pilot needs it to do. Because the list of available options is so exhaustive, it has its own dedicated page: @Compendium[tsl-content.tsl-rules.D2zl7PkUSmoJrSjm]{Vehicles - Modifications}.</p>\n<h3><strong>Fuel</strong></h3>\n<p>Odium is a hostile world where vehicles act as the lifeline for the struggling people trapped within. With these vehicles acting as the most important thing in the lives of those who depend on them...what, then, is more important? Their fuel, of course.</p>\n<p>With only a small handful of exceptions, all engines require fuel to operate properly. The costs for these fuels fluctuate constantly with dozens of factors playing into what determines their price. While perhaps not representing the prices of fuel at all times, the table below gives a good baseline for the Game Master to reference as the price for a fuel when supply and forecasts for availability are at their most ideal.</p>\n<table style=\"width:31.5186%\" border=\"1\">\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:100%\" colspan=\"2\">Fuel Costs</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:44.7633%\">Fuel Type</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:55.2367%\">Cost per Unit</td>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:44.7633%\">Water</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:55.2367%\">1 cp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:44.7633%\">Deezil</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:55.2367%\">4 cp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:44.7633%\">Guzzolene</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:55.2367%\">6 cp</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>Each fuel has different properties, significance, and methods of handling. These are detailed below. One thing that is common across all fuel types, however, is that they are not potable - at the very least, they can make the imbiber sick, and in the worst cases, they act as deadly ingested poisons. It is best to treat all forms of fuel with extreme caution in every situation.</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Due to the toxic nature of some fuels, players may find themselves tempted to use fuels as a form of poison. While not impossible, these fuels require a good bit more than most poisons to be effective (an entire mouthful or more, compared to the few drops of other poisons), and most thinking creatures with any sense of self-preservation will immediately spit out the fuel due to its powerful, distinct flavor and tendency to burn soft tissues. Game Masters should be wary of allowing players to trick their foes into drinking sufficient quantities of these fuels without a tremendous amount of planning and effort. </p>\n</blockquote>\n<p> </p>\n<p><em>        Water:</em> Not all water can be suitable for drinking, and Bastion is not the type of city to waste anything if they can help it. Excess moisture from industrial applications gets boiled off, then recondensed to make water for situations that don't require potability, like washing down mud and silt in the mines, or as fuel for steam engines. Because it isn’t potable, it isn’t worth nearly as much as the stuff that’s safe to drink, making it the most cost-effective fuel source.</p>\n<p>        If consumed, the imbiber must make a DC 12 Fortitude save. Failure means they are nauseated for a 1 minute per point of failure, and that they have contracted <a title=\"Filth Fever\" href=\"https://www.d20pfsrd.com/gamemastering/afflictions/diseases/diseases-paizo-inc/filth-fever/\">filth fever</a>. Characters are also subject to this saving throw if they get a suitable amount of fuel water in an open wound. This has been known to occur if a denizen of the Steamgrates happens to get a thorough dousing from a busted industrial pipe above or spends too much time in the downpour of the leaky pipes from the layers above. In these cases, it is referred to colloquially as “drizzle sickness.”</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>        <em>Deezil: </em>This energy-dense fuel is brewed in enormous vats in Industria (unfortunate, for those that happen to live in the Steamgrates layer above them). Deezil is the by-product of huge churning vats that ends up as the final destination for all solid sewage in Bastion, as well as the city’s dead. The result is a stable, energy-dense fuel used for generators, machinery, and vehicles running deezil engines. Deezil is not considered to be very toxic, especially when compared to guzzolene, but still presents a serious danger if handled improperly.</p>\n<p>        If consumed, the imbiber must make a DC 14 Fortitude save. Failure means they are nauseated for 2 minutes per point of failure, and that they suffer the effects of deezil fuel as an ingested poison. Its onset is 10 minutes, has a frequency of once per minute for 5 minutes, is cured after 2 consecutive saves, and deals 1d3 Constitution damage. The fuel can also be vomited at any point prior to taking the initial damage, which immediately stops the victim from taking additional damage.</p>\n<p>        The fumes for deezil fuel can also pose a threat. If a character inhales the fumes directly, or spends too much time in an unventilated space with an open container of deezil, they must make a DC 14 Fortitude save. Failure means they suffer the effects of deezil fuel as an inhaled poison. Its onset is 1 minute, has a frequency of once per minute until the victim has left the area and can once again breathe clean air, and deals 1d3 points of Constitution and Intelligence damage as well as applying a @Compendium[pf1.spells.n0bsyxchnigkkuqo]{Confusion} effect as per the spell.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>        <em>Guzzolene: </em>Whereas deezil is a stable fuel made from recycled waste, guzzolene is a volatile, toxic, flammable, all-around dangerous fuel made by applying a series of alchemical processes to oils pulled from the earth beneath Bastion. Some compare its handling and use to dealing with liquid fire. Despite how dangerous it is, the high-octane fuel is highly sought after for its powerful effects on engines strong enough to handle it.</p>\n<p>        If consumed, the imbiber must make a DC 18 Fortitude save. Failure means they are nauseated for 5 minutes per point of failure, and that they suffer the effects of guzzolene as an ingested poison. Its onset is 10 minutes, has a frequency of once per minute for 5 minutes, is cured after 3 consecutive saves, and deals 1d6 Constitution damage. The fuel can also be vomited at any point prior to taking the initial damage, which immediately stops the victim from taking additional damage.</p>\n<p>        The fumes for guzzolene can also pose a threat. If a character inhales the fumes directly, or spends too much time in an unventilated space with an open container of guzzolene, they must make a DC 18 Fortitude save. Failure means they suffer the effects of guzzolene as an inhaled poison. Its onset is 1 minute, has a frequency of once per minute until the victim has left the area and can once again breathe clean air, and deals 1d3 points of Constitution damage and 1d3 points of Intelligence drain as well as applying a @Compendium[pf1.spells.n0bsyxchnigkkuqo]{Confusion} effect as per the spell.</p>\n<p>        Guzzolene is also a volatile explosive compound, and can cause a tremendous amount of damage if improper handling leads to a sufficient amount catching fire. Guzzolene kept in sealed containers explodes for 1d10 fire and force damage, and affecting an area with a 5-ft radius spread, per 5 units. The explosion leaves behind a fire in that entire area, catching creatures and flammable materials on fire within it and setting creatures and flammable materials on fire upon entering it (unless they succeed on a DC 15 Reflex saving throw). Anything that has been set on fire takes 1d6 points of fire damage immediately, and again each round they fail their Reflex save until they finally succeed on the save and put themselves out. The fire burns itself out in about a minute.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>        <em>Void: </em>This mysterious material at the heart of the enigmatic void engine is said to be a material so anathema to the natural world that it reacts with the very air itself. While a fuel unto itself, in many ways it behaves quite differently. It is unavailable for purchase anywhere, but that hasn’t proved to be a problem for owners of the few known void engines, as they are so efficient with their fuel that no one has ever so much as claimed to have seen one run out.</p>\n<p>        Because it is contained with numerous redundant safety measures inside the engine itself, the nature of the fuel is unclear. It is assumed to be a toxic compound, but if any have ever been exposed to it, they haven’t survived. Because of its reaction with material outside the engine itself, exposure would likely result in a catastrophic explosion before having to concern oneself with toxicity.</p>\n<p>        Void engines that detonate as a result of an attack against them explode for 1d12 points of force damage per unit of fuel the vehicle stores, in a radius around the vehicle equal to 10 feet per unit of fuel. This becomes the radius for an area of severe radiation centered on the vehicle.</p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"In2xLaPZGv8dRTFr":3},"flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.Cq1yfTY5vefxa4lo"}}}
{"name":"Vehicles - Parasite Vehicles","content":"<p><strong>Source <a title=\"Hardpoints\" href=\"https://docs.google.com/document/d/1EPdMWRFoQcH9SgBecKxU4q6k523FThdzcZ7BVcg9mrM/edit?usp=sharing\">Hardpoints</a></strong></p>\n<p>Scavengers guilds that are well funded will often seek out new ways to provide their vehicles with additional utility and defense. Lately, this has meant introducing parasite vehicles, quasi-vehicles that provide functionality to another vehicle as a @Compendium[tsl-content.tsl-rules.LdfNkCeMnbYzUwaX]{Hardpoint} modification.</p>\n<p>Parasite vehicles are a broad and diverse category, but typically, they:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Cannot move under their own power</li>\n<li>Require pilots of their own (called \"operators\")</li>\n<li>Do not have Components of their own</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Despite being vehicles-within-vehicles, parasite vehicles are in many ways vehicles in their own right - they have a <strong>Size</strong>, <strong>Classification</strong>, <strong>Weight</strong>, and <strong>Cost </strong>just as normal vehicles do. They have parts that provide power for their functionality and can be disabled through hit point damage, provided by Armor according to their Classification. They replace the idea of crew capacity with their <strong>Operator</strong>, who activates the vehicle’s abilities and makes skill checks and saving throws on its behalf just as a pilot does.</p>\n<p>They can accept any vehicle modifications for which they can qualify - usually, those that do not require a particular Body style, Component, or mobility type. Being vehicles, they can also support Hardpoint mounts just as any other vehicle. If these Hardpoints are mounted with a siege weapon, the parasite vehicle’s operator is able to take up the firing position and combine the firing action with operation of the parasite vehicle.</p>\n<p>Because parasite vehicles do not have Components, they are incapable of using abilities or taking actions that require a Push to succeed, and are in turn immune to effects that are resisted by a Push.</p>\n<p>Because parasite vehicles are powered in part by their host vehicle, they do not have an Hours of Operation restriction, and do not deplete the Hours of Operation for their host vehicle. They can operate while their host vehicle is powered down, but are considered to be disabled and unusable whenever their host vehicle is.</p>\n<table border=\"1\">\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\" colspan=\"6\">Parasite Vehicles</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Vehicle</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Size</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Class</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Operators</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Weight</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Cost</td>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Ball turret</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Large</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Steamhorse</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">1</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">800 lbs.</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">850 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Excavator</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Huge</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Heavy</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">1</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">35,000 lbs.</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">2,200 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Rotating turret</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Huge</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Auto</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">1+2</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">5,000 lbs.</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">1,250 gp</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p><strong>Ball Turret:</strong> These small, cramped altazimuth-mount turrets are shaped like spheres, with the operator having to climb inside for operation. It is typically used as a gun turret for Aerial Heavies, and as a result, is uniquely designed to mount two Large siege weapons on its Large-sized Hardpoint that the operator can fire simultaneously. It can only do this if both Hardpoints hold a Large siege weapon - mounting any other Hardpoint modification on it means only being able to hold a single Large Hardpoint.</p>\n<p>The ball turret can be fully rotated along both axes in a single round, allowing it to rotate into position for any action the operator wants it to perform within the same round that it performs the desired action.</p>\n<p><strong>Excavator:</strong> This piece of heavy construction equipment is little more than a powered digger, wielding a 20-foot-long boom arm with a bucket already mounted on its available Hardpoint. Some scavengers will remove the excavator unit from its crawler chassis and mount it on a Heavy so they can use the boom arm on their rigs. With an excavator mounted on a Hardpoint, it can be used to help load and unload cargo, to allow vehicle crew to board another vehicle, or even right the vehicle if it capsizes.</p>\n<p>The arm itself confers three special attacks: a @Compendium[tsl-content.tsl-weapons.91aGsaLZRuGZoV6Z]{Batter}, performed by using the side of the bucket to bludgeon its target; a @Compendium[tsl-content.tsl-weapons.9m7Be4nCZKFfDWKI]{Scrape}, using the prongs of the bucket to pierce and tear its target; and a @Compendium[tsl-content.tsl-weapons.qnvTln04ozx0nEQs]{Spin}, where the excavator is rotated with the arm fully extended. The batter and scrape attacks deal 5d6 points of damage (bludgeoning for the batter attack, piercing and slashing for the scrape) with the Destructive weapon quality, and can be made against any target within 20 feet. The spin attack acts as a bull rush attack with a CMB of +15 against every creature or unattended object within 30 feet, pushing them in the direction of the spin.</p>\n<p>The excavator can make one full rotation in a single round, allowing it to rotate into position for any action the operator wants it to perform within the same round that it performs the desired action. Performing any action with the excavator requires the operator to make a full-round action.</p>\n<p><strong>Rotating Turret:</strong> These large assemblies are up-armored (base Armor of 30) housings for crew and armament, with their own engines and drive mechanism to spin the heavy turret. They are mostly seen on the latest tank designs, and typically mount a siege firearm of some sort, though they have their own Huge Hardpoint and are capable of mounting any compatible Hardpoint modification the owner wishes.</p>\n<p>The rotating turret can make one full rotation in a single round, allowing it to rotate into position for any action the operator wants it to perform within the same round that it performs the desired action. It can be operated by a single Operator, but can house up to 3 - usually the operator doubling as a gunner, a loader or other crew for the mounted siege firearm, and a radio operator or commander in typical tank crews.</p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"In2xLaPZGv8dRTFr":3},"flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.NRLpjer3sx9IRjMj"}},"_id":"LK2rVtw5v1qn3MHh"}
{"_id":"LdfNkCeMnbYzUwaX","name":"Vehicles - Hardpoints","content":"<p><strong>Source <a title=\"Hardpoints\" href=\"https://docs.google.com/document/d/1EPdMWRFoQcH9SgBecKxU4q6k523FThdzcZ7BVcg9mrM/edit?usp=sharing\">Hardpoints</a></strong></p>\n<p>While a lot of vehicle modifications address existing elements of the vehicle such as its Components (see the @Compendium[tsl-content.tsl-rules.D2zl7PkUSmoJrSjm]{Modifications} rules for more info), some modifications add new features or even smaller vehicle-type platforms to the vehicle. These special modifications, called Hardpoint Modifications, are truly what make Odian black thumbs the most creative in the world - they allow the enterprising machinist to achieve a vehicle’s greatest potential for customizability and modularity.</p>\n<h2>What are Hardpoints?</h2>\n<p>Every vehicle has a capacity for making dramatic modifications to its Body and overall form to eke out brand new possibilities for utility. These<strong> Hardpoints</strong> represent the vehicle’s ability to support a considerable change to its shape and structure. The modifications themselves come in all shapes and sizes, so one could imagine that some are too large for a smaller vehicle to reliably support and still function properly. Hardpoint modifications themselves all have a <strong>Size</strong> attribute, which is meant to act as a representation of their physical bulk. These reflect the size categories that are already established for creature and vehicle sizes.</p>\n<h2>Bigger is Better</h2>\n<p>Unless otherwise specified, a vehicle has exactly one Hardpoint equal to its size. This means that any vehicle can mount exactly one Hardpoint modification of the same size as the vehicle itself. Attempting to mount any Hardpoint modification of a larger size category will simply fail - the vehicle does not have the infrastructure required to support this modification.</p>\n<p>If that were where it ended, Hardpoints would not be a very flexible system. In order to support additional options for mounting Hardpoint modifications to a vehicle’s available Hardpoints, any Hardpoint can be split into a pair of Hardpoints one size category lower.</p>\n<p>Say for example that a black thumb has a Gargantuan vehicle, with exactly one Gargantuan Hardpoint. They could mount a Gargantuan Hardpoint modification, and that would be it - their vehicle is supporting all they can by way of Hardpoint modifications. Alternatively, they could instead split that mount into two Huge-sized Hardpoint modifications. They could then mount a Huge Hardpoint modification in one Hardpoint, then split the second into two Large-sized Hardpoints, then maybe split each of those into two Medium-sized Hardpoint modifications, and so on.</p>\n<h2>Flex Mounting</h2>\n<p>To express the greatest amount of flexibility possible, the Hardpoints system does not have an opinion on the locations of mounts. The Game Master and Players are encouraged to consider what makes the most sense for where and how a Hardpoint modification is mounted. The Game Master and Players are also encouraged to consider the Rule of Cool when making these choices.</p>\n<h2>Hardpoint Modifications</h2>\n<p>A list of available Hardpoint modifications are available below. They have a number of attributes:</p>\n<p><em>Size</em>, the size category for the Hardpoint modification.</p>\n<p><em>Effect</em>, the combination of benefits and penalties the vehicle receives after installation is complete. This is expressed in the write-up for the modification, and does not appear in the table.</p>\n<p><em>Weight</em>, the weight added to the vehicle after the Hardpoint modification is installed.</p>\n<p><em>Install Difficulty</em>, the Craft DC to install the Hardpoint modification correctly.</p>\n<p><em>Install Time</em>, the amount of time it takes to install the Hardpoint modification correctly.</p>\n<p><em>Cost</em>, the price to purchase the parts to apply the Hardpoint modification. To have it installed by a technician, this cost is doubled.</p>\n<table style=\"width:100%;height:170px\" border=\"1\">\n<thead>\n<tr style=\"height:17px\">\n<td style=\"height:17px;width:100%;text-align:center\" colspan=\"6\">Hardpoint Modifications</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style=\"height:17px\">\n<td style=\"width:37.4462%;height:17px;text-align:center\">Hardpoint Modification</td>\n<td style=\"width:12.4821%;height:17px;text-align:center\">Size</td>\n<td style=\"width:12.4821%;height:17px;text-align:center\">Weight</td>\n<td style=\"width:12.4821%;height:17px;text-align:center\">Install DC</td>\n<td style=\"width:12.4821%;height:17px;text-align:center\">Install Time</td>\n<td style=\"width:12.6255%;height:17px;text-align:center\">Cost</td>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr style=\"height:17px\">\n<td style=\"width:37.4462%;height:17px;text-align:center\">Body spikes</td>\n<td style=\"width:12.4821%;height:17px;text-align:center\">Medium</td>\n<td style=\"width:12.4821%;height:17px;text-align:center\">+5%</td>\n<td style=\"width:12.4821%;height:17px;text-align:center\">10</td>\n<td style=\"width:12.4821%;height:17px;text-align:center\">See entry</td>\n<td style=\"width:12.6255%;height:17px;text-align:center\">See entry</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style=\"height:17px\">\n<td style=\"width:37.4462%;height:17px;text-align:center\">Chopsaw</td>\n<td style=\"width:12.4821%;height:17px;text-align:center\">Large</td>\n<td style=\"width:12.4821%;height:17px;text-align:center\">2,000 lbs.</td>\n<td style=\"width:12.4821%;height:17px;text-align:center\">25</td>\n<td style=\"width:12.4821%;height:17px;text-align:center\">3 days</td>\n<td style=\"width:12.6255%;height:17px;text-align:center\">500 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style=\"height:17px\">\n<td style=\"width:37.4462%;height:17px;text-align:center\">Drillpunch</td>\n<td style=\"width:12.4821%;height:17px;text-align:center\">Large</td>\n<td style=\"width:12.4821%;height:17px;text-align:center\">2,000 lbs.</td>\n<td style=\"width:12.4821%;height:17px;text-align:center\">25</td>\n<td style=\"width:12.4821%;height:17px;text-align:center\">1 day</td>\n<td style=\"width:12.6255%;height:17px;text-align:center\">500 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style=\"height:17px\">\n<td style=\"width:37.4462%;height:17px;text-align:center\">Hammer cannon</td>\n<td style=\"width:12.4821%;height:17px;text-align:center\">Large</td>\n<td style=\"width:12.4821%;height:17px;text-align:center\">2,000 lbs.</td>\n<td style=\"width:12.4821%;height:17px;text-align:center\">25</td>\n<td style=\"width:12.4821%;height:17px;text-align:center\">1 day</td>\n<td style=\"width:12.6255%;height:17px;text-align:center\">500 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style=\"height:17px\">\n<td style=\"width:37.4462%;height:17px;text-align:center\">Lancer's perch</td>\n<td style=\"width:12.4821%;height:17px;text-align:center\">Medium</td>\n<td style=\"width:12.4821%;height:17px;text-align:center\">150 lbs.</td>\n<td style=\"width:12.4821%;height:17px;text-align:center\">10</td>\n<td style=\"width:12.4821%;height:17px;text-align:center\">4 hours</td>\n<td style=\"width:12.6255%;height:17px;text-align:center\">25 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style=\"height:17px\">\n<td style=\"width:37.4462%;height:17px;text-align:center\">Lookout post</td>\n<td style=\"width:12.4821%;height:17px;text-align:center\">Huge</td>\n<td style=\"width:12.4821%;height:17px;text-align:center\">3,500 lbs.</td>\n<td style=\"width:12.4821%;height:17px;text-align:center\">12</td>\n<td style=\"width:12.4821%;height:17px;text-align:center\">2 days</td>\n<td style=\"width:12.6255%;height:17px;text-align:center\">See entry</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style=\"height:17px\">\n<td style=\"width:37.4462%;height:17px;text-align:center\">Oil slick</td>\n<td style=\"width:12.4821%;height:17px;text-align:center\">Small</td>\n<td style=\"width:12.4821%;height:17px;text-align:center\">100 lbs.</td>\n<td style=\"width:12.4821%;height:17px;text-align:center\">15</td>\n<td style=\"width:12.4821%;height:17px;text-align:center\">4 hours</td>\n<td style=\"width:12.6255%;height:17px;text-align:center\">75 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"width:37.4462%;text-align:center\">Plow</td>\n<td style=\"width:12.4821%;text-align:center\">See entry</td>\n<td style=\"width:12.4821%;text-align:center\">See entry</td>\n<td style=\"width:12.4821%;text-align:center\">18</td>\n<td style=\"width:12.4821%;text-align:center\">4 hours</td>\n<td style=\"width:12.6255%;text-align:center\">See entry</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"width:37.4462%;text-align:center\">Polecat mount</td>\n<td style=\"width:12.4821%;text-align:center\">Medium</td>\n<td style=\"width:12.4821%;text-align:center\">500 lbs.</td>\n<td style=\"width:12.4821%;text-align:center\">15</td>\n<td style=\"width:12.4821%;text-align:center\">2 hours</td>\n<td style=\"width:12.6255%;text-align:center\">125 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"width:37.4462%;text-align:center\">Siege weapon</td>\n<td style=\"width:12.4821%;text-align:center\">See entry</td>\n<td style=\"width:12.4821%;text-align:center\">See entry</td>\n<td style=\"width:12.4821%;text-align:center\">See entry</td>\n<td style=\"width:12.4821%;text-align:center\">See entry</td>\n<td style=\"width:12.6255%;text-align:center\">See entry</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"width:37.4462%;text-align:center\">Smoke screen</td>\n<td style=\"width:12.4821%;text-align:center\">Small</td>\n<td style=\"width:12.4821%;text-align:center\">50 lbs.</td>\n<td style=\"width:12.4821%;text-align:center\">12</td>\n<td style=\"width:12.4821%;text-align:center\">2 hours</td>\n<td style=\"width:12.6255%;text-align:center\">40 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"width:37.4462%;text-align:center\">Steamhorse boom</td>\n<td style=\"width:12.4821%;text-align:center\">Large</td>\n<td style=\"width:12.4821%;text-align:center\">350 lbs.</td>\n<td style=\"width:12.4821%;text-align:center\">22</td>\n<td style=\"width:12.4821%;text-align:center\">1 day</td>\n<td style=\"width:12.6255%;text-align:center\">250 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style=\"height:17px\">\n<td style=\"width:37.4462%;height:17px;text-align:center\">Wheel spikes</td>\n<td style=\"width:12.4821%;height:17px;text-align:center\">See entry</td>\n<td style=\"width:12.4821%;height:17px;text-align:center\">See entry</td>\n<td style=\"width:12.4821%;height:17px;text-align:center\">15*</td>\n<td style=\"width:12.4821%;height:17px;text-align:center\">30 minutes*</td>\n<td style=\"width:12.6255%;height:17px;text-align:center\">45 gp*</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p><strong>Body Spikes:</strong> A simple, effective deterrent for boarders is to weld sharp, rusty metal spikes onto a vehicle’s body. When first boarding a vehicle, creatures must succeed on a DC 15 Acrobatics check or take 2d6 points of piercing and slashing damage. Once aboard, creatures must reduce their speed by half or take that same damage again.</p>\n<p><strong>@Compendium[tsl-content.tsl-weapons.ThQvgzngnvwhbZcK]{Chopsaw}:</strong> This devastating power saw has taken more than its fair share of limbs and lives in the wastes of Odium. This brutal on-board weapon platform adds an attack for the vehicle’s Pilot or a member of the vehicle’s Crew to use.</p>\n<p>As a standard action, this weapon can attack everything in a 10-foot line, dealing 5d6 points of slashing damage and automatically dealing @Compendium[tsl-content.tsl-rules.VVxBr33G7C8Xp1w7]{Special Damage} to any creatures struck. The Chopsaw is considered a Large siege weapon, with its stats listed below. It has the Destructive weapon quality.</p>\n<p><strong>@Compendium[tsl-content.tsl-weapons.Q2wAOrAYWt5dCnvh]{Drillpunch}:</strong> A powerful drill attached to the end of a pneumatic piston sounds like exactly the sort of thing your rig is missing. This brutal on-board weapon platform adds an attack for the vehicle’s Pilot or a member of the vehicle’s Crew to use.</p>\n<p>As a standard action, this weapon can attack everything in a 10-foot line, dealing 5d6 points of piercing damage and forcing all unbuckled creatures and unattended objects on the target vehicle to save against being thrown from the vehicle. The Drillpunch is considered a Large siege weapon, with its stats listed below. It has the Destructive weapon quality.</p>\n<p><strong>@Compendium[tsl-content.tsl-weapons.oN4pGWywjacQ0Fii]{Hammer Cannon}:</strong> Nothing less than an enormous pneumatic hammer, this brutal on-board weapon platform adds an attack for the vehicle’s Pilot or a member of the vehicle’s Crew to use.</p>\n<p>As a standard action, this weapon can attack everything in a 10-foot line, dealing 5d6 points of bludgeoning damage and forcing all unbuckled creatures and unattended objects on the target vehicle to save against being thrown from the vehicle. The Hammer Cannon is considered a Large siege weapon, with its stats listed below. It has the Destructive weapon quality.</p>\n<table border=\"1\">\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Siege Weapon</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Damage</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Critical</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Range</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Size</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Crew</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Aim</td>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Chopsaw</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">5d6 slashing</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">x3</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">10 ft. line</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">L</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">1</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">0, D</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Drillpunch</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">5d6 piercing</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">x3</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">10 ft. line</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">L</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">1</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">0, D</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Hammer cannon</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">5d6 bludgeoning</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">x3</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">10 ft. line</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">L</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">1</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">0, D</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p><strong>Lancer's Perch:</strong> These platforms are typically mounted at the front or rear of a pursuit vehicle, and provide safe external stations for a single Medium “lancer” to strike other vehicles with thundersticks or melee weapons. Creatures standing on a lancer’s perch are considered to automatically succeed on any saving throw to avoid falling off of or being thrown from a vehicle. They often will include a rack to hold thundersticks, but can also be used in combination with a mounted siege firearm Hardpoint for a safe gun platform, or even as a precarious place to hold a small amount of tied-down cargo.</p>\n<p><strong>Lookout Post:</strong> These semi-armored platforms are often found mounted on a trailer Hardpoint to allow a vehicle’s crew to watch the horizon for coming threats. It serves much the same purpose as a lancer’s perch for larger vehicles (and grants the same benefits), except for the added benefit of providing some armored cover - base Armor 10 - and conferring its benefits to as many as four Medium creatures instead of just one.</p>\n<p><strong>Oil Slick:</strong> This pressurized canister, typically mounted under the rear bumper, holds slick oil that it can spray out  - done as part of a piloting action by the vehicle’s pilot - to coat the ground behind it. It creates a patch of oil equal to the size of the vehicle (not including trailers). This oil acts like the @Compendium[pf1.spells.ik9u3eel5vfwrtb5]{Grease} spell, and any vehicle that passes over it must succeed on a Push against its Chassis or lose control. It can hold 4 uses - 1 unit of oil each - before having to be refilled.</p>\n<p><strong>Plow:</strong> This enormous metal wedge allows a vehicle to push obstacles out of its way - no matter what they are. As part of a vehicle piloting action, a Pilot can choose to raise or drop a plow. When a plow is dropped while the vehicle is on loose soil, sand, or snow, it creates a cloud of the substance all around its front. This turns mundane difficult terrain to normal terrain for the benefit of it and any vehicles or creatures behind it, and puts out any fires on and creates an effect like the @Compendium[pf1.spells.g33euis7yi9pwddy]{Fog Cloud} spell over the entire front half of the vehicle.</p>\n<p>The plow also helps protect a vehicle during a front-on collision. When the vehicle strikes an obstacle at the front, roll 2d10 for a @Compendium[tsl-content.tsl-weapons.0bnvqXm5xKkm9cq5]{Plow (Auto)} and 5d10 for a @Compendium[tsl-content.tsl-weapons.eMXxo64HBannM8Im]{Plow (Heavy)}. The vehicle with the Plow reduces this amount from the damage it suffers from the collision, while the opposing vehicle suffers this amount as damage.</p>\n<p>An Auto plow is size Medium, weighs 850 pounds, and costs 150 gp. A Heavy plow is size Large, weighs 8,000 pounds, and costs 350 gp.</p>\n<p><strong>Polecat Mount:</strong> This well-known device is simply a large metal pole with a heavy counterbalance mounted on an A-frame. At the end of the pole, a crew member (called a “polecat”) can buckle themselves in to stay attached to the end of the pole. Once strapped in, another crew member at the base can shift the pole to either side along a single axis. With a 20-foot reach, the pole can be used to put the polecat in position to attack targets on other vehicles. From here, they can do whatever they wish - attack targets in range, grapple and drag targets off a platform or vehicle, or detached from the pole and board another vehicle. Buckling into a polecat mount is a swift action. Rotating it across its entire range of movement can be done as a move-equivalent action.</p>\n<p><strong>Siege Weapon:</strong> This mount will support a Siege Weapon or Siege Firearm of equivalent Size. It costs no more than the siege weapon being mounted, and weighs only what that siege firearm weighs. The Install DC is 12 for a Large siege weapon, +2 per increase in size category over Large. The Install Time is 1 day for a Large siege weapon, +1 day per increase in size category over Large.</p>\n<p><strong>Smoke Screen:</strong> These canisters hold and burn oil in order to create huge clouds of smoke behind them. As part of a piloting action, the vehicle’s pilot can activate the smoke screen, causing a massive gout of thick black smoke to erupt from behind the vehicle. This creates an identical effect to the @Compendium[pf1.spells.kjke96zd1j1jz48z]{Stinking Cloud} spell, forming a cloud as wide as the vehicle along its path of travel for 1 minute. It can hold 4 uses - 1 unit of oil each - before having to be refilled.</p>\n<p><strong>Steamhorse Boom:</strong> These specialized boom arms are designed to deploy steamhorses on a moment’s notice without stopping. The arms stick straight up when in a state of rest, holding a steamhorse on its side. The rider can climb atop such a mounted vehicle, then release the boom arm, as a move equivalent action. The arm then swings out and drops the steamhorse, allowing them to hit the ground in motion. This can be done without another crew member to assist, though to recover the steamhorse, there must be another crew member available to lift the boom after they have reattached the steamhorse to it (also a move-equivalent action).</p>\n<p><strong>Wheel Spikes:</strong> These gnarly hubcap extensions are designed to cause damage to any vehicle whose pilot is unwise enough to get too close. As part of a vehicle piloting action, the pilot of a vehicle modified with wheel spikes can attack everything occupying a square adjacent to each wheel so modified, using the result of a @Compendium[tsl-content.tsl-skills.VTrVwSSCPSkTWjAZ]{Pilot} check in place of an attack roll. The listed details on the tables are per-wheel.</p>\n<table border=\"1\">\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Class</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Size</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Damage</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Critical</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Range</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Weight</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Cost</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Special</td>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">@Compendium[tsl-content.tsl-weapons.ctAPQWlHFAmUxDWI]{Wheel Spikes (Auto)}</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Medium</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">2d6</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">x3</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">5 ft. line</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">15 lbs.*</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">25 gp*</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Destructive</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">@Compendium[tsl-content.tsl-weapons.MejymFDe5w918wkU]{Wheel Spikes (Heavy)}</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Large</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">5d6</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">x3</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">5 ft. line</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">40 lbs.*</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">50 gp*</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Destructive</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"In2xLaPZGv8dRTFr":3},"flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.h0YLBqiey34uTY5R"}}}
{"_id":"TJYmpUXMTlv00Wtu","name":"Fuel Additives","content":"<p><strong>Source </strong><a title=\"Fuel Additives\" href=\"https://docs.google.com/document/d/1rWs_xulHnhU5R-_3EezrOG3HSc8EaX-AT92KuhpTIGI/edit?usp=sharing\">Fuel Additives</a></p>\n<p>Being as important as they are to the life of various nations the world over, vehicles get a lot of attention from various industries. One such new development comes from the realm of alchemy, where vehicle-specific potions have entered the market. Now vehicles can benefit from short-notice esoteric effects without a caster in the same way that people can.</p>\n<p>A fuel additive is a magic liquid that produces its effects after mixing with the fuel and being drawn into the engine. Fuel additives are very similar to potions, and indeed can be thought of as potions for vehicles. A fuel additive can be used only once. It can duplicate the effect of some spells or psionic powers of up to 3rd level that have a casting time of less than 1 minute.</p>\n<p><strong>Fuel Additives as Loot</strong></p>\n<table style=\"font-family:var(--font-primary);font-size:var(--font-size-14)\" border=\"1\">\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Minor</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Medium</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Major</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Spell Level</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Caster Level</td>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">01-20</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">--</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">--</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">0</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">1st</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">21-60</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">01-20</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">--</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">1st</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">1st</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">61-100</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">21-60</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">01-20</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">2nd</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">3rd</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">--</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">61-100</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">21-100</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">3rd</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">5th</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p><strong>Fuel Additive Costs<br /></strong></p>\n<table border=\"1\">\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Spell Level</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Full Prepared</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Full Spontaneous</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">3/4 Esoterics</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Half</td>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">0</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">12 gp 5 sp</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">12 gp 5 sp</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">12 gp 5 sp</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">--</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">1st</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">25 gp</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">25 gp</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">25 gp</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">25 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">2nd</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">150 gp</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">200 gp</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">200 gp</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">200 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">3rd</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">375 gp</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">450 gp</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">525 gp</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">525 gp</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<h3><strong>Price of Fuel Additives</strong></h3>\n<p>The price of a fuel additive is equal to the level of the spell × the creator’s caster or manifester level × 25 gp. If the fuel additive has a material component cost, it is added to the base price and cost to create. Table: Fuel Additive Costs gives sample prices for fuel additives created at the lowest possible caster or manifesting level for each category of esoterics class. Note that some fuel additives appear at different levels for different esotericists. The level of such spells or powers depends on the brewer of the fuel additive.</p>\n<p>Fuel additives are like spells or powers affected upon a vehicle. The administrator of the fuel additive doesn’t get to make any decisions about the effect - the brewer of the fuel additive has already done so. The vehicle consuming the fuel additive is the effective target, but the effective caster is the vehicle’s pilot (though the fuel additive indicates the caster or manifester level, the pilot still controls the effect).</p>\n<p><strong>Physical Description:</strong> A typical fuel additive consists of 16 ounces of liquid held in a glass or tin container with a long pour-spout and fitted with a tight stopper or screw-on lid. The container is usually about 10 inches high and 2 inches wide, and weighs 1 pound. The container has Armor Class 13, 1 hit point, hardness 1, and a break DC of 12.</p>\n<p><strong>Activation:</strong> Applying a fuel additive to a vehicle is a two-part process. First, the fuel additive must be added to the fuel - poured into the vehicle’s fuel tank. Doing this is a standard action that provokes attacks of opportunity. The pilot can then choose to activate it at any point while the vehicle is in operation within the next hour, which takes another standard action from the pilot (which provokes an attack of opportunity). If the fuel additive is not used within an hour of being added to the fuel tank, it destabilizes and is wasted. Upon activation, the fuel additive takes effect immediately. The target of the effect is the vehicle itself, even if the spell or psionic power effect that the fuel additive is replicating would not ordinarily qualify it as a target.</p>\n<p><strong>Drinking Fuel Additives:</strong> Because they are intended to be added to vehicle fuel tanks, fuel additives are not formulated for consumption by creatures. Fuel additives are ingested poisons if consumed. The imbiber must make a DC 15 Fortitude saving throw. Failure means they are nauseated for 1 minute per point of failure, and that they suffer the effects of fuel additives as an ingested poison. Its onset is 10 minutes, has a frequency of once per minute per 5 minutes, is cured after 2 consecutive saves, and deals 1d4 Constitution damage. The fuel additive can also be vomited at any point prior to taking the initial damage, which immediately stops the victim from taking additional damage.</p>\n<p><strong>Fuel Additives</strong></p>\n<table style=\"width:698px;border-top:1px solid var(--color-border-light-tertiary);border-bottom:1px solid var(--color-border-light-tertiary);height:85px\" border=\"1\">\n<thead style=\"text-shadow:1px 1px var(--color-shadow-dark);border-bottom:1px solid var(--color-border-dark)\">\n<tr style=\"height:17px\">\n<td style=\"width:258.375px;height:17px;text-align:center\">0th-Level</td>\n<td style=\"width:86.1094px;height:17px;text-align:center\">Price</td>\n<td style=\"width:86.1094px;height:17px;text-align:center\">0th-Level</td>\n<td style=\"width:86.1094px;height:17px;text-align:center\">Price</td>\n<td style=\"width:86.1094px;height:17px;text-align:center\">0th-Level</td>\n<td style=\"width:86.1875px;height:17px;text-align:center\">Price</td>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr style=\"height:17px\">\n<td style=\"width:258.375px;height:17px;text-align:center\"><em>chameleon scales</em></td>\n<td style=\"width:86.1094px;height:17px;text-align:center\">12 gp 5 sp</td>\n<td style=\"width:86.1094px;height:17px;text-align:center\"><em>create water</em></td>\n<td style=\"width:86.1094px;height:17px;text-align:center\">12 gp 5 sp</td>\n<td style=\"width:86.1094px;height:17px;text-align:center\"><em>diagnostics</em></td>\n<td style=\"width:86.1875px;height:17px;text-align:center\">12 gp 5 sp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style=\"height:17px\">