ign:center\">525 gp</td>\n<td style=\"width:161.094px;height:17px;text-align:center\"><em>protection from energy</em></td>\n<td style=\"width:71.3281px;height:17px;text-align:center\">375 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style=\"height:17px\">\n<td style=\"width:165.375px;height:17px;text-align:center\"><em>remove curse</em></td>\n<td style=\"width:72.0625px;height:17px;text-align:center\">375 gp</td>\n<td style=\"width:141.094px;height:17px;text-align:center\"><em>sessile spirit</em></td>\n<td style=\"width:78.0469px;height:17px;text-align:center\">525 gp</td>\n<td style=\"width:161.094px;height:17px;text-align:center\"><em>shrink item</em></td>\n<td style=\"width:71.3281px;height:17px;text-align:center\">375 gp</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p><strong>Modifications:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><em>Ant Haul:</em> Reduces felt load to 1/3 for duration.</li>\n<li><em>Cheetah's Sprint:</em> Double vehicle's Speed (before other esoteric or alchemical effects) for 1 round.</li>\n<li><em>Create Water:</em> Can be used like <em>fill up</em> for engines that take water as fuel.</li>\n</ul>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"In2xLaPZGv8dRTFr":3},"flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.ZBXWpw7Xh3jyOIz6"}}}
{"_id":"UbpSzyiNU4U6Gs47","name":"Vehicles - Components","content":"<p>Vehicles are made of a number of parts, each of which have a number of statistics which define their operation and performance. While most parts are exclusive to a particular classification, some parts can actually be used on other classifications for interesting results.</p>\n<p>Each part will have its own statistics that define aspects of the vehicle’s final performance statistics, often in combination with one or more parts on the machine. The possibilities in combining parts to create specialized high-performance machines are nearly limitless - one may spend hours wrenching on their hog or stallion, tweaking the numbers until their prized rig is just right. Each vehicle classification has five major components, which will each have some statistics that are shared with other parts and some that are unique to that part. These five components are the Body, the Engine, the Transmission, the Chassis, and the Suspension.</p>\n<p>With the exception of the Body, all components will also have an<strong> Integrity.</strong> This describes the current reliability of that component, and how many more times it can break and be repaired before it can no longer be salvaged for anything other than scrap, and must be completely replaced.</p>\n<p><span style=\"white-space:pre\"> </span><em style=\"font-family:var(--font-primary);font-size:var(--font-size-14)\">        </em><em style=\"font-family:var(--font-primary);font-size:var(--font-size-14)\">Body:</em><span style=\"font-family:var(--font-primary);font-size:var(--font-size-14)\"> The body of the vehicle describes its general shape and structure, as well as its type. There are a large number of body styles and shapes, and a driver can modify these down to the panels themselves to get the shapes they want. The body will typically define the following:</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"white-space:pre\"> </span><em style=\"font-family:var(--font-primary);font-size:var(--font-size-14)\">        </em><em style=\"font-family:var(--font-primary);font-size:var(--font-size-14)\">        </em><strong style=\"font-family:var(--font-primary);font-size:var(--font-size-14)\">Style:</strong><span style=\"font-family:var(--font-primary);font-size:var(--font-size-14)\"> The body style gives the basic shape, door arrangement, and crew capacity on a vehicle. A list of the most common body styles can be found later in this chapter, though custom styles not already defined can also be found or made.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"white-space:pre\"> </span><em style=\"font-family:var(--font-primary);font-size:var(--font-size-14)\">        </em><em style=\"font-family:var(--font-primary);font-size:var(--font-size-14)\">        </em><strong style=\"font-family:var(--font-primary);font-size:var(--font-size-14)\">Armor Class:</strong><span style=\"font-family:var(--font-primary);font-size:var(--font-size-14)\"> Like most objects, vehicles have an armor class. This is not necessarily dependent on the vehicle’s Body, but is considered an aspect of the Body component regardless. A vehicle’s AC is equal to 10 + its Size modifier + its Reactivity. In the case of vehicles, the Reactivity is treated as the vehicle’s Dexterity score, and any situation in which it would be denied its Dexterity bonus to Armor Class will see it denied its Reactivity as well.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"white-space:pre\"> </span><em style=\"font-family:var(--font-primary);font-size:var(--font-size-14)\">        </em><em style=\"font-family:var(--font-primary);font-size:var(--font-size-14)\">        </em><strong style=\"font-family:var(--font-primary);font-size:var(--font-size-14)\">Armor: </strong><span style=\"font-family:var(--font-primary);font-size:var(--font-size-14)\">Some vehicle bodies are sturdier than others. This figure works in many ways like Hardness on other objects, and can be modified with armor upgrades or downgrades. Some body styles within a classification may have different base Armor values depending on their shape and what material was used to manufacture the Body.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"white-space:pre\"> </span><em style=\"font-family:var(--font-primary);font-size:var(--font-size-14)\">        </em><em style=\"font-family:var(--font-primary);font-size:var(--font-size-14)\">        </em><strong style=\"font-family:var(--font-primary);font-size:var(--font-size-14)\">Hit Points: </strong><span style=\"font-family:var(--font-primary);font-size:var(--font-size-14)\">All sorts of dangers in the wastes can cause damage to a vehicle’s body. Attacks to a vehicle are assumed to strike the Body, and do not damage a particular component. When the vehicle’s Hit Points have reached zero, it’s too beat up to drive, and has to receive some general repairs. See the Vehicle Rules section for more information on attacking and damaging a vehicle.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"white-space:pre\"><em style=\"font-family:var(--font-primary);font-size:var(--font-size-14)\">       </em></span><em style=\"font-family:var(--font-primary);font-size:var(--font-size-14)\">        </em><span style=\"white-space:pre\"> </span><strong style=\"font-family:var(--font-primary);font-size:var(--font-size-14)\">Weight: </strong><span style=\"font-family:var(--font-primary);font-size:var(--font-size-14)\">Each body comes with a base weight, given in pounds. This weight is usually meant to describe the vehicle’s fully-assembled operating weight, with a full tank of fuel, but no crew or cargo. It assumes an average weight for each required component, but some modifications may increase or decrease the weight based on which abnormal parts may be applied. Such weight modifications will be described in the part description.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"white-space:pre\"> </span><em style=\"font-family:var(--font-primary);font-size:var(--font-size-14)\">        </em><em style=\"font-family:var(--font-primary);font-size:var(--font-size-14)\">        </em><em style=\"font-family:var(--font-primary);font-size:var(--font-size-14)\">Unlike the other four base components, the Body does not have Integrity, as there is nothing to necessarily wear down; most damage to these components comes from combat.</em></p>\n<p><em> </em></p>\n<p><span style=\"white-space:pre\"> </span><em style=\"font-family:var(--font-primary);font-size:var(--font-size-14)\">        </em><em style=\"font-family:var(--font-primary);font-size:var(--font-size-14)\">Engine: </em><span style=\"font-family:var(--font-primary);font-size:var(--font-size-14)\">The Engine describes the power plant for the vehicle. Most engines in The Sundered Lands will operate by using expanding gas to drive pistons, either by rapidly converting water into steam or by igniting combustible materials. The vehicle engine is the most important component of a vehicle, providing all of the power needed to haul cargo or reach empyrean speeds. It will define the following:</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"white-space:pre\"> </span><em style=\"font-family:var(--font-primary);font-size:var(--font-size-14)\">        </em><em style=\"font-family:var(--font-primary);font-size:var(--font-size-14)\">        </em><strong style=\"font-family:var(--font-primary);font-size:var(--font-size-14)\">Type: </strong><span style=\"font-family:var(--font-primary);font-size:var(--font-size-14)\">This describes the method of operation of the engine. The overwhelming majority of engines in The Sundered Lands will be a steam engine, an internal combustion engine, or an arcanotech engine, though all manner of strange unique engines may exist in secret.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"white-space:pre\"> </span><em style=\"font-family:var(--font-primary);font-size:var(--font-size-14)\">        </em><em style=\"font-family:var(--font-primary);font-size:var(--font-size-14)\">        </em><strong style=\"font-family:var(--font-primary);font-size:var(--font-size-14)\">Horsepower (Ho): </strong><span style=\"font-family:var(--font-primary);font-size:var(--font-size-14)\">The power of engines is the all-important core of a vehicle that the entire Odian culture is built on. Whether a vehicle is meant to be light and fast, slow and strong, or somewhere in between, the engine must be as strong as is possible to achieve desired results. This stat will interact with the Transmission Power Transfer to determine the assembled vehicle’s Top Speed and Torque.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"white-space:pre\"><em style=\"font-family:var(--font-primary);font-size:var(--font-size-14)\">       </em></span><em style=\"font-family:var(--font-primary);font-size:var(--font-size-14)\">         </em><strong style=\"font-family:var(--font-primary);font-size:var(--font-size-14)\">Fuel: </strong><span style=\"font-family:var(--font-primary);font-size:var(--font-size-14)\">All engines run on something, and this defines what powers the engine. This could viably be nearly any sort of combustible material though, typically, gasses and fluids are far more common as a fuel than solid material. Common fuels might be water or steam, alcohol, alchemical compounds, or magical sources, though there is nearly no limit here and even more experimental sources of engine fuel may be found. This stat will define how many hours your vehicle will be able to operate before needing to refill the tank.</span></p>\n<blockquote style=\"border-left:3px solid var(--color-border-light-tertiary)\">\n<p>An easy way for Game Masters to think about or describe an Engine is to think of the Horsepower as the number of cylinders the Engine has, with odd numbers either representing a particularly powerful Engine with one fewer cylinder than the Horsepower, or a particularly weak or worn-out Engine with one more cylinder than the Horsepower. This may not be perfectly accurate to the real world, but serves as an excellent short hand for describing the look of an Engine to players.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p><span style=\"white-space:pre\"><br /></span><em>        </em><em>Transmission: </em>Even the most powerful engine is useless unless you have a way to apply its power. This is where the transmission comes in - it manipulates the power from the engine through increasing stepwise gear ratios to change the vehicle speed and torque. After the choice of engine, the transmission is the most important choice when building a vehicle. The choice of transmission will be influenced by whether you are building a massive tank of a War Rig or a lightning-quick stallion. It will define the following:</p>\n<p><span style=\"white-space:pre\"><em style=\"font-family:var(--font-primary);font-size:var(--font-size-14)\">       </em></span><em style=\"font-family:var(--font-primary);font-size:var(--font-size-14)\">        </em><span style=\"white-space:pre\"> </span><strong style=\"font-family:var(--font-primary);font-size:var(--font-size-14)\">Type: </strong><span style=\"font-family:var(--font-primary);font-size:var(--font-size-14)\">There are two main types of transmission. The most common by a huge margin is the manual transmission, where the driver must change the gear themselves at key moments using a lever that mechanically moves gears around directly. Distantly second is the automatic transmission, so named because the gears are changed automatically using a complex series of clockwork gears. Just as with other components, other rarer types of transmission may exist.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"white-space:pre\"><em style=\"font-family:var(--font-primary);font-size:var(--font-size-14)\">       </em></span><em style=\"font-family:var(--font-primary);font-size:var(--font-size-14)\">        </em><span style=\"white-space:pre\"> </span><strong style=\"font-family:var(--font-primary);font-size:var(--font-size-14)\">Power Transfer (Po):</strong><span style=\"font-family:var(--font-primary);font-size:var(--font-size-14)\"> Whatever you are looking for in a Power Transfer stat will determine whether you are going for speed or strength. A higher Power Transfer means the transmission is better able to get heavier loads moving, but less able to apply the engine’s power to the overall top speed. This stat will interact with the Engine Horsepower to determine the assembled vehicle’s Top Speed and Torque.</span></p>\n<p> </p>\n<p><span style=\"font-family:var(--font-primary);font-size:var(--font-size-14);white-space:pre\"> </span><em style=\"font-family:var(--font-primary);font-size:var(--font-size-14)\">        </em><em style=\"font-family:var(--font-primary);font-size:var(--font-size-14)\">Chassis: </em><span style=\"font-family:var(--font-primary);font-size:var(--font-size-14)\">More than just a single part, the Chassis is what all other components rest on to make a complete vehicle. It’s what supports the Body, cradles the Engine, and is connected to the wheels by way of the Suspension, along with all of the parts outside of the Engine and the Transmission that play a part in delivering the Engine’s power to the wheels. The combinations of options in a vehicle’s Chassis are nearly limitless, allowing for unparalleled customizability. This component is a big part of what makes a scavenger’s ride uniquely their own.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"white-space:pre\"> </span><em style=\"font-family:var(--font-primary);font-size:var(--font-size-14)\">        </em><em style=\"font-family:var(--font-primary);font-size:var(--font-size-14)\">        </em><strong style=\"font-family:var(--font-primary);font-size:var(--font-size-14)\">Type: </strong><span style=\"font-family:var(--font-primary);font-size:var(--font-size-14)\">The type of Chassis will define a number of characteristics about the vehicle, including but not limited to which wheels drive the vehicle (rear-wheel drive, all-wheel drive, etc.), how many wheels the vehicle has, and the type of locomotion system it uses (wheel, tracks, screw-propelled, etc.).</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"white-space:pre\"> </span><em style=\"font-family:var(--font-primary);font-size:var(--font-size-14)\">        </em><em style=\"font-family:var(--font-primary);font-size:var(--font-size-14)\">        </em><strong style=\"font-family:var(--font-primary);font-size:var(--font-size-14)\">Brakes (Br): </strong><span style=\"font-family:var(--font-primary);font-size:var(--font-size-14)\">Almost as important as a vehicle’s ability to move is its ability to stop, preferably as quickly and reliably as possible. The Brakes can sometimes be easy to overlook, but any halfway intelligent scavenger will ensure their black thumb is keeping their Brakes in peak condition - the fun of going fast quickly ends when you need to stop, and the brake pedal does nothing. This stat will interact with the vehicle’s Load to determine the assembled vehicle’s Stopping.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"white-space:pre\"> </span><em style=\"font-family:var(--font-primary);font-size:var(--font-size-14)\">        </em><em style=\"font-family:var(--font-primary);font-size:var(--font-size-14)\">        </em><em style=\"font-family:var(--font-primary);font-size:var(--font-size-14)\">        </em><span style=\"font-family:var(--font-primary);font-size:var(--font-size-14)\">It is important to note that Aquatic vehicles do not have a Chassis.</span></p>\n<p><br /><span style=\"white-space:pre\"> </span><em style=\"font-family:var(--font-primary);font-size:var(--font-size-14)\">        </em><em style=\"font-family:var(--font-primary);font-size:var(--font-size-14)\">Suspension: </em><span style=\"font-family:var(--font-primary);font-size:var(--font-size-14)\">The suspension system is what permits the wheels to move independently of the rest of the vehicle, allowing the wheels to react to inconsistencies in the road surface without the occupants feeling each and every bump and dip. Good suspensions permit drivers to take corners tighter, hit larger obstacles without sustaining serious damage, and even perform extreme stunts such as jumps.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"white-space:pre\"> </span><em style=\"font-family:var(--font-primary);font-size:var(--font-size-14)\">        </em><em style=\"font-family:var(--font-primary);font-size:var(--font-size-14)\">        </em><strong style=\"font-family:var(--font-primary);font-size:var(--font-size-14)\">Type: </strong><span style=\"font-family:var(--font-primary);font-size:var(--font-size-14)\">There are countless different types of suspension, with more being developed constantly. Typically, the vehicle’s suspension will fall into two major categories: dependent suspension (two or more wheels move together), or independent suspension (each wheel moves on its own). Within these two categories are many different styles of suspension, which may be driven mechanically (coil or leaf springs), pneumatically, hydraulically, with a combination hydropneumatic system, or other more esoteric systems.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"white-space:pre\"> </span><em style=\"font-family:var(--font-primary);font-size:var(--font-size-14)\">        </em><em style=\"font-family:var(--font-primary);font-size:var(--font-size-14)\">        </em><strong style=\"font-family:var(--font-primary);font-size:var(--font-size-14)\">Reactivity (Re): </strong><span style=\"font-family:var(--font-primary);font-size:var(--font-size-14)\">How quickly your vehicle responds when you turn the wheel can mean life or death in a lot of situations. Unless you’re planning on just going fast in a straight line, a scavenger should invest as much as they can in making sure their ride can turn as sharply as possible...without tumbling end-over-end, of course. This stat interacts with the vehicle’s Top Speed and Load to determine the assembled vehicle’s Turning.</span></p>\n<p><br /><span style=\"white-space:pre\"><em style=\"white-space:normal\">        </em></span><em>Modifications:</em> Whenever a scavenger looks to kit out their machine with custom components or unique features, they are applying a Modification to it. Modifications are a wide category covering anything that isn’t one of the primary five Components. This could include things like mounted weapons, defensive systems, trailers and sidecars, alternative methods of propulsion, pedal extensions, and who knows what else? Modifications will typically have a more freeform approach to stats and how they impact the vehicle’s overall build, but most will have a Weight stat which counts toward the vehicle’s curb weight, and thus its Load.</p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"In2xLaPZGv8dRTFr":3},"flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.UO0O6gnBPeOCWLyx"}}}
{"_id":"VVxBr33G7C8Xp1w7","name":"Special Damage","content":"<p><strong>Source</strong> <a title=\"Special Damage\" href=\"https://docs.google.com/document/d/1XRcTlTKTL7Wv61kHMCKbddd9LbTsdBMQnkKJxp5AJxg/edit?usp=sharing\">Special Damage</a></p>\n<p>If one finds that combat doesn’t have enough lasting consequences, increase the threat that comes from the horrors of battle with these new rules for permanent disfiguring injuries.</p>\n<h3><strong>What is Special Damage?</strong></h3>\n<p>Special damage is an optional rule subset for games that want or need that extra bit of gritty, brutal risk for their combat. The abstraction used by Pathinder to represent overall health and wellness cannot allow for lasting wounds. This system aims to provide that by giving rules to suffer catastrophic damage from wounds that would realistically maim or kill. The results of these rules could leave a Player Character permanently hobbled, but if the Game Master and Players agree that permanent disability is too much, they may also implement the rules for @Compendium[tsl-content.tsl-rules.gCRcLkpk3SQQwnd9]{Body Swaps} in order to give themselves back their missing limbs.</p>\n<h3><strong>What Causes Special Damage?</strong></h3>\n<p>There are two situations that can cause a character to suffer from special damage.</p>\n<p>The first is if a character takes more than 50% of their total Hit Points in damage from a single attack.</p>\n<p>The second is if a character suffers from a confirmed critical hit that causes their current Hit Points to drop to 0 or below.</p>\n<p>The third is somewhat more nebulous: the Game Master may rule that certain spells or effects that main or cause damage via transmutation may subject their victims to special damage.</p>\n<h3><strong>Using Special Damage</strong></h3>\n<p>When a creature is subject to special damage, roll on the table below. The outcome of the die roll will determine the effect they suffer.</p>\n<table style=\"width:100%;height:221px\" border=\"1\">\n<thead>\n<tr style=\"height:17px\">\n<td style=\"width:10.4747%;height:17px;text-align:center\">Die Result</td>\n<td style=\"width:89.5253%;height:17px;text-align:center\">Effect</td>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr style=\"height:17px\">\n<td style=\"width:10.4747%;height:17px;text-align:center\">01-15</td>\n<td style=\"width:89.5253%;height:17px\">The creature suffers no special damage - the attack simply does damage as normal.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style=\"height:17px\">\n<td style=\"width:10.4747%;height:17px;text-align:center\">16-25</td>\n<td style=\"width:89.5253%;height:17px\">The creature loses an eye. This special damage has no associated penalty, though the Game Master may rule that certain Perception or Charisma-based checks suffer a minor penalty.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style=\"height:17px\">\n<td style=\"width:10.4747%;height:17px;text-align:center\">26-35</td>\n<td style=\"width:89.5253%;height:17px\">The creature loses a hand, and permanently reduces their Constitution score by 1.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style=\"height:17px\">\n<td style=\"width:10.4747%;height:17px;text-align:center\">36-45</td>\n<td style=\"width:89.5253%;height:17px\">The creature loses a foot, and permanently reduces their Constitution score by 1.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"width:10.4747%;text-align:center\">46-55</td>\n<td style=\"width:89.5253%\">One of the creature's lungs is mangled beyond repair. They permanently reduce their Constitution score by 1.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style=\"height:17px\">\n<td style=\"width:10.4747%;height:17px;text-align:center\">56-65</td>\n<td style=\"width:89.5253%;height:17px\">The creature's throat is cut. They permanently lose the ability to speak.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style=\"height:17px\">\n<td style=\"width:10.4747%;height:17px;text-align:center\">66-70</td>\n<td style=\"width:89.5253%;height:17px\">The creature loses an arm, and permanently reduces their Constitution score by 2.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style=\"height:17px\">\n<td style=\"width:10.4747%;height:17px;text-align:center\">71-75</td>\n<td style=\"width:89.5253%;height:17px\">The creature loses a leg, and permanently reduces their Constitution score by 2.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style=\"height:17px\">\n<td style=\"width:10.4747%;height:17px;text-align:center\">76-85</td>\n<td style=\"width:89.5253%;height:17px\">The creature loses an extraneous body part, such as a tail or wing. The consequences of this are dependent on the part lost, and are up to the Game Master to decide. If the creature has no such extraneous body parts, then they do not suffer special damage for this attack - it simply deals its damage as normal.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style=\"height:17px\">\n<td style=\"width:10.4747%;height:17px;text-align:center\">86-92</td>\n<td style=\"width:89.5253%;height:17px\">Most of the creature's guts are mangled beyond repair. They permanently reduce their Constitution score by 2, and begin dying (see below).</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"width:10.4747%;text-align:center\">93-95</td>\n<td style=\"width:89.5253%\">The creature’s heart is mangled beyond repair. They permanently reduce their Constitution score by 3, and begin dying (see below).</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style=\"height:17px\">\n<td style=\"width:10.4747%;height:17px;text-align:center\">96-98</td>\n<td style=\"width:89.5253%;height:17px\">The creature's liver or other vital organ is mangled beyond repair. They permanently reduce their Constitution score by 3, and begin dying (see below).</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style=\"height:17px\">\n<td style=\"width:10.4747%;height:17px;text-align:center\">99</td>\n<td style=\"width:89.5253%;height:17px\">The creature's brain is destroyed. The creature immediately dies.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style=\"height:17px\">\n<td style=\"width:10.4747%;height:17px;text-align:center\">00</td>\n<td style=\"width:89.5253%;height:17px\">Roll twice, and suffer both.</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>Certain effects state that the victim of the special damage begins to die. In these situations, the character takes 1 point of damage, which cannot be reduced or mitigated in any way, every time their Constitution modifier in minutes passes. This continues until the body part that was destroyed is somehow restored or until the creature’s Hit Points reach a negative amount equal to their Constitution score, at which point they die as normal. These hit points can be healed with healing spells and effects, or if the creature has the regeneration special ability. The fast healing special ability is not sufficient and does not heal the lost hit points.</p>\n<p>Spells and effects that can restore or reattach lost body parts, such as @Compendium[pf1.spells.3fbrrckyfagfzyop]{Regenerate}, will reverse the effects of special damage.</p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"In2xLaPZGv8dRTFr":3},"flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.U1A4Leu5v7B63dAD"}}}
{"_id":"XPgM9BpPuT9fraXU","name":"Vehicles - Universal Upgrades","content":"<table border=\"1\">\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\" colspan=\"6\">Component Upgrades</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Upgrade</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Prerequisites</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Weight</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Install DC</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Install Time</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Cost</td>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Cabriolet</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Any Open Top</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">5 lbs.</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">8</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">10 minutes</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">2 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Control Extensions</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">--</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">5 lbs.</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">10</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">1 hour</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">2 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Control Locks</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">--</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">15 lbs.</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">12</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">2 hours</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">45 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Dual Engine</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">See entry</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">+35%</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">30</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">1 week</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">500 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Emergency Sails</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Any Ground or Aquatic</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">220 lbs.</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">15</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">1 hour</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">220 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Extradimensional Cargo</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Cargo Space</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">--</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">See entry</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">See entry</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">2,500 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Five-Point Harness</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">--</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">15 lbs.*</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">12*</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">2 hours*</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">75 gp*</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Fuel Additive Interface</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">--</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">5 lbs.</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">22</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">1 day</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">250 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Killswitch</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">--</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">--</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">20</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">4 hours</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">245 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Radio, Standard</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">--</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">5 lbs.</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">15</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">1 hour</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">10 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Radio, WB</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">--</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">10 lbs.</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">18</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">1 hour</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">100 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Shiny</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">--</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">--</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">15</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">4 hours</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">800 gp</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p><strong>Cabriolet:</strong> This modification adds a fabric cover to any Open Top vehicle, providing soft cover to all occupants from above and protecting them from weather like rain and direct sunlight.</p>\n<p><strong>Control Extensions:</strong> This simple modification is little more than some bits of metal piping and cables rigged up to extend the length of pedals and steering mechanisms. This modification allows Small-sized creatures to pilot vehicles designed for Medium-sized creatures without issue.</p>\n<p><strong>Control Locks:</strong> Sometimes the pilot has to get involved in the fray, which leaves the vehicle’s controls unattended. With this modification, the pilot can, as a swift action, set a number of small mechanical devices into position. This locks the vehicle’s controls in place, essentially allowing the vehicle to maintain its current course and speed without having to be supervised by the pilot. While control locks are engaged, the vehicle itself manages its piloting checks, freeing up the pilot to do whatever they wish, even leave the pilot’s seat or the vehicle entirely. A control-locked vehicle can take only one action - continue moving at its current speed in the direction it is currently traveling. It cannot make Pushes or special pilot maneuvers on its own, nor can it use its pilot’s stats to defend against attacks. It is considered unattended for all purposes. The control locks can be disabled with another swift action once a pilot (not necessarily the original pilot) retakes control of the vehicle.</p>\n<p><strong>Dual Engine:</strong> The most obsessive black thumbs may install a second engine onto the crankshaft in their vehicle, which can provide an enormous boost to a vehicle’s power in exchange for consuming more fuel. Any Steamhorse or Auto can be installed with a second engine suitable for its classification. Once complete, this increases the vehicle’s effective Horsepower by 50% of the weaker engine’s Horsepower, rounded down. The vehicle consumes double the amount of fuel, meaning for each Hour of Operation, it reduces its Hours of Operation by 2 instead of 1. Whenever the vehicle is required to Push its Engine, it must Push each of its engines. The cost listed for the modification is the cost to modify the vehicle’s crankshaft to accept a second engine - the second engine itself must also be acquired separately.</p>\n<p>Heavies have a special relationship with the Dual Engine modification. Because their engines are so large, they cannot use the Dual Engine modification without also having the Engine Swap (Auto → Heavy) modification.</p>\n<p><strong>Emergency Sails:</strong> Engines die all the time in the wastes, but the wind is often strong in Odium. Wise scavengers keep a set of these large cloth sails on hand as preparation for the worst. Unlike other modifications, this is not installed by default. Instead, the listed install time is used to determine how long it takes to install when necessary - typically when the engine is dead. This allows the vehicle to travel at a flat Speed value based on the current wind speed, per the table below. A vehicle using emergency sails always has an XLR8 of 1.</p>\n<table border=\"1\">\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Wind Strength</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Wind Speed</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Emergency Sail Speed</td>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Light</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">0-10 mph</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">0</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Moderate</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">11-20 mph</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">1</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Strong</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">21-30 mph</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">2</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Severe</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">31-50 mph</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">3</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Windstorm</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">50+ mph</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">4, +1 per additional 25 mph</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p><strong>Extradimensional Cargo:</strong> It wouldn’t be wrong to call this a “trunk of holding,” because that is effectively why this modification was developed. This modification can take any vehicle cargo space of up to 12 cubic feet and increase its space to 150 cubic feet. The vehicle is still affected by the weight of all its cargo - it can simply carry more.</p>\n<p>If living creatures are placed within the cargo space, they can survive for up to 10 minutes, after which time they suffocate. Retrieving a specific item from an extradimensional cargo hold is a full-round action. Items placed inside the cargo space do not offer any benefit to the vehicle hauling them. In an area that nullifies esoterics, the cargo hold loses its connection to the extradimensional space where its cargo is stored. This connection returns once it has been removed from the area of esoterics nullification.</p>\n<p>Installing an extradimensional cargo space is identical in practice to crafting a bag of holding, and as such, requires the same checks and crafting time as crafting a bag of holding type I.</p>\n<p><strong>Five-Point Harness:</strong> For the safety-conscious, these harnesses offer far more protection during a wreck than normal safety harnesses. For anyone buckled in with this harness, they reduce the damage taken in a wreck by an additional 50% over a normal safety harness, making a total reduction of 75%. The listed details on the table are per-seat, with only the seats receiving this modification gaining the benefits.</p>\n<p><strong>Fuel Additive Interface:</strong> This modification installs a pipe that leads directly to the fuel line, allowing fuel additives to be injected directly into the engine. With this modification, fuel additives can be added and activated all in the same standard action.</p>\n<p><strong>Killswitch:</strong> For the highly paranoid, kill switches are a proven way to ensure that your vehicle stays where you left it. These are essentially a series of buttons and switches installed on and around the dashboard of your vehicle, which must be pressed or flipped in a particular sequence programmed by the installer. Without the correct sequence being put in, the vehicle won’t start. An attempt to hot-wire the vehicle can be made, but the DC for the @Compendium[pf1.skills.CCy1fajKKU3K02iQ]{Disable Device} skill check to do so is doubled.</p>\n<p><strong>Radio:</strong> This small device picks up radio signals and plays them aloud over speakers. More advanced models can transmit audio from a receiver as well, making them vital for those looking to communicate while on the move.</p>\n<p><em>Standard</em>: This type of radio can receive air signals and play them, usually for news, information, or entertainment purposes. These are identical to the radio adventuring gear item, but are powered by the vehicle and thus do not require batteries.</p>\n<p><em>WB</em>: A WB, or “waste-band” radio, is used by cargo haulers, aircraft, and other vehicle pilots to communicate with each other as well as stationary outposts. Since these transmit from inside a vehicle, they don’t have the power to send a signal over large distances. Their transmission distance is typically limited to about 5 miles. They otherwise function as a standard radio.</p>\n<p><strong>Shiny:</strong> This modification covers the surface of the vehicle in chrome, which is then buffed to a mirror finish. This makes it difficult to look at directly during the day due to the light reflecting off of it. During daylight hours, anyone trying to spot the vehicle gains a +10 bonus to their @Compendium[pf1.skills.YYmmxDgp0g3ltSUG]{Perception} check, but the vehicle and its occupants benefit from a 10% miss chance applied to attacks made against it, and a +5 bonus to Reflex saves against area of effect attacks.</p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"In2xLaPZGv8dRTFr":3},"flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.nucEucmd5gIJ4BrZ"}}}
{"_id":"aSq8Lon6CvzvQEbo","name":"Special Substances","content":"<p>The exploding vehicles market is one area in which modern alchemists and chemists can truly shine. Any manner of concoction can be brewed to do the impossible with vehicles and their components, all without having to worry about whether they’re safe to be ingested. Below are just a few of these new chemical marvels.</p>\n<table style=\"width:50.5682%\" border=\"1\">\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:36.338%\">Name</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:24.7998%\">Craft DC</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:18.8622%\">Price</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:20%\">Weight</td>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:left;width:36.338%\">NUDJ</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:24.7998%\">20</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:18.8622%\">2 sp</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:20%\">½ lb.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:left;width:36.338%\">Squeeze canister</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:24.7998%\">25</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:18.8622%\">1 gp</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:20%\">10 lbs.</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p><em>        NUDJ:</em> Never go out in the wastes without it. That’s what the scavengers of Bastion say, and its popularity both among the scavengers and those living in the desert are good indicators that it’s fine advice. NUDJ is a byproduct of distilling liquor, and is not safe for consumption by any means. But when mixed with water and sprayed into the air intake of a vehicle, it can provide a significant boost to the vehicle’s engine. Great care must be taken, though, as too much strain on an engine can lead to disastrous results.</p>\n<p>        NUDJ can be sprayed (or spit) into the air intake of a moving vehicle as a standard action. Doing so prompts a Push against the vehicle’s Engine from its pilot, with +1 Integrity Resistance. Success means the Engine’s Horsepower increases by 2 for one round. Failure results in the normal consequences for a failed Push.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>        <em>Squeeze Canister:</em> Sometimes called giggle gas, this substance is merely nitrous oxide gas condensed into a canister. When injected into an engine, as it so often is by scavengers and auto racers, it cools and condenses the air entering the cylinders, allowing a stronger fuel-air mixture and significantly increasing the vehicle’s power output. It can strain the engine tremendously, so it is best used sparingly. This canister has 10 charges.</p>\n<p>        Squeeze can be injected directly into the vehicle’s Engine by the pilot or another vehicle passenger using a Squeeze System (see the Vehicle Modifications rules for more details) as a swift action. Doing so prompts a Push against the vehicle’s Engine from its pilot, with +1 Integrity Resistance. Success means the Engine’s Horsepower increases by 6 for one round. Failure results in the normal consequences for a failed push, except that the vehicle’s Integrity is reduced by 2 instead.</p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"In2xLaPZGv8dRTFr":3},"flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.fGO94rsE4f59X6l4"}}}
{"_id":"cpuj7DT4RorGP2Fg","name":"Mutation","content":"<p>Prolonged exposure to radiation can result in mutations. Much like the dreaded wild magic surge, these alterations to the mind, body, and even sometimes spirit are unpredictable, and can be either a great boon or a terrible curse.</p>\n<p><strong>Rad Counter: </strong>Radiation that has stuck to a character is measured in what the Odians call \"rads.\" All characters who venture out into the wastes have a rad counter, which begins at 0 and has a threshold equal to the character's Constitution score. When a character's rad count reaches the threshold, they develop a random mutation - or, more accurately, the mutation they've been developing as a result of prolonged radiation exposure noticably manifests itself for the character. The exact nature of the mutation is rolled in secret by the Game Master, and passed to the character at the time that they discover it. This takes place over a period of [[1d6]] days from the moment the character's rad count reached its threshold.</p>\n<p><strong>Accumulating Rads: </strong>Whenever a character fails a Fortitude save to resist the effects of radiation poisoning, they gain a number of rads based on the severity of the radiation poisoning per the table below.</p>\n<p><strong>Removing Rads: </strong>Because rads represent the effects that radiation has on the stability of bodily cells, it is no easy feat to remove them. Typically spells of the conjuration (healing) school won't work, nor will any Heal skill check. The <em>restoration</em> line of spells is the only thing that can remove rads from a creature; treat the rad count as points of permanent ability score drain for the purpose of the spell.</p>\n<p><strong>Overexposure: </strong>Exposure to radiation continues to increment the rad counter even after it has reached its threshold. If a character manages to accumulate a number of rads equal to twice their threshold, they gain another mutation. This happens each time a character reaches a multiple of their rad threshold, forever.</p>\n<hr />\n<h3><strong>Rads Per Radiation Level</strong></h3>\n<table style=\"width:29.8126%\" border=\"1\">\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"width:52.1285%\">Radiation Level</td>\n<td style=\"width:47.8774%\">Rads Gained</td>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"width:52.1285%\">Low</td>\n<td style=\"width:47.8774%\">1</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"width:52.1285%\">Medium</td>\n<td style=\"width:47.8774%\">2</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"width:52.1285%\">High</td>\n<td style=\"width:47.8774%\">3</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"width:52.1285%\">Severe</td>\n<td style=\"width:47.8774%\">4</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"In2xLaPZGv8dRTFr":3},"flags":{"gm-notes":{"notes":"<table style=\"width: 53.1142%;\" border=\"1\">\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"width: 38.5685%;\">Character</td>\n<td style=\"width: 29.0786%; text-align: center;\">Current Rads</td>\n<td style=\"width: 32.0261%; text-align: center;\">Rad Threshold</td>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"width: 38.5685%;\"><strong>Lok</strong></td>\n<td style=\"text-align: center; width: 29.0786%;\"><strong>0</strong></td>\n<td style=\"text-align: center; width: 32.0261%;\"><strong>8</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"width: 38.5685%;\"><strong>Louie</strong></td>\n<td style=\"text-align: center; width: 29.0786%;\"><strong>0</strong></td>\n<td style=\"text-align: center; width: 32.0261%;\"><strong>14</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"width: 38.5685%;\"><strong>Magpie</strong></td>\n<td style=\"text-align: center; width: 29.0786%;\"><strong>0</strong></td>\n<td style=\"text-align: center; width: 32.0261%;\"><strong>10</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"width: 38.5685%;\"><strong>Pronto</strong></td>\n<td style=\"text-align: center; width: 29.0786%;\"><strong>0</strong></td>\n<td style=\"text-align: center; width: 32.0261%;\"><strong>12</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"width: 38.5685%;\"><strong>Raven</strong></td>\n<td style=\"text-align: center; width: 29.0786%;\"><strong>0</strong></td>\n<td style=\"text-align: center; width: 32.0261%;\"><strong>10</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"width: 38.5685%;\"><strong>Seti</strong></td>\n<td style=\"text-align: center; width: 29.0786%;\"><strong>0</strong></td>\n<td style=\"text-align: center; width: 32.0261%;\"><strong>12</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"width: 38.5685%;\"><strong>Turnover</strong></td>\n<td style=\"text-align: center; width: 29.0786%;\"><strong>0</strong></td>\n<td style=\"text-align: center; width: 32.0261%;\"><strong>8</strong></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>"},"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.v5YBlw2h0MoJdtSL"}}}
