lign:center;width:11.4755%\">+50%</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:10.043%\">25</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:13.4864%\">3 days</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:8.46485%\">275 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:23.9598%\">Expanded Fuel Tank</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:32.5704%\">--</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:11.4755%\">See entry</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:10.043%\">See entry</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:13.4864%\">See entry</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:8.46485%\">See entry</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:23.9598%\">Extended Bed</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:32.5704%\">Pickup Body</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:11.4755%\">1,250 lbs.</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:10.043%\">25</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:13.4864%\">1 week</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:8.46485%\">500 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:23.9598%\">Extra Fuel Tank</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:32.5704%\">Any with at least 2 Crew Capacity rows</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:11.4755%\">See entry</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:10.043%\">See entry</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:13.4864%\">See entry</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:8.46485%\">See entry</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:23.9598%\">Extra Seating</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:32.5704%\">Phaeton Body</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:11.4755%\">1,000 lbs.</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:10.043%\">15</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:13.4864%\">4 days</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:8.46485%\">400 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:23.9598%\">Hitch</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:32.5704%\">Any Ground Auto</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:11.4755%\">5 lbs.</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:10.043%\">8</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:13.4864%\">1 hour</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:8.46485%\">25 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:23.9598%\">Monster Chassis</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:32.5704%\">Any Ground Auto</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:11.4755%\">+250%</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:10.043%\">30</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:13.4864%\">2 weeks</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:8.46485%\">750 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:23.9598%\">Off Road Tires</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:32.5704%\">Any Ground with Wheels Chassis</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:11.4755%\">--</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:10.043%\">5</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:13.4864%\">1 minute per tire</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:8.46485%\">50 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:23.9598%\">Reinforced Frame</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:32.5704%\">--</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:11.4755%\">+20%</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:10.043%\">25</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:13.4864%\">4 days / class</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:8.46485%\">1 sp / lb.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:23.9598%\">Roll Cage</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:32.5704%\">--</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:11.4755%\">+15%</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:10.043%\">25</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:13.4864%\">4 days / class</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:8.46485%\">1 sp / lb.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:23.9598%\">Seaplane</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:32.5704%\">Libellule, Monoplane, Biplane, Megaplane</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:11.4755%\">--</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:10.043%\">15</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:13.4864%\">4 hours</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:8.46485%\">150 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:23.9598%\">Sidecar</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:32.5704%\">Ground Steamhorse</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:11.4755%\">275 lbs.</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:10.043%\">18</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:13.4864%\">1 day</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:8.46485%\">300 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:23.9598%\">Ski Plane</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:32.5704%\">Libellule, Monoplane, Biplane, Megaplane</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:11.4755%\">--</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:10.043%\">15</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:13.4864%\">4 hours</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:8.46485%\">150 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:23.9598%\">Snorkel Intake</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:32.5704%\">Any Ground</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:11.4755%\">8 lbs.</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:10.043%\">10</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:13.4864%\">2 hours</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:8.46485%\">15 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:23.9598%\">Tonneau Cover</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:32.5704%\">Pickup Body</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:11.4755%\">20 lbs.</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:10.043%\">8</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:13.4864%\">10 minutes</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:8.46485%\">5 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:23.9598%\">Weight Reduction</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:32.5704%\">--</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:11.4755%\">See entry</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:10.043%\">5</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:13.4864%\">See entry</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:8.46485%\">--</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p><strong>Armor Plating:</strong> The easiest way to up-armor your vehicle is to weld scrap metal to the outside, and that’s exactly what some black thumbs do. Armor plating can be added in increments of +1 Armor, up to a maximum of +5 Armor. The table below gives details on the weight increase, install difficulty and time, and costs per extra point of armor:</p>\n<table style=\"width:100%;height:102px\" border=\"1\">\n<thead>\n<tr style=\"height:17px\">\n<td style=\"width:20.608%;height:17px;text-align:center\">Armor Point</td>\n<td style=\"width:27.0885%;height:17px;text-align:center\">Weight Increase</td>\n<td style=\"width:16.6659%;height:17px;text-align:center\">Install DC</td>\n<td style=\"width:19.858%;height:17px;text-align:center\">Install Time</td>\n<td style=\"width:14.6334%;height:17px;text-align:center\">Cost</td>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr style=\"height:17px\">\n<td style=\"width:20.608%;height:17px;text-align:center\">+1</td>\n<td style=\"width:27.0885%;height:17px;text-align:center\">10%</td>\n<td style=\"width:16.6659%;height:17px;text-align:center\">12</td>\n<td style=\"width:19.858%;height:17px;text-align:center\">1 day</td>\n<td style=\"width:14.6334%;height:17px;text-align:center\">100 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style=\"height:17px\">\n<td style=\"width:20.608%;height:17px;text-align:center\">+2</td>\n<td style=\"width:27.0885%;height:17px;text-align:center\">25%</td>\n<td style=\"width:16.6659%;height:17px;text-align:center\">15</td>\n<td style=\"width:19.858%;height:17px;text-align:center\">2 days</td>\n<td style=\"width:14.6334%;height:17px;text-align:center\">400 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style=\"height:17px\">\n<td style=\"width:20.608%;height:17px;text-align:center\">+3</td>\n<td style=\"width:27.0885%;height:17px;text-align:center\">45%</td>\n<td style=\"width:16.6659%;height:17px;text-align:center\">19</td>\n<td style=\"width:19.858%;height:17px;text-align:center\">4 days</td>\n<td style=\"width:14.6334%;height:17px;text-align:center\">1,200 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style=\"height:17px\">\n<td style=\"width:20.608%;height:17px;text-align:center\">+4</td>\n<td style=\"width:27.0885%;height:17px;text-align:center\">70%</td>\n<td style=\"width:16.6659%;height:17px;text-align:center\">24</td>\n<td style=\"width:19.858%;height:17px;text-align:center\">8 days</td>\n<td style=\"width:14.6334%;height:17px;text-align:center\">3,200 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style=\"height:17px\">\n<td style=\"width:20.608%;height:17px;text-align:center\">+5</td>\n<td style=\"width:27.0885%;height:17px;text-align:center\">100%</td>\n<td style=\"width:16.6659%;height:17px;text-align:center\">30</td>\n<td style=\"width:19.858%;height:17px;text-align:center\">16 days</td>\n<td style=\"width:14.6334%;height:17px;text-align:center\">8,000 gp</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p><strong>Crew Cab:</strong> When used for hard labor, pickups can be more useful when they have the space to transport laborers to the work site as well as materials. This is where a crew cab comes in. These larger pickups have an extra row of seating, increasing their Crew Capacity by +3. They also add an extra pair of doors - one for each side of the new row of seating.</p>\n<p><strong>Engine Swap:</strong> Whether due to availability concerns or simply the spirit of experimentation, occasionally black thumbs will perform an engine swap - putting an engine from one class of vehicle into the bay of another class of vehicle. The cost listed for the modification is the cost to modify the vehicle’s engine bay to accept the foreign engine - the engine itself must also be acquired separately.</p>\n<p><em>Auto → Heavy</em>: Usually caused by availability issues, Auto engines can be swapped into Heavy frames, though never on their own. In order to make a Heavy operate with an Auto engine, it requires two Auto engines, making the Dual Engines modification a prerequisite. Once installed, both Auto engines suffer a -2 Horsepower penalty for having to punch above their weight class. Even still, the combination of the two engines can potentially result in more power output than a single Heavy engine could.</p>\n<p><em>Auto → Steamhorse</em>: For the most insane speed freaks, a powerful V8 can be shoehorned into a Steamhorse frame for the ultimate in ill-advised power boosts. Auto engines installed in a Steamhorse frame gain an effective +2 Horsepower boost due to the huge reduction in weight they’re normally accustomed to hauling.</p>\n<p><strong>Expanded Fuel Tank:</strong> Fuel is essential for surviving the wastes. This makes the expanded fuel tank one of the most important modifications that a scavenger can invest in. This modification increases the size of the fuel tank, allowing it to hold more fuel. The vehicle’s fuel capacity and hours of operation are increased by 25% (rounded down). The vehicle’s weight and cost increase, as well as the modification install DC and time, are determined by their classification. This modification replaces and is replaced by the Extra Fuel Tank.</p>\n<p><em>Steamhorse</em>: The weight increases by 10 lbs. The install DC is 12. The install time is 2 hours. This modification costs 10 gp.</p>\n<p><em>Auto</em>: The weight increases by 30 lbs. The install DC is 15. The install time is 1 day. This modification costs 25 gp.</p>\n<p><em>Heavy</em>: The weight increases by 500 lbs. The install DC is 18. The install time is 5 days. This modification costs 75 gp.</p>\n<p><strong>Extended Bed:</strong> The most efficient scavengers want to drag in as big a haul as possible. A natural choice then is to extend the bed of their utes. An extended bed pickup extends their pickup bed by an additional 2 feet, increasing the cubic feet of storage space it can hold by 24 cubic feet.</p>\n<p><strong>Extra Fuel Tank:</strong> For the biggest increase in fuel capacity, the only choice is to sacrifice crew space. This modification removes one row of seats in the crew capacity (or the sleeper berth in the case of the Sleeper Cab Rig) and replaces it with a complete second fuel tank. This increases the fuel capacity for the vehicle by +100%. The vehicle’s weight and cost increase, as well as the modification install DC and time, are determined by their classification. This modification replaces and is replaced by the Expanded Fuel Tank.</p>\n<p><em>Steamhorse</em>: The weight increases by 40 lbs. The install DC is 15. The install time is 4 hours. This modification costs 25 gp.</p>\n<p><em>Auto</em>: The weight increases by 120 lbs. The install DC is 20. The install time is 2 days. This modification costs 75 gp.</p>\n<p><em>Heavy</em>: The weight increases by 2,000 lbs. The install DC is 25. The install time is 10 days. This modification costs 200 gp.</p>\n<p><strong>Extra Seating:</strong> The largest and most expensive phaetons are often used as limousines for wealthy passengers, and so can be upgraded to extend their seating arrangement. Each time this modification is purchased, it adds an extra row of seating to the phaeton body, increasings its Crew by +3. It also adds an extra 1,000 lbs of weight, and an extra pair of doors - one for each side of the new row. This modification can be purchased twice, to a total Crew of 3+3+3 and a maximum of 6 doors.</p>\n<p><strong>Hitch:</strong> This device is attached to the Chassis of a vehicle (or its Body directly, in the case of an Aquatic vehicle) to facilitate towing. Fitting a vehicle with a Hitch allows it to pull trailers. Day Cab Rig and Sleeper Cab Rig body styles come with hitches built-in.</p>\n<p><strong>Monster Chassis:</strong> Bigger is always better. If you agree, you should modify your vehicle with a Monster Chassis. This large, scaffolded frame for a Ground Auto increases its size by lifting the entire body up several feet. Vehicles modified in this way are elevated to the Heavy classification. They must now use Heavy components, and gain all the advantages and disadvantages of that vehicle class.</p>\n<p><strong>Off Road Tires:</strong> Racing slicks and everyday all-purpose tires can’t provide the grip one needs to properly move on difficult terrain. Instead scavengers turn to off-road tires, which have large paddles and deep treads to increase surface area and maximize grip on uneven or pliable surfaces. A vehicle outfitted with this modification is treated as being on pavement or stone while on hard or packed earth, and as being on hard or packed earth while on soft or loose earth. It also halves all penalties for road conditions, and the vehicle does not suffer from -1 effective Integrity when making Push attempts on unstable terrain. It instead suffers from -1 effective Integrity when making Push attempts on paved road or stone ground types.</p>\n<p>This modification is incompatible with the Solid Tires modification.</p>\n<p><strong>Reinforced Frame:</strong> This modification is ideal for pilots that find themselves frequently in vehicular combat, solidifying the vehicle’s frame in order to withstand more hits in combat. Vehicles with the reinforced frame modification are counted as one size category higher when figuring how much damage it receives from a collision. The vehicle’s weight increases by 20% when modified in this way, and the cost for this modification is 1 sp per pound increased. It takes 4 hours per the vehicle’s classification tier to complete this modification install - this equates to 4 hours for a Steamhorse, 8 hours for an Auto, 12 hours for a Heavy, and 16 hours for an Ultra.</p>\n<p><strong>Roll Cage:</strong> Wrecks are common in the wastes, and there is little more devastating to a (surviving) vehicle pilot than having their precious rig totaled in a wreck. To help protect against this, vehicles can be modified with a more rigid supporting structure to help keep them in a smaller number of pieces when they inevitably do wreck. Vehicles modified with a roll cage reduce any damage they take from a wreck by 50%. The vehicle’s weight increases by 15% when modified in this way, and the cost for this modification is 1 sp per pound increased. It takes 4 hours per the vehicle’s classification tier to complete this modification install - this equates to 4 hours for a Steamhorse, 8 hours for an Auto, 12 hours for a Heavy, and 16 hours for an Ultra.</p>\n<p><strong>Seaplane:</strong> Sometimes, an air vehicle needs to be able to land on a runway of water as opposed to earth. This modification replaces the standard air vehicle landing gear with large pontoons, allowing the plane to float on the water.</p>\n<p><strong>Sidecar:</strong> Steamhorse pilots are often left wanting when comparing their vehicle loadout to that of a sprinter like phaetons or coupés. The sidecar seeks to remedy that, serving as a way to add another fully disconnected passenger from the humble steamhorse. After installation, the sidecar changes the steamhorse to a 2+1 vehicle (as opposed to the default 1+1), allowing it to operate as a light attack vehicle or sprinter.</p>\n<p><strong>Ski Plane:</strong> For landings in remote locations, sometimes wheels are not the ideal landing gear. This modification replaces the standard air vehicle landing gear with large skis, which allows the plane to land on soft, loose earth like sand or snow.</p>\n<p><strong>Snorkel Intake:</strong> These modifications are essential when a vehicle absolutely must be forded across a river. Typically, a vehicle’s air intake is at the same level as its engine, and thus is very easy to flood in deep enough water. A snorkel intake raises the air intake, placing it as much as several feet above its stock location. A vehicle outfitted with a snorkel is only considered to be taking water into its air intake when the vehicle is fully submerged.</p>\n<p><strong>Tonneau Cover:</strong> Pilots who fear that their cargo will be stolen from their open-top pickup beds, fear no more. This modification is a hard shell that can be fastened to an Open Top cargo space, making it a Hard Top cargo space instead.</p>\n<p><strong>Weight Reduction:</strong> The easiest way to make a vehicle quicker and more agile is to strip out unnecessary weight, and luckily for the average black thumb, this modification is entirely free - after all, it costs nothing to get rid of stuff you already have. This modification can address stripping out two elements - Armor and Crew Capacity. For each point of Armor reduced, the vehicle loses 5% of its total weight. For each Crew Capacity removed, the vehicle loses 2% of its total weight. It takes 1 day per point of Armor reduced to complete the Armor weight reduction modification, and 1 hour per Crew Capacity removed to complete the Crew Capacity weight reduction modification. This can reduce the vehicle’s Armor to +0, and the Crew Capacity to 1 - only the pilot.</p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"In2xLaPZGv8dRTFr":3},"flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.bPHK7BesR5YAzHE7"}}}
{"_id":"dJuCCgo3ZYqIuCSa","name":"Vehicles - Building a Vehicle","content":"<p>Once all of the necessary components and desired modifications have been gathered and applied, the vehicle can be assembled. A complete vehicle has a different set of stats than its individual components, which are all influenced and modified by the stats of the component parts. The vehicle stats can be thought of as the vehicle’s “ability score modifiers” in that, much like ability score modifiers for a player character, these stats are informed by another set of stats, and are mostly what will be applied for practical vehicle usage.</p>\n<h3><strong>Component Stats</strong></h3>\n<p>In order to assemble a functioning vehicle, the user or builder must have gathered an Engine, a Transmission, a Chassis, a Suspension, and a Body. The values on the Engine’s <strong>Horsepower (Ho)</strong>, Transmission’s <strong>Power Transfer (Po)</strong>, Chassis’s <strong>Brakes (Br)</strong>, and Suspension’s <strong>Reactivity (Re)</strong> must fall within the usable range for each of these components, and each must have an <strong>Integrity </strong>greater than 0.</p>\n<p>The usable range for each component is typically between 1 and 10, though most parts can theoretically exceed 10 with enough modifications or with rare components. The exception to this is the Transmission’s <strong>Power Transfer</strong>, which will always be on a scale of 1 to 10. This is because the final vehicle stats that use Power Transfer in their calculations are measuring the percentage of the vehicle’s muscle being applied to either moving weight or to the vehicle’s top speed, so this statistic is representing what percentage is dedicated to each.*</p>\n<blockquote style=\"border-left:3px solid var(--color-border-light-tertiary)\">\n<p>* For this reason, modifications to the Transmission will never modify the Power Transfer stat, but will likely modify the final assembled vehicle stat of Torque instead.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Vehicle component <strong>Integrity </strong>will always be on a scale of 1 to 10, with 10 representing a brand new component.</p>\n<h3><strong>Assembled Stats</strong></h3>\n<p>Once the vehicle has been assembled by a capable black thumb, the base component stats come together in various ways to form <strong>Top Speed (Sp)</strong>, <strong>Torque (Tq)</strong>, <strong>XLR8</strong>, <strong>Load (Ld)</strong>, <strong>Turning (Tu)</strong>, and <strong>Stopping (St)</strong>. These stats have an assortment of calculations, all of which are easy to perform with a calculator. The formulas for each of the assembled stats are detailed below.</p>\n<p><em style=\"font-family:var(--font-primary);font-size:var(--font-size-14)\">         </em><strong style=\"font-family:var(--font-primary);font-size:var(--font-size-14)\">Top Speed (Sp)</strong><span style=\"font-family:var(--font-primary);font-size:var(--font-size-14)\">: This statistic is a representation of the vehicle’s maximum top speed. It is calculated by subtracting the Transmission’s Power Transfer from 11, then multiplying the difference by the Engine’s Horsepower.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-family:var(--font-primary);font-size:var(--font-size-14);white-space:pre\"> </span><em style=\"font-family:var(--font-primary);font-size:var(--font-size-14)\">        </em><strong style=\"font-family:var(--font-primary);font-size:var(--font-size-14)\">Torque (Tq):</strong><span style=\"font-family:var(--font-primary);font-size:var(--font-size-14)\"> This statistic is a representation of the vehicle’s maximum capacity for weight. It is calculated by multiplying the Engine’s Horsepower by the Transmission’s Power Transfer, then multiplying that number by 10.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"white-space:pre\"> </span><em style=\"font-family:var(--font-primary);font-size:var(--font-size-14)\">        </em><strong style=\"font-family:var(--font-primary);font-size:var(--font-size-14)\">Load (Ld):</strong><span style=\"font-family:var(--font-primary);font-size:var(--font-size-14)\"> This statistic is a representation of the vehicle’s overall Weight, translated in a way to more easily work with the other scaled stats. For every 200 pounds of Weight, the vehicle gains 1 point of Load. Additionally, the vehicle’s Load will impact its Top Speed and Hours of Operation. For every 100 points in the vehicle’s Load, the vehicle’s Top Speed and Hours of Operation are reduced by 1 (more on this in the Fuel and Operating Time section, below).</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"white-space:pre\"> </span><em style=\"font-family:var(--font-primary);font-size:var(--font-size-14)\">        </em><strong style=\"font-family:var(--font-primary);font-size:var(--font-size-14)\">XLR8:</strong><span style=\"font-family:var(--font-primary);font-size:var(--font-size-14)\"> This statistic is a representation of the vehicle’s ability to quickly move its own weight. The XLR8 represents the maximum Speed increase a vehicle can affect upon itself during a single move action. The pilot may choose to XLR8, and thus increase the vehicle’s Speed, anywhere from 1 up to its XLR8 (without exceeding their Top Speed). The XLR8 is calculated by dividing the vehicle’s Torque by its Load (to a maximum of the vehicle’s Top Speed).</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"white-space:pre\"> </span><em style=\"font-family:var(--font-primary);font-size:var(--font-size-14)\">        </em><strong style=\"font-family:var(--font-primary);font-size:var(--font-size-14)\">Turning (Tu):</strong><span style=\"font-family:var(--font-primary);font-size:var(--font-size-14)\"> This statistic is a representation of the vehicle’s turning radius. The Turning is the minimum number of squares required to safely make a 90-degree turn while traveling at its current Speed, along both axes. For example, a vehicle traveling north with a Turning of 15 would have to travel 15 squares (75 feet) along the X-axis, then another 15 squares (75 feet) along the Y-axis in order to make a turn. The Turning is calculated by adding together the Speed and Load, then dividing that sum by the Reactivity.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"white-space:pre\"> </span><em style=\"font-family:var(--font-primary);font-size:var(--font-size-14)\">        </em><strong style=\"font-family:var(--font-primary);font-size:var(--font-size-14)\">Stopping (St):</strong><span style=\"font-family:var(--font-primary);font-size:var(--font-size-14)\"> This statistic is a representation of the vehicle’s ability to safely bring itself to a stop. It is something like an inverse of XLR8 - the pilot may choose to decrease the vehicle’s current Speed by any number between 1 and its Stopping, until the vehicle has reached Speed 0 and stopped completely. The Stopping Distance is calculated by dividing the vehicle’s Load by 100, then subtracting the result from double the vehicle’s Brakes (to a minimum of 1).</span></p>\n<p>As mentioned previously, Aquatic vehicles have no Chassis, and therefore have no Brakes. Instead of relying on brakes to slow down, aquatic vehicles instead run their engines in reverse. This makes their Stopping equal to their XLR8.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>A vehicle sheet for FoundryVTT that does all of the necessary calculations is provided in order to make applying changes to a vehicle quick and easy to do, even with temporary changes to modifiers on the fly for any circumstances. This sheet can be found <a title=\"TSL Module for Foundry\" href=\"https://github.com/AugmenTab/tsl-module\">here</a>.</p>\n<h3><strong>Ground, Aquatic, and Aerial Differences</strong></h3>\n<p>All the rules given above are for Ground vehicles. They have no additional stat considerations based on their type alone.</p>\n<p>Aerial vehicles function mostly the same as Ground vehicles in regards to components and final stats, with one key difference: Aerial vehicles will additionally have a minimum Speed value, which represents the Speed they must reach in order to achieve lift and become airborne. If at any point their Speed is reduced below this point, they begin to fall (though most Aerial vehicles can glide safely back to the ground so long as their wings are undamaged). If the vehicle is unable to reach this minimum Speed, then it is simply unable to fly.</p>\n<p>Aquatic vehicles are a little different, however, in that they are missing one key component: the Chassis. That’s right: Aquatic vehicles do not use a Chassis component at all! So then how do they stop? By running their engines in reverse, of course. All Aquatic vehicles treat their XLR8 as their Stopping stat, too, and slow down at exactly the same rate as they speed up.</p>\n<h3><strong>Actual vs Reference</strong></h3>\n<p>Among these statistics for a completed vehicle, there are three that refer directly to existing game measurements of distance and time: Turning, Stopping, and XLR8. These can be used to refer to a vehicle’s performance in the game without issue, and will be the most commonly necessary stats to use in-game. The remaining statistics (Speed, Torque, and Load), do not have an immediate connection to any existing game measurements. Load can be easily multiplied by 200 to give a rough estimation of the Weight, but the vehicle sheet also keeps track of the vehicle’s weight in the event that it is needed (just the total weight of whatever crew and cargo is being carried, plus the vehicle weight, makes for the total weight). Speed and Torque are meant to be used mostly for loose reference, so the players and the Game Master can see at a glance how much faster one vehicle is moving compared to another, or how much more muscle one has compared to another.</p>\n<p>A vehicle’s Top Speed is converted automatically to miles per hour, kilometers per hour, and squares per round on the vehicle sheet, which is a great reference when determining travel time over long distances. This is the most likely circumstance in which this information will be sought after, and is readily available as a result. Rarely should it be important to know anything other than the Top Speed in terms of squares per round or miles per hour during a combat situation, as raiding or other vehicle combat will almost always be taking place at the slowest vehicle’s current Speed. Even damage based on vehicle collisions is based on the Speed value, but some Game Masters may prefer to use their own damage calculations based on miles per hour instead. There are calculations for these in order to understand them should the need arise.</p>\n<p>To calculate the equivalent miles per hour for any given Speed, double the Speed value, then add 40.</p>\n<p>To calculate the equivalent squares per round, multiply the miles per hour by 88, then divide by 30.</p>\n<p>The vehicle sheet does provide this information for both the vehicle’s current Speed as well as a handy macro for converting any recognized speed unit value into any other, and post it to chat.</p>\n<h3><strong>Fuel and Operating Time</strong></h3>\n<p>In addition to the base statistics, an assembled vehicle will also have values related to its fuel capacity and how long it can be driven before needing a refill. As a general rule, all vehicles of the same classification will have the same <strong>Fuel Capacity</strong>, which is how many Units of fuel they can hold in their tank or reservoir. Some modifications can increase or decrease this amount, and some special vehicles may naturally have an abnormal Fuel Capacity, but these will be fringe cases.</p>\n<p><strong>Units</strong> of fuel is a helpful way of determining the cost to refill a vehicle’s tank or reservoir. Not all vehicles use the same type of fuel, so instead of trying to include every possible measurement for all possible fuel types, fuel is instead defined as a fraction of a “whole” tank, with every topped off vehicle providing the same Hours of Operation as any other in its classification. The cost of fuel can fluctuate based on a number of factors, so prices are provided in this manual and by the Game Master on a per unit basis. Fuel is purchased in units, allowing a scavenger to purchase fractions of or complete tanks and reservoirs of all sizes.</p>\n<p>Related to the Fuel Capacity, a vehicle’s <strong>Hours of Operation</strong> is how long in hours the vehicle can be continually operated (while driven, idling, or otherwise powered on and consuming fuel) before the tank or reservoir is empty and must be refilled. This, too, will be about the same for every vehicle of the same classification, though as with the Fuel Capacity, modifications and special vehicles may provide abnormal figures. This is given for a full tank or reservoir, but determining the remaining Hours of Operation remaining on partial tanks is relatively easy math.</p>\n<p>Tanks or reservoirs are filled at a rate of 1 unit per round. This may require direct action from the character, in which case it requires their move-equivalent action, and cannot take any other actions that would require them to use their hands (or whatever limbs they are using to hold the fuel can they are refilling the vehicle with) or to move away from the vehicle. Some refilling aparati, such as automated pumps, need only be set up with an initial move-equivalent action, then continue filling unassisted until the vehicle is full or the source of fuel runs out.</p>\n<p>Below is a table showing the base Fuel Capacity and Hours of Operation for each classification:</p>\n<table style=\"width:56.7335%\" border=\"1\">\n<thead style=\"text-shadow:1px 1px var(--color-shadow-dark);border-bottom:1px solid var(--color-border-dark)\">\n<tr>\n<td style=\"width:29.484%;text-align:center\">Classification</td>\n<td style=\"width:29.2383%;text-align:center\">Fuel Capacity</td>\n<td style=\"width:41.2776%;text-align:center\">Hours of Operation</td>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"width:29.484%;text-align:center\">Steamhorse</td>\n<td style=\"width:29.2383%;text-align:center\">4 units</td>\n<td style=\"width:41.2776%;text-align:center\">4 hours</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"width:29.484%;text-align:center\">Auto</td>\n<td style=\"width:29.2383%;text-align:center\">12 units</td>\n<td style=\"width:41.2776%;text-align:center\">8 hours</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"width:29.484%;text-align:center\">Heavy</td>\n<td style=\"width:29.2383%;text-align:center\">200 units</td>\n<td style=\"width:41.2776%;text-align:center\">24 hours</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>The Ultra classification mostly comprises specialty vehicles and custom builds, so the Fuel Capacity and Hours of Operation vary too drastically in this classification to simplify it here. Each vehicle will be a unique case, and will provide these values in their entry.</p>\n<p>Aerial vehicles require much more fuel to maintain their lift, and as such, have much larger fuel tanks to fill in order to get the same hours of operation out of their vehicle. An Aerial vehicle’s fuel capacity is eight times that of an equivalent Ground vehicle.</p>\n<p>Besides the base figure and modifiers from modifications or special vehicles, Hours of Operation is modified by one other value: the Load. Carrying or dragging a lot of weight is hard on an engine, and will increase the amount of fuel needed to go the same distance or travel the same speed as an engine not so inundated. For every 100 points of Load, there is a -1 penalty to the Hours of Operation. This is typically only a concern for vehicles in the Heavy or Ultra category, which are designed primarily for moving extremely heavy payloads, but it would not be impossible for other classifications to experience this penalty under the right circumstances.</p>\n<h3><strong>Armor and Hit Points</strong></h3>\n<p>Vehicles will have a base Armor value determined by their size, per the table below. Armor functions like Hardness in nearly every way - all effects that apply to Hardness also apply to Armor, including (but not limited to) magic enhancement bonuses, spells and effects that target or affect Hardness, and oils or alchemical items that alter Hardness. Most vehicle Armor is assumed to be made of steel, though other materials, such as mithral, adamantine, akyrium, and obdurium can be used to make vehicle Armor. To make Armor out of these exotic materials is an extremely costly undertaking; most of the time, the necessary amount of material doesn’t even exist in all of Bastion, so to do so would require importing it, making it little more than a pipe dream for most.</p>\n<table style=\"width:56.3037%\" border=\"1\">\n<thead style=\"text-shadow:1px 1px var(--color-shadow-dark);border-bottom:1px solid var(--color-border-dark)\">\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:39.2857%\">Classification</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:32.8571%\">Base Armor</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:27.8571%\">Hit Points</td>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:39.2857%\">Steamhorse</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:32.8571%\">5</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:27.8571%\">25</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:39.2857%\">Auto</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:32.8571%\">10</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:27.8571%\">50</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:39.2857%\">Heavy</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:32.8571%\">15</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:27.8571%\">75</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>The Ultra classification mostly comprises specialty vehicles and custom builds, so the Armor will vary too drastically in this classification to simplify it here. Each vehicle will be a unique case, and will provide this value in its entry.</p>\n<p>Some Body Styles may alter the Armor value based on their shape and construction. The vehicle’s base Hit Points are always equal to 5 times the Armor value. Some modifications can increase or decrease the Armor, which will increase or decrease the Hit Points for the vehicle accordingly. Other modifications may also increase or decrease the Hit Points directly; these will have no effect on the Armor.</p>\n<p>Vehicle Armor can be enchanted, much like armor worn on a person, to become magical. This costs twice what it costs when improving worn armor in such a manner. Each +1 of enhancement bonus increases the vehicle’s Armor value by 2, which increases the hit points by +10. Vehicles can also be given enchantments, though they have their own special enchantments found in the Vehicle Special Qualities section.</p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"In2xLaPZGv8dRTFr":3},"flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.tletWyNIyghqkwvp"}}}
{"_id":"exqy89csX01xiqbv","name":"Vehicles","content":"<p><strong>Source</strong> <a title=\"Vehicles\" href=\"https://docs.google.com/document/d/19DJkzbFx_gFLGBFKc0qAFmHwgif6tpQ6a1kTjYDKIcQ/edit?usp=sharing\">Vehicles</a></p>\n<p>While automobiles have been around in one form or another for some time, nowhere are they more important to the culture and way of life of the people who drive them than in Odium. Powerful custom stallions and hogs roar through the forgotten sand dunes of The Sundered Lands, sowing chaos out in the wastes and bringing back the resources and riches vital to keeping the city of Bastion alive. Using the rules below, you will soon join them in a hog or stallion of your very own.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<h3><strong>Table of Contents</strong></h3>\n<ol>\n<li>@Compendium[tsl-content.tsl-rules.sXf75HdN9MmDoC73]{Classifications}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[tsl-content.tsl-rules.UbpSzyiNU4U6Gs47]{Components}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[tsl-content.tsl-rules.dJuCCgo3ZYqIuCSa]{Building a Vehicle}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[tsl-content.tsl-rules.i5P90tVM5MaT8lPH]{Vehicle Rules}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[tsl-content.tsl-rules.heVI4TL1SIJVyHYP]{Ultras}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[tsl-content.tsl-rules.fDdluFQYMl6OVQj8]{Scavenging Parts}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[tsl-content.tsl-rules.K0ygnJNiFu1khvSw]{Vehicles - Items, Modifications, &amp; Equipment}<br />\n<ol>\n<li>@Compendium[tsl-content.tsl-rules.5PRsKcEsizUcwGyz]{Body Descriptions}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[tsl-content.tsl-rules.qiQLRCvKrpBCk1F1]{Engine Descriptions}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[tsl-content.tsl-rules.8MAFpYXYpSpXieVu]{Transmission Descriptions}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[tsl-content.tsl-rules.v9CTejiMLBDcFP3p]{Suspension Descriptions}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[tsl-content.tsl-rules.IK7327TO436bD4EG]{Chassis Descriptions}</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n<li>@Compendium[tsl-content.tsl-rules.TJYmpUXMTlv00Wtu]{Fuel Additives}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[tsl-content.tsl-rules.aSq8Lon6CvzvQEbo]{Special Substances}</li>\n</ol>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"In2xLaPZGv8dRTFr":3},"flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.hRRPVIgLLYmMozHz"}}}
{"_id":"fDdluFQYMl6OVQj8","name":"Vehicles - Scavenging Parts","content":"<p>While traveling in the wastes of Odium, you will eventually come across a lost or abandoned vehicle (and possibly what’s left of its unfortunate crew, as well). Like vultures, Odians know how to pick a vehicle (and a corpse) clean of all of its useful gear. </p>\n<p>Scavenging vehicles for parts and scrap is at the heart of life in Odium, but may not be very common in other regions of the campaign tsl-content. As such, this entire section can be viewed as an optional variant rule.</p>\n<p>Discovering a vehicle in the wastes is a lucky find, and so, most of the rules for scavenging parts are determined using dice rolls. Either the Game Master or the players will be able to roll dice according to the tables below, and once finished, the sequence of rolls will spit out a vehicle, functioning or otherwise, that the players can recover.</p>\n<p>First is to determine what the vehicle classification and type are, using the tables below. Finding an Ultra is a rare situation, and typically results in an event or encounter that treats the Ultra as a map unto itself, perhaps with rival scavengers or animals having already claimed the mechanical beast. Because Ultras are all unique and highly specialized, they cannot be salvaged for components to use with other Ultras.</p>\n<table style=\"width:31.6761%\" border=\"1\">\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:35.5815%\">d%</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:64.4185%\">Vehicle Found</td>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:35.5815%\">01-40</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:64.4185%\">Steamhorse</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:35.5815%\">41-80</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:64.4185%\">Auto</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:35.5815%\">81-99</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:64.4185%\">Heavy</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:35.5815%\">00</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:64.4185%\">Ultra</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<table style=\"width:31.6761%\" border=\"1\">\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:35.4196%\">d%</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:64.5804%\">Type Found</td>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:35.4196%\">01-80</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:64.5804%\">Ground</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:35.4196%\">81-99</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:64.5804%\">Aerial</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:35.4196%\">00</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:64.5804%\">Aquatic</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>Once this is known, the Body style can be determined using the below set of tables. The remaining hit points for the vehicle is equal to a percentage of that Body style’s base hit points, rolled using a d% (rounding down). Vehicles found with 0% of their remaining hit points can either be salvaged for scrap or repaired, but may still contain components that are worth recovering.</p>\n<table style=\"width:63.7536%\" border=\"1\">\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:100%\" colspan=\"4\">Steamhorse Body Types</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:15.8111%\">d%</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:31.4168%\">Ground</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:28.9528%\">Aerial</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:23.8193%\">Aquatic</td>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:15.8111%\">01-30</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:31.4168%\">Putter Pony</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:28.9528%\" rowspan=\"2\">Libellule</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:23.8193%\" rowspan=\"2\">Dinghy</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:15.8111%\">31-70</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:31.4168%\">Steamhorse</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:15.8111%\">71-00</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:31.4168%\">Quad</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:28.9528%\">Gyrocopter</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:23.8193%\">Skimmer</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<table style=\"width:63.7536%\" border=\"1\">\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:100%\" colspan=\"4\">Auto Body Types</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:14.2037%\">d%</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:29.2683%\">Ground</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:26.3989%\">Aerial</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:30.1291%\">Aquatic</td>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:14.2037%\">01-05</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:29.2683%\">Barchetta</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:26.3989%\" rowspan=\"7\">Biplane</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:30.1291%\">Thunderboat</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:14.2037%\">06-10</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:29.2683%\">Big Axle</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:30.1291%\" rowspan=\"5\">Catamaran</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:14.2037%\">11-15</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:29.2683%\">Buggy</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:14.2037%\">16-30</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:29.2683%\">Coupé</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:14.2037%\">31-35</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:29.2683%\">Open-Wheel</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:14.2037%\">36-45</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:29.2683%\">Phaeton</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:14.2037%\">46-60</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:29.2683%\">Pickup</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:30.1291%\" rowspan=\"5\">Runabout</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:14.2037%\">61-70</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:29.2683%\">Roadster</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:26.3989%\" rowspan=\"4\">Monoplane</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:14.2037%\">71-80</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:29.2683%\">Sedan</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:14.2037%\">81-90</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:29.2683%\">Van</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:14.2037%\">91-00</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:29.2683%\">Wagon</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<table style=\"width:445px;border-top:1px solid var(--color-border-light-tertiary);border-bottom:1px solid var(--color-border-light-tertiary)\" border=\"1\">\n<thead style=\"text-shadow:1px 1px var(--color-shadow-dark);border-bottom:1px solid var(--color-border-dark)\">\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:438px\" colspan=\"4\">Heavy Body Types</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:60.125px\">d%</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:189.562px\">Ground</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:104.094px\">Aerial</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:84.2188px\">Aquatic</td>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:60.125px\">01-15</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:189.562px\">Bus</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:104.094px\" rowspan=\"3\">Aerostat</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:84.2188px\" rowspan=\"3\">Barge</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:60.125px\">16-50</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:189.562px\">Day Cab Rig</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:60.125px\">51-65</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:189.562px\">Double-Decker</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:60.125px\">66-95</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:189.562px\">Sleeper-Cab Rig</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:104.094px\" rowspan=\"2\">Megaplane</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:84.2188px\" rowspan=\"2\">Yacht</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:60.125px\">96-00</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:189.562px\">Tank</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>After the Body comes the components within the Body. First, a roll is made to determine how many components, if any, are salvageable from the vehicle. These recovered components may be either rolled randomly (using a d4 or other appropriate die) or chosen by the Game Master.</p>\n<p>Once selected, each component’s Integrity and Power Transfer, Horsepower, Reactivity, or Brakes stat must be determined. Integrity is found by rolling a d10 - the result is the part’s Integrity, with the exception of a result of 10, which is instead treated as a 0 (the part is beyond repair, and is good only for scrap). As for the part’s respective stat, this is determined by the roll of the die indicated on the tables below.</p>\n<p>For some components, multiple different values must be rolled to fully determine the nature of the part. In those cases, the d% is rolled once for each section (separated by a dashed line).</p>\n<table style=\"width:29.0831%\" border=\"1\">\n<thead>\n<tr style=\"text-align:center\">\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:33.1293%\">d%</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:66.8707%\">Salvageable Parts</td>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:33.1293%\">01-05</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:66.8707%\">0</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:33.1293%\">06-45</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:66.8707%\">1</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:33.1293%\">46-75</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:66.8707%\">2</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:33.1293%\">76-95</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:66.8707%\">3</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:33.1293%\">96-00</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:66.8707%\">4</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<table style=\"width:53.5817%\" border=\"1\">\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:13.1367%\">d%</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:34.5773%\">Dependency</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:1.07955%\"> </td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:30.563%\">Suspension</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:20.6434%\">Re Die</td>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:13.1367%\">01-45</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:34.5773%\">Dependent</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:1.07955%\"> </td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:30.563%\">Mechanical</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:20.6434%\">d6</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:13.1367%\">46-75</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:34.5773%\">Mixed</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:1.07955%\"> </td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:30.563%\">Hydraulic</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:20.6434%\">d8</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:13.1367%\">76-95</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:34.5773%\" rowspan=\"2\">Fully Independent</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:1.07955%\" rowspan=\"2\"> </td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:30.563%\">Pneumatic</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:20.6434%\" rowspan=\"2\">d10</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:13.1367%\">96-00</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:30.563%\">Esoteric</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<table style=\"width:40.1146%\" border=\"1\">\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:20.4334%\">d%</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:52.9412%\">Engine Fuel Type</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:26.6254%\">Ho Die</td>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:20.4334%\">01-40</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:52.9412%\">Steam</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:26.6254%\">d6</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:20.4334%\">41-60</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:52.9412%\">Guzzolene</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:26.6254%\" rowspan=\"2\">d8</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:20.4334%\">61-80</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:52.9412%\">Deezil</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:20.4334%\">81-84</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:52.9412%\">Arcanomotor</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:26.6254%\" rowspan=\"3\">d10</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:20.4334%\">85-88</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:52.9412%\">Crystal Engine</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:20.4334%\">89-90</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:52.9412%\">Elemental</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:20.4334%\">91-00</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:52.9412%\">Tourbillon</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:26.6254%\">d8</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<table style=\"width:40.1146%;height:95px\" border=\"1\">\n<thead>\n<tr style=\"height:17px\">\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:23.3813%;height:17px\">d%</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:49.6403%;height:17px\">Transmission Type</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:26.9784%;height:17px\">Po Die</td>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr style=\"height:10px\">\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:23.3813%;height:10px\">01-50</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:49.6403%;height:10px\">Manual</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;height:61px;width:26.9784%\" rowspan=\"4\">\n<p>d10</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style=\"height:17px\">\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:23.3813%;height:17px\">51-70</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:49.6403%;height:17px\">Sequential</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style=\"height:17px\">\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:23.3813%;height:17px\">71-85</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:49.6403%;height:17px\">Horlogian</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style=\"height:17px\">\n<td style=\"te