{"_id":"gCRcLkpk3SQQwnd9","name":"Body Swaps","content":"<p><strong>Source</strong> <a title=\"Body Swaps\" href=\"https://docs.google.com/document/d/1BZaXV_kmUln_7k8ERwRItv4-RkCQeay2drzD-S2xgDI/edit?usp=sharing\">Body Swaps</a></p>\n<p>Odium is a dangerous place. Folks lose life and limb all the time, but while there isn’t much that can be done about the former, body swaps were created to remedy the latter.</p>\n<p>Body swaps, simply put, is a term used to refer to any mechanically- or esoterically-created artificial limb or body part meant to replace a lost biological one. Hands and feet, entire arms and legs, eyes, organs - you name it, you can buy a body swap replacement somewhere. There are scavengers in Bastion who are more machine than flesh now, and you can be too, if you so desire - or are just unlucky enough.</p>\n<h2>Body Swap Rules</h2>\n<p>The various body swaps available in Odium can be purchased and installed at a number of chop shops in Bastion or even in the Wastes. Whether you’re searching for a body swap to replace a lost part, being brought in as a waiter about to kick it, or just as someone that wants to cut off a perfectly bit of flesh and replace it with cold unfeeling steel, the rules regarding the surgeries, installations, and prostheses all remain the same.</p>\n<p>This rule set does not provide a comprehensive list of mechanical penalties or other rules for what happens after losing a body part. Other systems can provide this, the Game Master can write one, or the rules can be created based on the circumstance in which they were lost. This variant rule set is more for those who want a simple system for how one goes about replacing lost limbs with prostheses. For the rules on the variant health system used in The Sundered Lands setting by default, you can reference the @Compendium[tsl-content.tsl-rules.VVxBr33G7C8Xp1w7]{Special Damage} rules.</p>\n<p>In this body swap rule set, prostheses are split up into two separate groups: the actual <strong>Prosthesis</strong> of the body part that is to be replaced, and the <strong>Build</strong>, which defines what type of system it runs on. There are twelve different prostheses available: <em>Hand, Arm, Foot, Leg, Tail, Wings, Eye, Voicebox, Lung, Heart, Splanchnic,</em> and<em> Guts</em>. There are three different build types available: <em>Unpowered, Powered,</em> and <em>Esocrafted</em>. More information on each of these will be provided in the Descriptions section below.</p>\n<p>Regardless of what body part is being replaced and by what, the important thing to remember is that, apart from the special rules for each, the prostheses will all function as the intended body part. This means they can be targeted by spells that target specific body parts, that the user can still wear apparel or slotted items on the spaces they would otherwise represent, and that they are treated as the body part for any effect or condition that might otherwise affect that body part.</p>\n<p>In addition to counting as the body part in question, prostheses are also considered to be attended objects while they are attached or installed. Unlike a true body part, attacks made to a prosthesis do not affect the hit points of the wearer. They can be sundered, damaged, and destroyed just like any other object and, upon taking damage in excess of half of its total hit points, a prosthesis will likewise gain the broken condition. Unless otherwise stated, body swap components have the same hardness and hit points as a suit of full plate armor made of the same material.</p>\n<p>While a prosthesis is suffering from the broken condition, any aspects of that prosthesis that would be affected by the broken condition are affected as if they too have the broken condition. Additionally, all of the special benefits of a prosthesis are lost until the prosthesis is repaired - it simply functions like a normal body part. These penalties all disappear once a prosthesis is repaired to where it is no longer below half of its total hit points. Prostheses can all be repaired like any other object of their type, be it mundane or esoteric.</p>\n<p>If a prosthesis is damaged to the point that it is reduced to zero total hit points, it is destroyed. The wearer loses all benefits of the prosthesis immediately, and is treated as if they had once again lost the body part that was replaced by it.</p>\n<h2>Body Swap Installation</h2>\n<p>Once a body part has been lost (or the decision to replace an existing one with a prosthesis has been made), the patient must be delivered to a chop shop or other medical expert who is able to perform an installation surgery. These surgeries are slightly different depending on the type of prosthesis being replaced, but in all cases, they are stressful for the patient and must be performed very carefully in the innately unsanitized environment that is Odium.</p>\n<p>For Heart, Lung, Guts, and Splanchnic prostheses, they are permanently installed during the surgery and cannot be removed without severe risk to the user. If one of these prostheses must be replaced, it requires another installation surgery, and everything that goes along with it (detailed below).</p>\n<p>For Hand, Arm, Foot, Leg, Tail, Wings, Eye, and Voicebox prostheses, the surgery is not to install the prosthesis itself but rather to install a special mounting bracket, called a “hot swap joint” (or a “hot swap socket” for the Eye and Voicebox prostheses) at the location to which the prosthesis will connect. This installation will connect the muscle and nerves at the location to the hot swap joint, which will allow the user to move and control the prosthesis as if it were their own lost body part. The prostheses themselves are then attached or inserted into this joint.</p>\n<h3><strong>Swapping Prostheses</strong></h3>\n<p>Hand, Arm, Foot, Leg, Tail, Wings, Eye, and Voicebox prostheses make use of a hot swap joint or hot swap socket and can be switched out for upgraded or specialized prostheses as desired. Swapping a Hand, Arm, Foot, or Leg prosthesis from a hot swap joint takes ten minutes - removing the existing prosthesis takes five minutes, and attaching a prosthesis takes five minutes. Removing an Eye prosthesis from a hot swap socket and inserting another takes one full round action. Hot swappable prostheses are designed to be swapped out with one hand - doing so requires no assistance or tool kits.</p>\n<h3><strong>The Installation Surgery</strong></h3>\n<p>Once the patient has been delivered to the chop shop, the surgery takes 8 hours to complete and deals an amount of hit point damage to the user depending on the prosthesis (listed in its entry in the Descriptions section below). This hit point damage can reduce the patient to below zero hit points, or even kill them, if they begin the surgery with some hit point damage already sustained or if they simply do not have a pool large enough to have a positive hit point pool after taking the surgical damage.</p>\n<p>If reduced to zero or fewer hit points by the surgery, complications arise during the surgery. This is resolved normally, with the patient beginning to bleed out unless the organic mechanics can stabilize them or the patient arranges for a source of magical healing to be available during the surgery. If this hit point damage would reduce their hit points to below their death threshold, they die on the operating table. If using the Massive Damage optional rule, and this hit point damage would qualify as massive damage, the patient dies.</p>\n<p>If a patient dies on the operating table, the surgery immediately ends, and the organic mechanics will inform the patient’s companions (if any) in one round. The patient can be revived, or have their body and soul preserved for later revival, if the resources are available to their allies.</p>\n<p>To perform the surgery, the operator must make a series of successful Heal skill checks in a row depending on the prosthesis being installed. Failing a check means the patient takes the surgical damage again, and the counter for successful checks resets. These checks can be retried as many times as are necessary to complete the surgery, assuming the patient survives. The cost for the surgery is 100 gp, regardless of the outcome or prosthesis being installed. Organic mechanics will perform this surgery even if the patient cannot pay - even in Bastion, medical professionals have a sense of duty to the sick and injured. The patient simply falls into debt with them, and must pay back the cost of the surgery over time.</p>\n<p>After the surgery is complete, the patient begins the healing process. Once their hit points have healed back up to their maximum hit points, the surgery is considered healed and ready for the prosthesis to be attached (if applicable). For the purpose of healing the surgery, magical healing will not count towards healing the surgery - the body must become accustomed to its new state on its own, though magic can be used to speed up the natural healing process. Once the installation is complete, all non-permanent penalties associated with missing that body part are removed. If installing an Eye, Voicebox, Lung, Heart, Splanchnic, or Guts prosthesis, the process is now complete. If installing a Hand, Arm, Foot, Leg, Tail, or Wings prosthesis, the acclimation period begins.</p>\n<h3><strong>The Acclimation Period</strong></h3>\n<p>Some prostheses do not provide sensory information like a real body part does, and it takes time to adjust and learn how to move the part, understand its location relative to the wearer, and apply the right amount of force for everyday tasks. Once the patient has fully healed, they must begin an acclimation period. </p>\n<p>This period lasts for 70 days, or 10 weeks. It can be reduced by 1 day per point of combined Intelligence and Wisdom score. Those who have already experienced an acclimation period for an installed prosthesis before also reduce this period by 7 days per installed prosthesis. The minimum acclimation period is 30 days - it cannot be reduced below this amount by any means.</p>\n<p>This acclimation period must be experienced each time a new prosthesis is first installed, even if the wearer already has another prosthesis of the same type. For example, if the wearer has a right arm prosthesis that they have acclimated to, but then suffers an injury later and must install a left arm prosthesis, the left arm prosthesis still requires an acclimation period.</p>\n<p>The wearer will experience side effects during the acclimation period. These are different for each type of prosthesis (listed in their respective entries in the Description section below). The effects listed are physical, but the Game Master may add additional side effects that can be a mix of physical, psychological, and even spiritual obstacles that the wearer will have to overcome. All effects of the acclimation are removed once the acclimation period is complete.</p>\n<p>Prostheses built using the esocrafted build will include esoteric connections that provide touch sensation just like real body parts do. In this case, the wearer does not experience an acclimation period, but recovering from an amputation or other serious injury that could warrant a prosthesis is difficult in more ways than just physically. The Game Master may still provide obstacles on a character’s psychological, emotional, or spiritual recovery, even with an esocrafted prosthesis.</p>\n<h3><strong>Extraneous Installs</strong></h3>\n<p>Due to the flexibility of these engineering marvels, prostheses can be installed even on characters that haven’t lost any body parts. In these cases, they are known as extraneous installs, and are the ultimate expression of disposable wealth and body modification in Bastion.</p>\n<p>Performing an extraneous install has the same process as installing any other prosthesis, though typically the host can go into the surgery in a much healthier state. Each prosthesis has a <strong>Limit</strong> value, shown on the table Body Swap Prices, which dictates how many of the given prosthesis can be installed on a creature. Some are prefixed with a plus (+), which indicates how many prostheses can be installed extraneously on any creature, regardless of how many of the body type that prosthesis replaces they already have. Others are simply a flat number value, which indicates how many of both the normal body part and the prostheses any one creature can possess.</p>\n<p>For any prosthesis with an acclimation period, having it installed extraneously means its acclimation period (after adjustments) is doubled - this is both for adapting to using the limb adeptly, as well as learning how to use a limb you previously didn't have in the first place.</p>\n<h2>Body Swap Descriptions</h2>\n<p>There are three prosthesis build types that can be installed.</p>\n<p><span style=\"white-space:pre\"> </span><em>Unpowered:</em> Prostheses of the unpowered build type are made of complex and delicate Horlogian clockwork mechanisms, and were not designed with adventurers or scavengers in mind. They are available in much higher quantities than the others, though, due to how easy they are to import. These prostheses are always mundane, and thus function normally in an area of nullified esoterics.</p>\n<p><span style=\"white-space:pre\"> </span><em>Powered:</em> Prostheses of the powered build type are typically designed and built in Bastion proper, using scrap and auto parts to create something more appropriate for the dangerous work of the revered scavengers. These units require a steamhorse engine of at least Horsepower 1 to function, but are capable of much more than the unpowered variants. If the engine chosen takes fuel, they consume 1 unit of fuel per day in order to function. If the engine chosen has a special attack, the wearer of the prosthesis may use it once per day as a full-round action. If the selected engine is mundane, then the prosthetic itself is mundane, and functions in an area of nullified esoterics. Otherwise, the prosthetic is useless in such an area without the esoterics shielding engine modification.</p>\n<p><span style=\"white-space:pre\"> </span><em>Esocrafted:</em> These top of the line prostheses are designed by esoterics engineers for the express intent of being the best of the best. An esocrafted prosthesis can use arcane magic, divine magic, nature magic, psionics, or another form of esoteric engineering in its construction. This allows them to provide sensory information to their wearer, and as a result, have no acclimation period. It also allows them to be later enchanted to provide an enhancement bonus to an ability score based on the prosthetic. It comes standard with esoterics nullification shielding, preventing it from become totally worthless in an area of esoterics nullification - in such an area, it continues to function as a normal limb with sensory information, though any enchantments it may have been given will still cease functioning in the area as normal.</p>\n<p>Regardless of prosthesis or build type, prostheses can be made of any material used to make armor or weapons, though they may not all provide a benefit. If none is specified at the time of purchase, a prosthesis is assumed to be made of iron or steel, or otherwise whatever the cheapest and most readily available suitable material is.</p>\n<p>All prostheses count as masterwork for any aspect of their composition - they come ready for enchantment, strikes with them gain a +1 enhancement bonus on attack rolls, built-in tools grant a +2 circumstance bonus on related skill checks, and anything else that may come up. This is already factored into their price.</p>\n<p>All prices given on the table below are for Medium creatures. The prices are doubled for Large, and again for every size category high. Conversely, they are halved for Small creatures; creatures any smaller than that still pay the price for Small creatures, as making extremely small, complex objects like prostheses comes with its own expensive challenges.</p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"In2xLaPZGv8dRTFr":3},"flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.kAfkQVXaP59YgBwG"}}}
{"_id":"gcrFxNyQBhz73nt8","name":"Vehicles - Component Upgrades","content":"<table border=\"1\">\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\" colspan=\"6\">Component Upgrades</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Upgrade</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Prerequisites</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Weight</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Install DC</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Install Time</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Cost</td>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Anti-Lag System</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Engine with Turbocharger</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">20 lbs.</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">18</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">2 days</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">180 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Dracolytic Converter</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Any Engine</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">25 lbs.</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">25</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">4 days</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">800 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Esoengine Conversion</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Arcanomotor or Crystal Engine</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">10 lbs.</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">22</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">2 days</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">550 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Esoengine Shielding</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Any Non-Mundane Engine</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">450 lbs.</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">28</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">5 days</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">1,500 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Flash-Evap Piston Heads</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Steam Engine</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">--</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">30</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">8 weeks</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">1,350 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Header</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Any Exhausting Engine</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">--</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">15</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">1 hour</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">85 gp*</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Performance Exhaust</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Any Exhausting Engine</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">15 lbs.</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">18</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">4 hours</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">175 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Psiconverter</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Any Engine</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">25 lbs.</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">25</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">4 days</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">800 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Recondenser</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Steam Engine</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">35 lbs.</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">30</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">7 days</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">1,250 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Solid Tires</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Wheels Chassis</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">30 lbs.*</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">12*</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">5 minutes*</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">50 gp*</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Squeeze System</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Any Engine</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">15 lbs.</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">18</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">1 day</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">50 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Supercharger</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Any Engine</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">100 lbs.</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">20</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">4 hours</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">200 gp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Tuning</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Any Mundane Engine</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">--</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">15 + Ho boost</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">1 day</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">See entry</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Turbocharger</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Any Engine</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">50 lbs.</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">25</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">1 day</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">70 gp</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p><strong>Anti-Lag System:</strong> Perhaps the only downside of turbochargers is turbo lag - a brief period where the turbo needs to spool up after the accelerator is depressed before the boost kicks in. The solution to this problem is the anti-lag system, which uses a richer fuel mixture and some extra plumbing in the exhaust system to keep the turbocharger constantly spooled up for immediate boost. Vehicles with an anti-lag system installed don’t suffer the usual XLR8 penalty associated with turbochargers, but suffer a -1 effective Integrity Resistance to their Engine. Anyone making a @Compendium[pf1.skills.YYmmxDgp0g3ltSUG]{Perception} check to hear the vehicle receives a +10 bonus.</p>\n<p><strong>Dracolytic Converter:</strong> This flexible modification converts every 2 spell levels fed into it into 1 hour of operation for any engine type, allowing the magically-gifted to fuel a vehicle regardless of what type of fuel it typically takes. Spell levels can be added by holding onto a conduit which accepts the spell energy. This conduit is typically attached to the steering mechanism or handlebars to permit the driver to channel the energy themselves, though it can be mounted anywhere.</p>\n<p><strong>Esoengine Conversion:</strong> This module converts between types of esoteric fuel, allowing power points to fuel an arcanomotor or spell levels to fuel a crystal motor. To convert between esoengine fuel types doubles the number of spell levels or power points required to gain an additional hour of operation.</p>\n<p><strong>Esoengine Shielding:</strong> Often seen as one of the most important modifications for engines that will go out into the wastes, this complex shell of lead and exotic metals protects an esoteric engine from the nullification effects of the wastes. Engines fitted with this modification continue to operate normally in an area of esoterics nullification of any kind.</p>\n<p><strong>Flash-Evap Piston Heads:</strong> This modification was developed in the early days of the steam engine, and remains popular even today. It requires disassembling the engine and inscribing a special rune into the top of the pistons which instantly turns injected water into steam on contact, with tremendous force. A steam engine with this modification installed gains a +2 boost to its Horsepower, and loses all of its Horsepower limitations. The engine is now considered an esoteric engine, and is subject to dispelling and esoterics nullification zones.</p>\n<p><strong>Header:</strong> Rather than an exhaust manifold and a system to pipe exhaust to the rear of the vehicle, this engine vents its exhaust straight out the side with short pipes. This results in a huge performance boost, granting the modified engine a +2 Horsepower increase. However, because the exhaust system is extremely limited, it can’t support as many turbochargers as a normal engine, limiting it to a maximum of one Turbocharger modification. Hooking up the turbocharger is also more difficult and requires a different system, doubling the cost and install time of the Turbocharger modification. The Header modification is incompatible with the Anti-Lag System modification. Anyone making a @Compendium[pf1.skills.YYmmxDgp0g3ltSUG]{Perception} check to hear a vehicle with the Header modification receives a +10 bonus.</p>\n<p>This modification is incompatible with the Performance Exhaust modification. It can only be installed on an engine that exhausts some form of waste - Guzzolene, Deezil, Void, and Steam engines that do not have the Recondenser modification.</p>\n<p><strong>Performance Exhaust:</strong> One obvious performance boost that can be made to a vehicle is to cut out all of the extra attachments to a vehicle’s exhaust system - mufflers are important for cutting down noise in a city, but they’re only restricting an engine’s true potential in the wastes. By removing as many bends and obstructions in a vehicle’s exhaust system, you have implemented a “straight-pipe” exhaust, granting your engine a +1 Horsepower increase. Anyone making a @Compendium[pf1.skills.YYmmxDgp0g3ltSUG]{Perception} check to hear a vehicle with the Header modification receives a +5 bonus.</p>\n<p>This modification is incompatible with the Header modification. It can only be installed on an engine that exhausts some form of waste - Guzzolene, Deezil, Void, and Steam engines that do not have the Recondenser modification.</p>\n<p><strong>Psiconverter:</strong> This flexible modification converts every 4 power points fed into it into 1 hour of operation for any engine type, allowing the psionically-gifted to fuel a vehicle regardless of what type of fuel it typically takes. Power points can be added by holding onto a conduit which accepts the psionic energy. This conduit is typically attached to the steering mechanism or handlebars to permit the driver to channel the energy themselves, though it can be mounted anywhere.</p>\n<p><strong>Recondenser:</strong> As the weakest available engine option, steam engines leave a lot to be desired compared to their more expensive kin. While recondensers don’t improve their performance, they do give the humble steam engine an advantage by capturing their “exhaust.” Recondensers take the steam that has been passed through the engine’s turbine and condense it back into water, allowing it to be fed back into the boiler and become steam to turn the turbine once again. Steam engines with recondensers installed never run out of fuel, unless their fuel tanks are drained or broken.</p>\n<p>This modification is incompatible with the Header and Performance Exhaust modification.</p>\n<p><strong>Solid Tires:</strong> Nothing strands you in the wastes quicker than a blown tire, so a common modification is to get solid tires that can’t be popped. These heavy tires grant a +1 effective Integrity Resistance to the Chassis they’re mounted on, and can never be punctured or deflated. However, because they cannot deform to adjust their grip on malleable surfaces, they double any offroad penalties. The listed details on the table are per-wheel, and every wheel on a vehicle must receive the modification in order to gain the benefits.</p>\n<p>This modification is incompatible with the Off Road Tires modification.</p>\n<p><strong>Squeeze System:</strong> This complex web of tubing and brackets mounts a squeeze canister in the engine bay of the vehicle, and provides all of the necessary hosiery and wiring required to charge and inject an engine with squeeze. Applying a shot of squeeze to an engine with a squeeze system is a free action made as part of a piloting action.</p>\n<p><strong>Supercharger:</strong> These powerful air compressors sit on top of the engine and are driven by a belt connected to the engine. They force air into the engine to the tune of their distinctive whine, and allow the engine to use more fuel and create more power. A supercharger increases the Engine’s Horsepower by 2. A single Engine can benefit from this modification twice.</p>\n<p><em>Special</em>: When a vehicle has at least one Supercharger and at least one Turbocharger on the same Engine, it is considered Twincharged. The combination flutter-whine emitted by the pair of performance-boosting compressor types grants a +2 morale bonus to attack rolls, saving throws, ability checks, and skill checks for the pilot and their allies that are currently on board.</p>\n<p><strong>Tuning:</strong> Engine tuning is when an engine’s timing chains and other moving parts are adjusted to work in perfect harmony. Well-tuned engines see huge performance gains to their Horsepower, making the shop of those skilled in the art of tuning (typically black thumbs, but sometimes bards can also tune engines - one of the best ways to tune them is by ear, after all) the first stop for the proud owner of a new engine.</p>\n<p>Engine tuning is priced based on the benefit provided to the engine’s Horsepower value. The price is equal to the Horsepower value increase squared, times 100 gp. If you can perform the tune yourself, then there is no cost associated, but failing the @Compendium[pf1.skills.L6LEhHRrn53cMuhE]{Craft} skill check to perform the tune means you cannot attempt to tune the same engine again for 1 month. The Horsepower increase granted by this modification can exceed the normal limitations of an engine.</p>\n<p><strong>Turbocharger:</strong> These small turbines are set inside (or near) the engine bay of a vehicle and are driven by the engine’s own exhaust system. Like the supercharger, it is an air compressor that forces additional air into the engine (and emits a pleasing flutter), allowing it to use more fuel while maintaining the ideal ratio of air and fuel. A turbocharger increases the Engine’s Horsepower by 1, but applies a 5% penalty to the vehicle’s XLR8 (after being modified by the Horsepower increase) due to the spin-up time. A single Engine can benefit from this modification four times.</p>\n<p><em>Special</em>: When a vehicle has at least one Supercharger and at least one Turbocharger on the same Engine, it is considered Twincharged. The combination flutter-whine emitted by the pair of performance-boosting compressor types grants a +2 morale bonus to attack rolls, saving throws, ability checks, and skill checks for the pilot and their allies that are currently on board.</p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"In2xLaPZGv8dRTFr":3},"flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.nucEucmd5gIJ4BrZ"}}}
{"_id":"heVI4TL1SIJVyHYP","name":"Vehicles - Ultras","content":"<p>For some pilots, the ultimate expression of their craft is to be at the helm of a mountainous machine operating at the absolute limits of (and oftentimes pushing the bounds of) modern engineering. Because they exist at the edge of what is possible for a single machine, Ultras have some unique rules for their operation and management that sets them apart from other vehicle types.</p>\n<p>Chief among these unique rules is that Ultra components do not behave the same way that those of other vehicles do. Their engines, transmissions, chassis, suspensions, and bodies are integrated into the vehicle in such a way that they cannot be divorced from them. This makes every component of an Ultra specific to that Ultra - they cannot have their parts swapped out or replaced with something drastically different to transform them in the same way that vehicles of other classifications can. Repairs to Ultras are purely narrative, and may occasionally require seeking out a rare proprietary part.</p>\n<p>Rather than calculating an Ultra’s assembled vehicle stats from the stats of its components, an Ultra will always come with its assembled stats as part of its write-up. These stats may not make sense in relation to each other, but that’s part of the wonder of Ultras - they are operating at such incredible scales to where their engineering solutions are sometimes unthinkable.</p>\n<p>So, what purpose does an Ultra’s components serve? Each component still has an Integrity value, and occasionally innate Integrity Resistance, to permit the Ultra to make Push attempts. Pilots of Ultras are often reluctant to make Push attempts unless they absolutely must, since finding replacements should a component’s Integrity reach zero is difficult.</p>\n<p>Because Ultras treat components differently than other vehicles, most vehicle modifications are not compatible with Ultras in general. This may make them appear to have less customization options in general, and as far as the rules for Vehicles are concerned, that is true. Instead, Ultra customization is richest outside of these rules - it is best to think of Ultras as mobile fortresses or keeps, and can be modified with additional structures and architecture befitting buildings that no ordinary vehicle could ever hope to support. Because they can be treated in many ways like land or architecture, they can also contain furniture and comfort items, as well as support as many weapons mounts as they have the floor space to fit.</p>\n<p>Treating Ultras as structures doesn’t necessarily have to stop there, though. Due to their size, some Ultras can be as immovable (unless they choose to move) as a building would be when faced with some forces, such as weather or difficult terrain. A flying fortress airship or supermassive cargo freighter can shrug off the kind of inclement weather that would effortlessly toss around smaller vehicles. All Ultras, regardless of type, take half penalties at most from weather or difficult terrain, and in some cases, a Game Master may decide that an Ultra may not suffer from these conditions at all.</p>\n<p> </p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"In2xLaPZGv8dRTFr":3},"flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.0e5WLntsTb6uRTFQ"}}}
{"_id":"i5P90tVM5MaT8lPH","name":"Vehicles - Vehicle Rules","content":"<p>Steamhorses and autos got so popular so quickly, and became such an important part of Bastion society, because they were simple enough to operate that anyone could learn in mere minutes how to control them - far faster than learning how to control a horse or other living mount, for sure.</p>\n<p>This ease of use is reflected in the rules of this section, which will outline how to pilot the various types of motorized vehicles available for purchase or construction in The Sundered Lands (and elsewhere, if you decide to extend these rules to other areas of your campaign).</p>\n<h3><strong>Vehicle Basics</strong></h3>\n<p>Vehicles are treated much like other objects, though they do have some rules that separate them from your typical everyday object.</p>\n<p>Vehicles must be in a more specific state than other objects to be considered attended for the purposes of <a title=\"Damaging Objects\" href=\"https://www.d20pfsrd.com/equipment/damaging-objects/#TOC-Saving-Throws\">making saving throws</a>. Specifically, a vehicle is only considered attended while it is in motion under its own power and has a pilot actively piloting it. Put another way, a vehicle is only considered attended when its pilot is able to react to threats at the time they appear.</p>\n<p>Assuming the vehicle is indeed attended, it functions as a mundane attended object. When subject to a saving throw, it makes saving throws as its owner. In the case of Reflex saving throws, the vehicle gains a bonus equal to its Reactivity. In the case of magical vehicles, they may use their own saving throw instead, which is given the same bonus equal to Reactivity.</p>\n<h3><strong>Pilot Qualifications</strong></h3>\n<p>First, the most important question: who can pilot a vehicle? Easy - everyone! Much like riding a horse, all characters who would reasonably have been exposed to a motorized vehicle are assumed to know how to pilot one. For most characters in The Sundered Lands, this means that just about everyone would be well-versed in how to pilot ground steamhorses and autos, at the very least. For anything else, ranks in the new @Compendium[tsl-content.tsl-skills.VTrVwSSCPSkTWjAZ]{Pilot} skill will be required.</p>\n<p>In the terms of the game, everyone is considered to be proficient in piloting ground versions of both Steamhorses and Autos, unless otherwise determined by the GM. Players should speak with their GM and work out what they might know and what they might not. One example of a player character that might start out without proficiency in piloting steamhorses and autos might be a character native to a place that hasn’t had any exposure to the technology. Except for these special cases, all characters are able to pilot any ground Steamhorse and Auto, even without any ranks in Pilot. In the event that a player and the GM have determined that a character does not automatically know how to pilot ground Steamhorses and Autos, they should gain this knowledge upon purchasing their first rank in the Pilot skill (in a way not dissimilar to the classic 3.5 barbarian’s <a title=\"Barbarian (D&amp;D 3.5e)\" href=\"https://www.d20srd.org/srd/classes/barbarian.htm#illiteracy\">illiteracy ability</a>).</p>\n<p>Heavies, along with all versions of aquatic and aerial vehicles, having slightly more complex methods for piloting them and less opportunities to be practiced on, are not as universally understood as steamhorses and autos in any category. Piloting any sort of heavy, or any sort of non-ground vehicle, will require some ranks in the Pilot skill.</p>\n<p>Even those who aren’t proficient in the type of vehicle they are attempting to pilot will still be able to get the vehicle to move - a Pilot check is not necessarily required to put these vehicles into motion. However, nonproficiency carries with it some penalties and conditions that will make using the vehicle to its fullest potential much harder. More information on this will be included in the Pilot skill entry.</p>\n<p>Ultras are the rarest and most difficult vehicles to pilot. They are usually one-of-a-kind machines with very specific operating procedures, and thus have special rules. Piloting an ultra, in addition to requiring a number of ranks in the Pilot skill, also requires specific training, which will take time. This is typically measured in a number of 8-hour days, and will be listed in the entry for the Ultra or left up to the GM to decide. </p>\n<h3><strong>Entering a Vehicle</strong></h3>\n<p>Rather than requiring a specific type of action, entering a vehicle seat instead requires expending a number of feet of movement as part of a move action. You can enter a vehicle at any point during your move, so long as you are in a square adjacent to the seat you wish to be sitting in, and have the remaining feet required to enter the vehicle in question. You can spread out the movement across multiple rounds, if you do not have enough movement to enter a vehicle with the remaining movement in the current round.</p>\n<p>You can see the number of feet required to enter a vehicle of any given classification and type on the table below.</p>\n<table style=\"width:29.6562%;height:85px\" border=\"1\">\n<thead>\n<tr style=\"height:17px\">\n<td style=\"width:55.8393%;height:17px;text-align:center\">Classification</td>\n<td style=\"width:44.1607%;height:17px;text-align:center\">Movement</td>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr style=\"height:17px\">\n<td style=\"width:55.8393%;height:17px;text-align:center\">Steamhorse</td>\n<td style=\"width:44.1607%;height:17px;text-align:center\">5 ft.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style=\"height:17px\">\n<td style=\"width:55.8393%;height:17px;text-align:center\">Auto</td>\n<td style=\"width:44.1607%;height:17px;text-align:center\">10 ft.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style=\"height:17px\">\n<td style=\"width:55.8393%;height:17px;text-align:center\">Heavy</td>\n<td style=\"width:44.1607%;height:17px;text-align:center\">15 ft.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style=\"height:17px\">\n<td style=\"width:55.8393%;height:17px;text-align:center\">Ultra</td>\n<td style=\"width:44.1607%;height:17px;text-align:center\">30 ft.</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<table style=\"width:207px;border-top:1px solid var(--color-border-light-tertiary);border-bottom:1px solid var(--color-border-light-tertiary);height:85px\" border=\"1\">\n<thead style=\"text-shadow:1px 1px var(--color-shadow-dark);border-bottom:1px solid var(--color-border-dark)\">\n<tr style=\"height:17px\">\n<td style=\"width:112.016px;height:17px;text-align:center\">Type</td>\n<td style=\"width:89.9844px;height:17px;text-align:center\">Movement</td>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr style=\"height:17px\">\n<td style=\"width:112.016px;height:17px;text-align:center\">Ground</td>\n<td style=\"width:89.9844px;height:17px;text-align:center\">+0 ft.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style=\"height:17px\">\n<td style=\"width:112.016px;height:17px;text-align:center\">Aquatic</td>\n<td style=\"width:89.9844px;height:17px;text-align:center\">+5 ft.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style=\"height:17px\">\n<td style=\"width:112.016px;height:17px;text-align:center\">Aerial</td>\n<td style=\"width:89.9844px;height:17px;text-align:center\">+15 ft.</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>In addition to the number of feet required to enter an Ultra, they may have a specific cockpit area on the vehicle that you must reach. Most Ultra classification vehicles are large enough to qualify as maps unto themselves, so this may require several turns of moving through the vehicle’s structure to reach the cockpit.</p>\n<p>If you are attempting to climb onto a vehicle, rather than enter any specific seat, then no specific additional movement is required - you simply move onto that part of the vehicle as you would any other square, which may require climbing, jumping, or any other special movement actions as normal terrain might.</p>\n<h3><strong>In the Driver's Seat</strong></h3>\n<p>Once seated, getting a vehicle moving and driving it round-to-round is a trivial matter.</p>\n<p>Starting a vehicle is a standard action, regardless of vehicle drive type, fuel type, classification, or current integrity status. If you are not proficient in the vehicle type and classification, you may be required to make an Intelligence check, as detailed in the Pilot skill rules. If you are the vehicle owner, or are permitted by them to operate the vehicle, you are assumed to have a key. If you are not the owner and are instead attempting to steal a vehicle, you must make a Disable Device skill check, treating the vehicle as a lock with a quality dependent on its classification:</p>\n<table style=\"width:54.8711%\" border=\"1\">\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:33.5113%\">Classification</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:31.672%\">Lock Quality</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:34.8168%\">Disable Device DC</td>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:33.5113%\">Steamhorse</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:31.672%\">Simple</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:34.8168%\">20</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:33.5113%\">Auto</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:31.672%\">Average</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:34.8168%\">25</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:33.5113%\">Heavy</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:31.672%\">Good</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:34.8168%\">30</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:33.5113%\">Ultra</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:31.672%\">Amazing</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:34.8168%\">40</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>Piloting a vehicle is a move-equivalent action by default, which can be reduced to a swift action with certain feats and class abilities. Only one Pilot action can be taken in a round, regardless of the action length or how many said action abilities the character has per round. In other words, you cannot substitute a standard action with a move action to get an extra Pilot action in a round, nor can you use haste or other spell effects to Pilot a vehicle twice in one round. Additionally, you cannot use abilities or spells that might grant another “turn” of rounds to pilot a vehicle twice in one round under any circumstances.</p>\n<p>When one enters and becomes seated in any seat (in the crew compartment or elsewhere) of a vehicle, they are assumed to have their safety harness buckled. While buckled, damage taken from vehicle collisions is reduced (more on this in the Collisions section), and being thrown from the vehicle is impossible. Unbuckling the safety harness (in order to leave the seat and move around the vehicle) requires no action at all, and can be done in combination with or as part of) any other action; buckling it once seated again requires only a swift action.</p>\n<p>While seated inside a vehicle, regardless of the seat, a vehicle provides cover relative to attacks from all sides by default through its paneling and doors. Some vehicles also have a hard top roof, which provides cover or total cover relative to attacks from above, as determined by the Game Master. Some vehicles may provide more or less cover than the standard - this will be detailed in the entry for their Body component, if relevant.</p>\n<p>Additionally, while inside a vehicle with a hard top roof, all characters are considered to be <a title=\"Squeezing\" href=\"https://www.d20pfsrd.com/gamemastering/combat/#squeezing\">squeezing through a tight space</a>, and take the appropriate penalties to movement and attack rolls when using a melee weapon, thrown weapon, or bow. If attacking a target inside the vehicle’s enclosed space with them, characters using crossbows and firearms also suffer the penalty to attack rolls, and all characters engaged in a combat inside a vehicle’s enclosed space suffer the Armor Class penalties.</p>\n<p>If the vehicle is in motion and the pilot fails to spend an action to maintain its course, the vehicle is considered unattended until its pilot once again actively maintains its course or a new pilot takes over. While unattended, the vehicle moves on its previous pilot’s turn (and can still move only a maximum of once per round). </p>\n<h3><strong>The Push</strong></h3>\n<p>No matter how rugged and well-built a vehicle may be, there are limitations to what it and its components are capable of pulling off. Operating a vehicle inside of these limitations can (almost) always be assumed to be a safe endeavor. However, great pilots know that by taking calculated risks with their machines, they are often able to perform outside the normal realm of possibility.</p>\n<p>A Push is just that: an attempt by the pilot to force the vehicle into overperforming, possibly at the expense of the vehicle’s ability to operate. Any pilot is able to push any component of the vehicle they are currently operating - there are no skill checks or special feats required. While some maneuvers described in the Pilot skill do require a Pilot skill check and count as a Push, the actual Push itself does not require the skill check.</p>\n<p>A Push is made against the Integrity for the given component. Whenever a Push is made, the pilot must roll a d10. If the result of this d10 roll is under the component’s Integrity, the Push is successful - the vehicle performs as desired. However, if the result of this d10 roll is equal to or greater than the component’s Integrity, the Push fails - the component fails to perform as desired, and the component’s Integrity is reduced by 1.</p>\n<p>Components, through either abilities or feats of the vehicle’s pilot, or the component itself, can have their Integrity bolstered through Integrity Resistance. This is a number added to the Integrity of the component, which increases its effective Integrity when rolling. So for example, if a component with an Integrity of 7 has an Integrity Resistance of +1, the d10 roll for a Push must meet or exceed 8 in order to count as a failed Push, as opposed to the usual 7. A roll of 10 on the d10 roll will always count as a failure, even if the Integrity Resistance brings a component’s effective Integrity above 10.</p>\n<p>Exactly what may constitute a Push is left intentionally vague so that the Game Master can call for a Push when it makes sense for the moment, though there are some obvious examples for each component listed below. Additionally, a number of maneuvers or stunts that require a Pilot check may also count as a Push, regardless of whether or not they are performed successfully (more about this can be found in the Pilot skill entry). The Game Master may also call for a Push for additional actions the pilot may attempt to perform, or for additional situations which might be particularly strenuous for the machine.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p><em>Engine:</em></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Moving at the vehicle's top Speed for more than 1 minute per Engine Integrity.</li>\n<li>Traveling faster than the vehicle's top Speed for 1 round.</li>\n<li>Starting the vehicle in severe cold (0° F and below) or severe heat (110° F and above).</li>\n<li>Operating the vehicle in extreme cold (-20° F and below) or extreme heat (140° F and above) for more than 1 minute per Engine Integrity.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><em>Transmission:</em></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Taking a double XLR8.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><em>Suspension:</em></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Reducing the vehicle's Turning by half of the pilot's ranks in the Pilot skill (minimum 1).</li>\n<li>Regain control of a falling Aerial vehicle (see Aerial Vehicle Stalling Speed below).</li>\n</ul>\n<p><em>Chassis:</em></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Taking a double Stop.</li>\n</ul>\n<p> </p>\n<p>Extreme cold (-20 F) and extreme heat (140 F) requires a Push to start the vehicle, and another Push for every minute of operation.</p>\n<p>Other instances of the Push can be found in other locations throughout this section, where their announcements are more relevant to the situations that cause them.</p>\n<h3><strong>Vehicles in Motion</strong></h3>\n<p>As previously stated, a vehicle’s Speed represents a vehicle’s top Speed rating, but a vehicle doesn’t have to travel at its top Speed all the time. In fact, it’s often inadvisable - doing so for a number of minutes equal to the vehicle’s Integrity rating results in a Push. The counter for the minutes at maximum Speed that contribute to a Push is reset every time the vehicle is powered off and allowed to sit for a number of hours equal to 11 minus the Engine’s current Integrity.</p>\n<p>Vehicles spend most of their time moving forward - that is, the direction the vehicle is facing - but if the vehicle is stationary, the pilot can choose to instead run the vehicle in one of its other drive directions. This is typically limited to reverse gear for most vehicles, but some have the ability to strafe or travel in other directions besides just forward and back. While traveling in reverse, a vehicle’s Speed is limited to 10% of its top Speed (minimum Speed 1), unless it is an Aquatic vehicle or has a special rule that states otherwise. The same rules about traveling at top Speed apply to a vehicle operating in reverse.</p>\n<p>The vehicle’s XLR8 is the maximum increase in Speed the vehicle can affect upon itself in a single round. Attempting to outdo this and increase Speed by more than the XLR8 in a single round requires a Push.</p>\n<p>While moving at its current Speed, the Turning represents the minimum number of squares forward and in the turning direction required for the vehicle to move in order to safely complete a full 90-degree turn. This calculation is provided as part of a built-in feature of the vehicle sheet.</p>\n<p>While some vehicles are able to turn on their own axis (turning in place), or on a zero-axis (which will be stated in the special rules of the components granting such an ability), all vehicles have a minimum Turning. The default is a minimum Turning equal to the length of the vehicle in squares. Any vehicle whose minimum Turning is not the default will mention so in the component, modification, or ability that grants the improved turning. For a vehicle able to turn on its own axis, the center point on the side the vehicle is turning towards acts as the pivot around which the vehicle rotates. For a vehicle able to turn on a zero-axis, it simply rotates in place as it desires. In all of these cases, the vehicle can make up to a 360-degree rotation as a move action at Speed 1.</p>\n<p>Some vehicles cannot turn under their own power at all. This, like those that can turn on their own axis or on a zero-axis, will be listed in the component imposing the special rule.</p>\n<p>Traveling at top Speed makes it difficult for a vehicle to stop on a dime, and this is represented by the vehicle’s Stopping. This calculation, like the Turning, is provided as part of a built-in feature of the vehicle sheet. It represents the reduction in Speed the vehicle can affect upon itself each round, and in that way it is something of a counterpart to the vehicle's XLR8. Like XLR8, trying to decelerate more than what the vehicle's Stopping allows will require a Push.</p>\n<h3><strong>Aerial Vehicle Stalling Speed</strong></h3>\n<p>Unlike Ground or Aquatic vehicles, Aerial vehicles have to worry about traveling fast enough to provide sufficient lift to stay airborne. If they drop below a certain Speed, they cannot get enough air to flow over the wings and provide lift, and so they plummet (or never take off at all). </p>\n<p>An Aerial vehicle’s Stall Speed, or the minimum Speed required to achieve flight, is equal to double the vehicle’s Load. Falling below this Speed in-flight results in the vehicle stalling; it powers down as the engine sputters and dies, and the entire aircraft begins to fall. Treat this as you would any other falling incident, though the pilot may attempt to recover the vehicle.</p>\n<p>To regain control of the vehicle as it falls, the pilot must succeed on a Push to the vehicle’s Suspension. Once they have control again, they may perform whatever actions they choose to try and save their skin. They may attempt a Push to the vehicle’s Engine or Transmission to attempt to pick up enough Speed to fly again - and may benefit from the fall as a descent to try and pick up sufficient Speed (see Vehicles on Difficult Terrain). They may also regain Speed from the use of an alchemical aid such as fuel additives or NUDJ, from a magic spell or psionic power, from favorable weather conditions like a tailwind, or whatever else they can think of that will work. Alternatively, they may just choose to take the chance to bail before going down with their craft - assuming they packed a parachute, of course.</p>\n<p>This does mean that some assembled Aerial vehicles might have insufficient power to ever get off the ground - in these cases, it’s back to the drawing board for the black thumb who built it.</p>\n<h3><strong>Moving On and Falling Off of Vehicles</strong></h3>\n<p>Sometimes, a character may have to move along the body of a vehicle while it is in motion. There could be any number of reasons why a character would wish to do this - to get to other stations on a vehicle, to collect gear from a cargo bay, or to intercept boarders are but a few examples.</p>\n<p>If a character is already on the vehicle they wish to move along, simply moving along the vehicle’s body requires no special checks - the vehicle is simply treated as difficult terrain. However, other conditions (ex. poor visibility, a storm) or actions (wanting to move at their full speed) could require the character to make a check, or could modify other checks.</p>\n<p>Jumping onto a moving vehicle, or jumping from one moving vehicle onto another, requires an appropriate skill check with a DC of 10 + 1 per point of difference in Speed between the jumper and the target. If jumping from one point on a moving vehicle onto another point on the same vehicle, the DC is simply 10, meaning most characters can automatically succeed simply by taking 10 if they are not under duress. This check may be modified by other factors per the required skill. If the difference in height between the starting and ending point of the jump is enough to where the jumper is at risk of taking falling damage, it is handled according to the normal rules for falling damage.</p>\n<p>A driver can shake unwanted hitchhikers or boarders with a Pilot check in one of two ways. They may choose to try and swerve the vehicle sharply, to which they gain a bonus equal to the vehicle’s Reactivity. Alternatively, they may slam on the brakes, which will slow the vehicle and instead confer a bonus equal to the vehicle’s Brakes. The result of this check sets the DC to keep from being thrown from the vehicle, which must be rolled by all occupants of the vehicle who are freely moving throughout the vehicle. This check can be made with either an appropriate skill check, or as a Reflex saving throw.</p>\n<p>While moving along a vehicle, a character may use their swift action at the end of their turn to hold on to the vehicle. This allows them to maintain a hold of the vehicle until the start of their next turn. If a character is holding on at the time they would be subject to a check to keep from falling off the vehicle, they gain a bonus equal to twice their Strength modifier on that check.</p>\n<p>For any character moving along the surface of a moving vehicle, any effect that would knock them prone or otherwise change their position, as well as any vehicle collisions (described below), will also warrant a check or saving throw to stay on the vehicle, should they fail the save against that effect. A character who loses consciousness for any reason while moving along the surface of a moving vehicle is entitled to a Reflex saving throw in order to stay on the vehicle. However, if they were holding on prior to becoming unconscious, they do not gain the benefits of holding on as described above.</p>\n<p>Failure for any of these checks means falling from their current position on the moving vehicle. This may mean that they fall onto another platform for the vehicle. If the character failed their check to remain on the vehicle by less than 5, and there is another platform for the vehicle in an adjacent square that is lower than the current platform, the character simply falls to that. In this case, the character handles falling normally (including taking, and any checks to prevent, applicable falling damage, if any), and are still on the vehicle.</p>\n<p>If there are no additional platforms of lower height, or if the character failed their check to remain on the vehicle by 5 or more, they instead fall off the vehicle completely. In addition to any applicable falling damage, the player takes an amount of damage equal to the vehicle’s Load plus its Speed at the time they fell. If they fall onto a yielding surface, such as soft ground or mud, this damage is halved. This damage is considered half bludgeoning damage, half force damage.</p>\n<h3><strong>Attacking and Defending a Vehicle</strong></h3>\n<p>Vehicles are subject to attacks just like any other object, but due to their special rules and additional mobility compared to most other objects, there are special rules and considerations that must be taken into account.</p>\n<p>Attacking a vehicle counts as a <a title=\"Sunder\" href=\"https://www.d20pfsrd.com/gamemastering/Combat/#TOC-Sunder\">Sunder attempt</a>, though unlike with typical ranged sunder attempts, a ranged sunder can be made against a vehicle without a special ability. Anything that applies to sunder attempts can apply when attacking a vehicle. Attacking a vehicle without the Improved Sunder feat will provoke an attack of opportunity from the pilot, regardless of where they are relative to the attacker, as well as provoking an attack of opportunity from all other eligible enemies. The pilot can either attack with a melee or ranged weapon (if able), or can instead make a Pilot check with a target DC of the attack roll result in an attempt to throw off the attack. If the pilot succeeds, the attack against the vehicle simply misses.</p>\n<p>Attacking a moving vehicle is considerably more difficult than attacking a stationary one, and considering the speeds some vehicles can achieve, it can even be more difficult than attacking a moving creature. Thus, the vehicle’s Speed imposes a to-hit penalty on any attack rolls made against it. For every 10 points of Speed difference between the attacker and the vehicle, the attacker suffers a -1 penalty to their attack roll. If the target vehicle is moving along a path parallel to the attacker, this penalty is halved (rounded down, to a minimum of -1). If the attacker is also on a moving vehicle, the penalty is doubled. Attempting a melee attack against a vehicle you are on imposes no penalty (as there is no difference in Speed), which means climbing onto a vehicle and performing a melee attack is the most reliable way to damage a moving vehicle, but doing so is a far more dangerous stunt to perform than simply shooting a vehicle from a distance.</p>\n<p>In many circumstances, a vehicle’s pilot can make a Pilot check in place of most other types of rolls that a vehicle might be subject to. Chief among these are Reflex saves - a vehicle pilot can use a Pilot check in place of the vehicle’s Reflex save. In this case, the outcome of this saving throw is also the result of the pilot’s saving throw - if the vehicle fails, they both fail, though this may not have any ill effect on the driver.</p>\n<p>When the vehicle is brought to below half of its total Hit Points, a component is targeted based on a roll against the table below. Whichever component is the result of that roll then loses 1 point of Integrity, and the vehicle gains the @Compendium[pf1.conditions.jQLJg0XQq4rx9yzx]{Broken} condition, conferring a -2 penalty to AC, as well as on @Compendium[tsl-content.tsl-skills.VTrVwSSCPSkTWjAZ]{Pilot} checks and saving throws. </p>\n<table style=\"width:41.8338%\" border=\"1\">\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:22.8121%\">d%</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:77.1879%\">Component Targeted</td>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:22.8121%\">01-25</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:77.1879%\">Chassis</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:22.8121%\">26-50</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:77.1879%\">Suspension</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:22.8121%\">51-70</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:77.1879%\">Transmission</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:22.8121%\">71-90</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:77.1879%\">Engine</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:22.8121%\">91-00</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:77.1879%\">Roll twice.</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>When the vehicle is reduced to 0 Hit Points, another component is targeted based on the same table, and it loses 1 point of Integrity. Additionally, the vehicle will power off immediately and cannot be run until repaired. The pilot may choose to power the machine back on, which is considered a Push to keep the vehicle running. If the Push fails, the vehicle continues running, but instead takes 2 points of Integrity to the targeted component.</p>\n<p>If a vehicle sporting a guzzolene or void engine is reduced to 0 hit points from an attack that results in a critical hit, electricity or fire damage, or from damage dealt by an explosion, the remaining fuel held in the vehicle’s fuel tank detonates. Everyone in or on the vehicle at the time of the explosion must save against the explosion - see the rules for guzzolene explosions in the Fuel section for the effects of a guzzolene explosion.</p>\n<h3><strong>Collisions</strong></h3>\n<p>Vehicle collisions occur all the time in Odium. For the purposes of this game, a vehicle collision is when a moving vehicle strikes either another object, structure, or terrain feature, or a living creature. Whether it be the result of poor performance in the Thunderdome, an unfortunate run-in with vultures in the wastes, or an intentional ramming attack as a desperate last option, just about the worst thing that can happen to a vehicle (or creature) is to get involved with some sort of collision.</p>\n<p>Vehicle collisions are treated as an area-of-effect line attack, striking everything along their path for a single turn of movement. This attack does not have to be intentional - the vehicle simply strikes whatever is in its way. For an unintentional collision, the DC for the Reflex saving throw to avoid being struck by the vehicle is 1 per 10 points of Speed difference. For an intentional attack, the DC is the half the Pilot check result made by the vehicle’s pilot (minimum 10), +1 per 10 points of Speed difference between the vehicle and its targets. In both cases, the target receives an additional -2 penalty on the Reflex save per size category smaller than the vehicle in all collisions.</p>\n<p>Damage is based on a simple base damage amount dealt to the vehicle in question, as well as whatever the vehicle impacted and all passengers and crew aboard, with modifiers and conditions affecting that damage until the final, true damage result is calculated independently for all involved.</p>\n<p>The base damage for a collision starts with the vehicle’s Speed at the time of impact. The vehicle that initiated the collision, whatever it has struck, and all crew members that are buckled in will be subject to this base damage, after all appropriate modifiers have been applied. If the vehicle struck another vehicle moving in the same direction, this base damage is instead the difference in Speed between the two vehicles. If the vehicle struck another in a head-on collision, the base damage is instead the sum of their respective Speeds. If the vehicle struck another in a T-bone collision, the base damage is instead the sum of the striking vehicle’s Speed, plus half the struck vehicle’s Speed.</p>\n<p>After the base damage is calculated, the damage between the moving vehicle and whatever it has struck are then split into their respective damages, with additional added damage applied based on the conditions of the collision.</p>\n<p>A vehicle’s Load also plays into the damage dealt to it and whatever it has struck. The lighter of the two’s base damage is increased by the difference between their Load. If what the vehicle struck was a permanent terrain fixture, or is so much greater in mass as to be immovable by the vehicle, both that target and the vehicle itself then takes an extra point of damage per 10 points of the striking vehicle’s Load.</p>\n<p>Size also plays a factor in determining damage. For every size category difference between the striking vehicle and its target, the damage taken by the larger of the two is halved, while the smaller of the two takes an additional 25% damage. So, if the striking vehicle is Gargantuan, and the target is only Medium, then the striking vehicle takes only ⅛ of the base damage, while the target takes an additional +75% of its base damage.</p>\n<p>Finally, the target takes additional damage equal to the striking vehicle’s modifiers to ramming damage, whether that be from fuel additives, spells, or other modifications.</p>\n<p>Passengers in a vehicle involved in a collision will also suffer damage, though typically, being in a vehicle and buckled in is a far less worrying fate than the alternative. If a passenger is seated in one of the seats designated in a vehicle’s crew capacity and buckled in, they reduce the damage taken from the collision by 25%, regardless of which vehicle they are in. If they are buckled into a vehicle with a cabin (that is, a vehicle with walls and a roof protecting their seat), they instead reduce this damage by 50%. All passengers buckled into a vehicle are subject to a Reflex save on the modified damage. The DC for this Reflex save is the same as that for the vehicle.</p>\n<p>If a passenger is not buckled in at the time of the collision, they are instead thrown from the vehicle, and calculate damage based on those rules as above.</p>\n<p>After all damage calculations have been made, all involved parties subject to damage reduce the damage dealt from their current hit points, with damage reduction, hardness, or modifications or effects that reduce damage from collisions applying as normal. A vehicle collision is considered half bludgeoning damage, half force damage.</p>\n<h3><strong>Wrecks</strong></h3>\n<p>A wreck is a special kind of collision where the vehicle collides with nothing at all - instead, it crashes on its own as a result of the pilot losing control, or a poor landing from a jump or stunt, or possibly being tripped up by a trap. Wrecks can come out of anywhere, which makes them so terrifying to scavengers.</p>\n<p>Despite how scary they can be, the rules surrounding dealing with a wreck are fairly simple. A wreck is treated as a collision, where the vehicle and its occupants simply set their base damage equal to the sum of its current Speed, Load, and all of its modifiers to ramming damage.</p>\n<h3><strong>Falling and Sinking</strong></h3>\n<p>When an Aerial vehicle is reduced to 0 Hit Points, its body no longer has enough surface area to provide lift, and it begins to fall. Once this has occurred, there is nothing (short of esoterics or divine intervention) that can save the aircraft or its occupants - it simply is no longer mechanically possible for it to fly. After 1 round of falling, the vehicle reaches Speed 10. On the second round of falling, the vehicle reaches its terminal falling Speed of 40. Treat the vehicle’s impact with the ground as a Wreck at whatever Speed it is traveling at.</p>\n<p>If the vehicle loses power due to some other reason, such as Engine failure from reaching Integrity 0, the pilot has more options on how to handle the situation. Typically, they can glide until the vehicle lands safely (though perhaps not smoothly - many a rough landing has resulted in a Wreck). The pilot must make a DC 25 Pilot check to successfully glide the vehicle to the ground (gliding 1 mile per 300 feet of elevation before losing power), and then another DC 25 Pilot check to land safely. Failing the first means the vehicle begins to fall, as above. Failing the second means the vehicle Wrecks upon landing.</p>\n<p>Unique to Aquatic vehicles, sinking is when a watercraft has sustained enough damage to compromise the integrity of its hull. When this happens, it loses its buoyancy and begins to fill with water, eventually slipping beneath the waves forever.</p>\n<p>When an Aquatic vehicle suffers enough damage to bring its Hit Points to 0, it begins to sink. This is a special activity that occurs on its own initiative count in combat, always going last in a round of turns. An Aquatic vehicle always takes 1 round per 100 points of its Load value to sink, with a 5% penalty per point of damage it took over the amount required to bring its Hit Points to 0, to a minimum of 1 round. Some actions may be taken to slow the sinking (typically through esoterics), but once it has reached this point, it’s only a matter of time.</p>\n<p>A sinking Aquatic vehicle fully slips below the water at the end of the last round of sinking.</p>\n<h3><strong>Vehicles on Difficult Terrain</strong></h3>\n<p>Up to now, the assumption has been that the vehicles will be running on a paved road, and for most settings, that may be true. However, there are times when vehicles need to travel off the beaten path. When that happens, the vehicle will suffer a penalty to various assembled stats based on the road conditions. The table below gives a set of stacking penalties for various types of ground the vehicle could be traveling on, as well as the ground conditions.</p>\n<table style=\"width:60.1719%\" border=\"1\">\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:41.3199%\">Ground Type</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:58.6801%\">Modifiers</td>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:41.3199%\">Paved Road or Stone</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:58.6801%\">--</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:41.3199%\">Hard or Packed Earth</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:58.6801%\">-5% XLR8, -5% St, +5% Tu</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:41.3199%\">Soft or Loose Earth</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:58.6801%\">-10% XLR8, -10% St, +10% Tu</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<table style=\"width:419.984px;border-top:1px solid var(--color-border-light-tertiary);border-bottom:1px solid var(--color-border-light-tertiary)\" border=\"1\">\n<thead style=\"text-shadow:1px 1px var(--color-shadow-dark);border-bottom:1px solid var(--color-border-dark)\">\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:170.109px\">Conditions</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:244.875px\">Modifiers</td>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:170.109px\">Dry</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:244.875px\">--</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:170.109px\">Wet or Slick</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:244.875px\">-25% XLR8, -25% St, +25% Tu</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:170.109px\">Ice or Snow</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:244.875px\">-50% XLR8, -50% St, +50% Tu</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:170.109px\">Unstable</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:244.875px\">-1 effective Integrity when Pushing</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>While in wet or icy conditions, attempting to slow down, stop, or turn at all requires a Pilot check with a DC of 20 (or, in extreme cases, a Push). Failure means the vehicle skids (in the case of a stop) or fails to turn (in the case of a turn), and the vehicle continues moving straight at its current speed for the turn.</p>\n<p>Aerial vehicles have similar penalties to particular stats based on flying conditions, but rather than the type of ground or moisture levels, an aerial vehicle is subject to the speed and direction of the wind.</p>\n<table border=\"1\">\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Wind Type</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Headwind Modifiers</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Crosswind Modifiers</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Tailwind Modifiers</td>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Light Wind</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">-5 Sp</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">--</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">+5 Sp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Moderate Wind</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">-10 Sp</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">--</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">+10 Sp</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Strong Wind</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">-15 Sp, -10% XLR8, +10% St</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">-10% Tu against wind,<br />+10% Tu into wind</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">+15 Sp, +10% XLR8, -10% St</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Severe Wind</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">-25 Sp, -25% XLR8, +25% St</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">-25% Tu against wind,<br />+25% Tu into wind</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">+25 Sp, +25% XLR8, -25% St</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Windstorm</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Lower of: -25 Sp or -50% Sp;<br />½ XLR8, +50% St</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">-50% Tu against wind,<br />+50% Tu into wind</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center\">Greater of: +25 Sp or +50% Sp;<br />+50% XLR8, -50% St</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>For windstorm-level wind speeds as a headwind and a tailwind, it states that the modifier is the “lower of” or “greater of” the given Speed flat values and percentages. This is meant to refer to the modified Speed stat - use the value that makes the final modified Speed stat lower or greater than the alternative, as stated. Note that wind speed penalties for a headwind can bring an aerial vehicle to such a low Speed that it would not be able to fly. If this happens while the vehicle is aloft, it stalls.</p>\n<p>Operating an aerial vehicle during inclement weather is significantly more dangerous, and a Game Master may decide that an aerial vehicle could be subject to damage from turbulence or intense weather conditions beyond what is listed here. In any case, it is typically the wind itself that impedes a vehicle’s movement, but icing over, getting struck by lightning, flying into a tornado, or visibility could create additional issues outside the scope of this section.</p>\n<p>Aquatic vehicles suffer penalties and other drawbacks based on the water’s conditions and obstructions. In some cases, the vehicle may take damage if it trundles carelessly into conditions that could puncture the hull. In the event that a Push specifies an outcome for failure, the vehicle suffers the normal consequences for failing a Push in addition to whatever is listed. </p>\n<p>For the Heavy Waves condition, use the following values as the vehicle's multiplier:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Steamhorse: 1</li>\n<li>Auto: 10</li>\n<li>Heavy: 25</li>\n<li>Ultra: 50</li>\n</ul>\n<table style=\"width:64.4699%\" border=\"1\">\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:28.1132%\">Aquatic Conditions</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:71.8868%\">Modifiers</td>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:28.1132%\">Calm</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:71.8868%\">--</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:28.1132%\">Choppy</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:71.8868%\">-50% Sp, St, XLR8; +100% Tu</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:28.1132%\">Heavy Waves</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:71.8868%\">Choppy + Push every 10 x Size minutes or capsize</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<table style=\"width:450px;border-top:1px solid var(--color-border-light-tertiary);border-bottom:1px solid var(--color-border-light-tertiary)\" border=\"1\">\n<thead style=\"text-shadow:1px 1px var(--color-shadow-dark);border-bottom:1px solid var(--color-border-dark)\">\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:123px\">Obstructions</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:322px\">Modifiers</td>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:123px\">Ice</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:322px\">½ (Sp + Ld) damage; risk collision with ice</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:123px\">Foliage</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:322px\">Push every Po rounds</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:123px\">Shallows</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:322px\">Sp + Ld damage</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>At some point in its life, a vehicle comes across a heavy slope. For most situations, the effects of the slope will apply to all vehicles in an encounter with consistent penalties across the board, or will be encountered in a narrative “travel time,” making it easy to simply ignore the condition. For situations where it must be observed, however, use the following table:</p>\n<table style=\"width:71.6332%\" border=\"1\">\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:26.0481%\">Slope Conditions</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:37.2786%\">Incline (per 5 degrees)</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:36.6733%\">Decline (per 5 degrees)</td>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:26.0481%\">Dry</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:37.2786%\">-5% Sp and Tq, +5% St</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:36.6733%\">+5% Sp and Tq, -5% St</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:26.0481%\">Wet</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:37.2786%\">-10% Sp and Tq, +10% St</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:36.6733%\">+10% Sp and Tq, -10% St</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:26.0481%\">Snow/Ice</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:37.2786%\">-20% Sp and Tq, +10% St*</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:36.6733%\">+20% Sp and Tq, -10% St*</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<blockquote>\n<p>* Vehicles on a snowy or icy slope are at a severe risk of losing control. The Game Master may choose to handle this however they want considering the circumstances, but it is recommended that trying to decelerate or perform any sort of vehicle stunt in these conditions always be treated as a Push unto itself, in addition to other required Push rolls for the given maneuver.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Aerial vehicles treat climbs as dry slopes for the purpose of determining the impact on their Speed, and whether they can perform a given climb without stalling out.</p>\n<p>When a vehicle is not traveling on some sort of established road, or even on a flat surface free of obstacles, the vehicle is considered to be offroading. Some vehicle classifications and drive types excel at this more than others, but any vehicle can make the attempt. When offroading begins, the vehicle makes an initial Push. Success means the vehicle is able to successfully traverse the difficult terrain for a distance of 1 mile - failure means the vehicle gets stuck. The vehicle must make this Push again at the beginning of each additional mile of difficult terrain traversed.</p>\n<p>While crawling over terrain that would reasonably impede a vehicle, it is wise to move at a slow and careful pace to avoid damaging the vehicle - every round of movement in excess of 10% of the vehicle’s Top Speed will require a Push.</p>\n<p>Another potential risk to vehicles is offroading through a body of water. If the water is too deep or the pilot isn’t careful, this can cause the engine to get flooded. For every round a vehicle is still powered on while its air intake is under water, the pilot must make a Push to prevent the engine from flooding. A vehicle’s air intake is considered to be underwater if the entire engine bay is submerged, unless the vehicle has a modification that raises the air intake. After a number of consecutive rounds spent underwater equal to the engine’s Integrity, the engine is treated as having failed a Push anyway.</p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"In2xLaPZGv8dRTFr":3},"flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.l29WrfB5SejHMtd5"}}}
{"_id":"qiQLRCvKrpBCk1F1","name":"Vehicles - Engine Descriptions","content":"<p><strong>Engines:</strong> The base cost for an engine is listed on the table Component Costs - Engine. The cost for naturally-aspirated engines (that is, an engine which does not have a supercharger or turbocharger) that exceed a Horsepower rating of 10 is twice the cost of the previous engine for every point of Horsepower above 10. So, a naturally-aspirated engine with a Horsepower rating of 11 will cost 12,000 gp (double the 6,000 gp cost of the Horsepower 10 engine), one with a Horsepower rating of 12 will cost 24,000 gp, and so on. Each engine has its strengths and weaknesses, with some even having special abilities the driver can use for maneuvers while driving. Some types of engines will have a limit on how much Horsepower they can have while naturally aspirated.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>        <em>Steam: </em>The cheapest (and thus most plentiful) power plant in the city of Bastion. Their fuel (water) is the cheapest available, they are hardly ever at risk of failing due to magical attack, and they can even be modified to recondense and reuse their fuel to greatly extend their own operating time.</p>\n<p>        Steam engines gain a +4 bonus to all saving throws against any magical attack that would disable them or cause them to malfunction.</p>\n<p>        Steam engines cannot be purchased with a base Horsepower greater than 6.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>        <em>Guzzolene: </em>The scavenger’s own beating heart. These internal combustion engines use combustible liquid fuel to power their rides. Guzzolene itself is refined in Industria and, while not as plentiful as tainted water for steam power, is still easy to come by at a fair price. Guzzolene is extremely volatile, lending itself to use in hyper-fast stallions and sprinter hogs.</p>\n<p>        Drivers of vehicles sporting guzzolene engines can make a Push and burn an amount of fuel equivalent to one hour of operation in order to run the engine rich, creating a massive gout of flame which erupts from the exhaust. This effect creates a 15-foot cone of fire from every square the exhaust pipes on the vehicle are located, in the opposite direction of the vehicle, dealing damage as a hellbelcher. The driver makes a Pilot check in place of an attack roll, with no possibility of a misfire.</p>\n<p>        Guzzolene engines cannot be purchased with a base Horsepower greater than 12.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>        <em>Deezil:</em> Whenever there is a need for a reliable engine to work tirelessly far longer than when any other would quit, accept nothing less. Deezil engines use deezil fuel, which is like a more stable, nonflammable version of guzzolene. Deezil engines are also more efficient than guzzolene engines, allowing them to do more work than a guzzolene engine exerting the same amount of effort. This makes them the prime candidates for generators, pump engines, and the engines of vehicles designed to pull heavy loads.</p>\n<p>        Drivers of vehicles sporting deezil engines can make a Push and burn an amount of fuel equivalent to one hour of operation in order to run the engine rich, causing a massive gout of thick black smoke to erupt from the exhaust. This effect functions as if a stinking cloud spell had been cast on each of the exhausts. Instead of the normal area of effect, the vehicle trails the cloud with it for one round, then ceases, leaving the cloud over the area it passed to linger or disperse as normal. Additionally, a deezil engine provides a +50 bonus to the vehicle’s Torque for every point of Horsepower it has.</p>\n<p>        Deezil engines cannot be purchased with a base Horsepower greater than 12.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>        <em>Arcanomotor and Crystal Engine:</em> Esoteric engineering has come a long way as of late, and nothing proves that better than the arcanomotor and the crystal engine. Where other engines consume fuel, these engines convert esoteric energy into mechanical energy. Naturally, arcanomotors metabolize arcane energy, channeled into it by a knowing operator from the Weave or passed into it from the activity of the gods themselves. Crystal engines instead are fed pure psionic energy, either by an operator who themselves has the Gift, or by feeding it the energy stored in power stones.</p>\n<p>        Arcanomotors can convert every spell level fed into it into 1 hour of operation for the chosen vehicle. Crystal engines can instead convert 2 power points into the same.</p>\n<p>        Arcanomotors and crystal engines can also be overcharged to increase performance. They can be fed additional energy to immediately increase the Horsepower, Reactivity, or Brakes stat by 1 per additional hour of operation fed into it, or shift the Power Transfer up or down by the same amount, to their permitted limits. This performance boost lasts for one round.</p>\n<p>        Additionally, arcanomotors and crystal engines are practically silent, and as such, cannot be detected by sound at a distance. This makes detecting them at night a difficult task.</p>\n<p>        Arcanomotors and crystal engines do not have a base Horsepower limit. For as powerful and efficient as they can be, however, they are at an incredible risk of faltering in the wild magic and esoterics nullification zones that can be found in the wastes. Those operating a vehicle equipped with one of these engines should take extra precautions.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>        <em>Elemental: </em>Binding elementals to power large vessels has been a practice well over two centuries now, but only recently have the materials and binding techniques permit the use of the technique in binding elementals to engines for personal vehicles. For most, this is prohibitively expensive and far out of reach, but it produces some of the most powerful engines ever made.</p>\n<p>        Elemental engines are able to extend a paired elemental immunity and vulnerability to all occupants of the vehicle. This is automatically applied to any creature in physical contact with the body of the vehicle while it is powered on, and removed from an affected creature immediately upon their loss of physical contact with the vehicle or upon the vehicle powering down. The type of elemental immunity and vulnerability are dependent on the bound elemental, based on the table below.</p>\n<table style=\"width:46.8481%\" border=\"1\">\n<thead style=\"text-shadow:1px 1px var(--color-shadow-dark);border-bottom:1px solid var(--color-border-dark)\">\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:100%\" colspan=\"3\">Elemental Immunities and Vulnerabilities¹</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:30.4225%\">Elemental</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:34.3662%\">Immunity</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:35.2113%\">Vulnerability</td>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:30.4225%\">Aether</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:34.3662%\">Radiation</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:35.2113%\">Force</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:30.4225%\">Air</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:34.3662%\">Electricity</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:35.2113%\">Fire</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:30.4225%\">Earth</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:34.3662%\">Electricity</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:35.2113%\">Cold</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:30.4225%\">Fire</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:34.3662%\">Fire</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:35.2113%\">Cold</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:30.4225%\">Ice</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:34.3662%\">Cold</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:35.2113%\">Fire</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:30.4225%\">Lightning</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:34.3662%\">Electricity</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:35.2113%\">Acid</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:30.4225%\">Magma</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:34.3662%\">Fire</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:35.2113%\">Cold</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:30.4225%\">Mud</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:34.3662%\">Acid</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:35.2113%\">Fire</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:30.4225%\">Water</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:34.3662%\">Cold</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:35.2113%\">Electricity</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<blockquote style=\"border-left:3px solid var(--color-border-light-tertiary)\">\n<p>¹ This table contains only official Pathfinder elemental creatures and content from The Sundered Lands. For an expanded list that includes elementals from Pathfinder third-party content, D&amp;D 3.5 and its third party content, and other homebrew content, see the optional Expanded Elemental Engine section.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>        Elementals can also be summoned forth from their engines by the Pilot to fight. To coax the elemental out of the engine, the pilot must make their choice of a Wisdom or Charisma check as a standard action, opposed by the elemental with a Will saving throw. If the elemental succeeds, it remains inside the engine, and is immune to further attempts to coax it out for the next 24 hours. If it fails, it appears on the same square as the engine’s location on the vehicle. It shares its turn with the vehicle. It acts on its own, with the primary goal of protecting itself and the vehicle from what it perceives as the greatest threat. It is limited in movement to the vehicle itself, having to always be in contact with the vehicle.</p>\n<p>        The elemental can be ordered back into the engine as a free action by the pilot on their turn. The elemental’s hit points are independent of the engine’s, but returns immediately to the engine if the vehicle is powered down or the engine sustains enough damage to shut down. If the elemental is slain while outside the engine, it is no longer bound to the engine, and the engine becomes worthless.</p>\n<p>        If an elemental engine is reduced to Integrity 0, the binding magic fails, releasing the elemental. It appears immediately on the same square as the engine’s location on the vehicle, and can act freely according to its own will - in most cases, this does not bode well for anyone nearby.</p>\n<p>        Elemental engines have a base Horsepower equal to 1½ times the Challenge Rating of the elemental creature bound within it, and so their costs are determined prior to their creation based on the specific elemental that is to be bound to it.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>        <em>Tourbillon:</em> Hailing from Canton d’Horloge, the tourbillon engine is nothing less than a miracle of modern horological engineering. This complex series of gears and springs is able to power a vehicle without stopping, seemingly forever, without requiring any fuel whatsoever.</p>\n<p>        A tourbillon engine takes no fuel, but counts its hours of operation differently than other vehicles. A vehicle utilizing a tourbillon engine must remain in constant motion in order to provide movement to the mechanisms that wind the engine’s mainspring. Rather than counting down as fuel is used, the vehicle instead begins counting down while stationary. Once in motion again, it recharges its lost hours of operation at a rate of 1 hour gained per every 2 hours in motion. While parked at Bastion, special turntables in the Motor Fields can keep the vehicles moving by spinning them in a circle, keeping them charged and ready.</p>\n<p>        Additionally, tourbillon engines are practically silent, and as such, cannot be detected by sound at a distance. This makes detecting them at night a difficult task.</p>\n<p>        Tourbillon engines cannot be purchased with a base Horsepower greater than 12.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>        <em>Void:</em> These dangerous and powerful engines are the result of an ongoing experiment by the Forscythe Company (one that is rumored to be something of a black mark for them). No one is entirely sure how they work, or even how to safely disassemble them. Contained within the engine is a volatile material that is so efficient in the energy it consumes that the engine seemingly never runs out of fuel - or, at least, nobody has ever claimed to see one run out, and certainly no one knows how to refuel them if one were to run empty.</p>\n<p>        Void engines use minute amounts of fuel, and as such a full tank lasts for so long that they are always considered to be filled. Their hours of operation seem to never deplete, and they are immune to any effect that would drain the engine of its fuel - this is a supernatural effect, and the engine has extensive shielding to prevent esoterics nullification effects from disabling the engine’s safety mechanisms. This gives it the Esoengine Shielding modification included.</p>\n<p>        Drivers of vehicles sporting void engines can make a Push in order to overextend the engine, suffusing the area around it with deadly radiation. Every creature within 30 feet of the vehicle, including occupants, must make a Fortitude save against high radiation. The radiation fades after one round.</p>\n<p>        Unlike other engines, void engines cannot be purchased through normal means. Most of those that have been found were in abandoned vehicles or facilities in the wastes, and none who own one is ever willing to part with it except when in dire need.</p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"In2xLaPZGv8dRTFr":3},"flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.tp5V3hpNnRfuVYqh"}}}
{"_id":"sXf75HdN9MmDoC73","name":"Vehicles - Classifications","content":"<p>There are four classifications of vehicles, which give a basic description of their size, shape, and role within the many fleets of the scavenger guilds of Bastion. These classifications will define what sort of parts their respective vehicles can take.</p>\n<p><em>        Steamhorse:</em> This classification describes any two-, three-, or four-wheeled motorized vehicle which is generally ridden with the driver stradling the chassis, and with the engine mounted directly beneath the driver. Occasionally, they may have different drive methods or seating situations, but the majority will fall into this description. They will almost never have a roof or other cabin structure, instead having the driver exposed to open air. Built for maneuverability above all else, these vehicles have a wide range of speeds and tend to fare better than all other classifications when dealing with rough terrain. Being the cheapest vehicles to manufacture means they are available in a wide range of configurations, with versions existing for nearly every size enthusiast. The majority will count as Small through Large size.</p>\n<p><em>        Auto:</em> This classification describes any motorized vehicle with three or more wheels that is primarily designed for transporting people as opposed to cargo. Most house their engines in an engine bay, protecting it from outside harm, unlike the Steamhorses whose engines are largely exposed. Most, but not all, will have a cabin structure, and some may have added spaces to carry additional cargo or passengers. Not as flexible in sizing as the Steamhorses, Autos are typically built to be driven by Medium-size creatures (though Small-size creatures can make modifications) and tend mostly towards the sizes Large through Huge.</p>\n<p><em>        Heavies:</em> This classification describes any motorized vehicle with four or more wheels that is primarily designed to transport cargo. Their shapes may vary in a number of ways, but each will typically have a cabin that can support up to three individuals and either a large integrated storage area for cargo, or a towing system to pull separate vehicles that exclusively store cargo. Their design and manufacture is almost exclusively seen as the territory of the dwarves, whose practical minds are well suited to their conception. Built for work and little else, these come in sizes ranging from Huge through Colossal.</p>\n<p><em>        Ultras:</em> This classification describes any motorized vehicle that exceeds a Heavy in size by a considerable amount. Very little else can be used to classify these monstrous machines by way of description, as they are typically built with a specialized purpose in mind. These may appear in the wastes as repurposed mining equipment, large transportation vessels, or airships, to name but a few. Many have completely custom components that are incompatible with any other classification or even other vehicles within the Ultra class. Their operation typically requires dedicated training which brings with it a great deal of respect from other operators and scavengers - Ultra pilots are seen as prized assets to any scavenger guild they happen to join. These vehicles will rarely fit into anything less than the Colossal size category, and some go beyond even that.</p>\n<p>In addition to the four classifications, there are also three main types of vehicle that communicate how it moves - whether it moves along the ground, floats or swims through the water, or flies in the air. These are referred to as <em>Ground</em>, <em>Aquatic</em>, and <em>Aerial </em>respectively.</p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"In2xLaPZGv8dRTFr":3},"flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.1lfa3hxP36TvyP5f"}}}
{"name":"Vehicles - Suspension Descriptions","content":"<p><strong>Suspensions:</strong> The base cost for a suspension system is listed on the table Component Costs - Suspension. The cost for suspensions that exceed a Reactivity rating of 10 is the sum of the price for the two previous Reactivity ratings. So, a suspension with a Reactivity rating of 11 will cost 1,440 gp (the sum of 890 gp for a Reactivity 10 suspension, and 550 gp for a Reactivity 9 suspension). There are two considerations for a suspension: its <strong>Type</strong>, or method of operation; and its <strong>Dependency</strong>, or whether the wheels on an axle can move together or separately. Some types of suspensions will have a limit on how much Reactivity they can have.</p>\n<p><strong>        Type:</strong></p>\n<p>        <em>Mechanical: </em>Most suspensions will use a mechanical system for their suspension. For ground vehicles, that usually means either a torsion bar or some manner of coil or leaf spring. Aerial and aquatic vehicles instead use a system of levers, gears, and pulleys to operate the wing and fin flaps, or rudder and foils.</p>\n<p>        Mechanical suspensions cannot be purchased with a base Reactivity greater than 8.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>        <em>Hydraulic:</em> These suspensions will use pistons filled with an incompressible liquid instead of compressing a spring or twisting a bar. This allows a traveling wheel to spring back into position, or apply force to a fin or rudder to move with more conviction against the medium the vehicle travels through.</p>\n<p>        Hydraulic suspensions cannot be purchased with a base Reactivity greater than 10.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>        <em>Pneumatic:</em> The primary difference between these and hydraulic suspensions is that pneumatic suspensions use a much more compressible fluid (air), which provides a smoother travel than the more stiff and inflexible hydraulic piston.</p>\n<p>        Pneumatic suspensions cannot be purchased with a base Reactivity greater than 12.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>        <em>Esoteric:</em> The best of the best in suspension technology, the esoteric suspension uses arcanotech or psionics to attach the vehicle to whatever steers it. For a ground vehicle, this means the wheels (or tracks, screw, etc.) are fixed to the vehicle with an esoteric tether, and power from the engine is transferred to it through this link. This makes the vehicle appear to be entirely detached from its wheels, wings, or other components, with everything floating in parallel. This allows the vehicle to react to any road conditions without affecting the body too much. For an aerial vehicle, this not only treats the landing gear like the ground version would, but also allows the entire wing or fin to rotate and affect turning. For aquatic vehicles, this affects the rudder (and hydrofoils, if applicable) in much the same way.</p>\n<p>        Esoteric suspensions have no Reactivity maximum. Additionally, esoteric suspensions gain 1 point of Integrity Resistance, as there are no moving parts to wear down.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>        <strong>Dependency:</strong></p>\n<p>        <em>Dependent: </em>A fully dependent suspension system is set up so that each wheel on an axle travels together (in other words, the suspension applies to the entire axle), for every axle. While cheap and tough, these suspensions make for an uncomfortable ride, and tend to tire passengers and pilots before long.</p>\n<p>        Anyone on a ground vehicle with fully dependent suspension can only deal with 6 hours of travel per day, and cannot effectively find rest aboard such a vehicle while in motion. If they continue traveling beyond that, they become fatigued. If they travel another full hour beyond that, they are instead exhausted. </p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>        <em>Mixed:</em> If an otherwise dependent suspension system has at least one axle where the wheels can travel independently of each other (usually the frontmost axle), that system is considered a mixed suspension system. While not a perfectly smooth and comfortable ride, it is more reactive than a dependent system, which allows most to bear a full day of riding before finding themselves tiring of the experience.</p>\n<p>        Anyone on a ground vehicle with a mixed suspension can only deal with 8 hours of travel per day, and cannot effectively find rest aboard such a vehicle while in motion. If they continue traveling beyond that, they become fatigued. If they travel another full hour beyond that, they are instead exhausted. </p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>        <em>Fully Independent:</em> Top of the line suspension systems will have every point of contact travel independently of all others, making the system fully independent. Ground vehicles equipped with these are preferred by any who have had the privilege to travel long distances in them. As for aerial and aquatic vehicles, they <strong>MUST </strong>utilize such suspension systems in order to operate effectively.</p>\n<p>        Anyone on a vehicle with a fully independent suspension can travel any amount of time without tiring of the riding itself, and are able to effectively rest aboard such a vehicle while in motion, given that there are no external conditions preventing rest such as inclement weather or turbulence.</p>\n<p> </p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"In2xLaPZGv8dRTFr":3},"flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.wb6pJe0d27w06PwG"}},"_id":"v9CTejiMLBDcFP3p"}
{"name":"Flare Communication","content":"<p>Flares are small, cylindrical pyrotechnic devices that can be used to signal location and communicate over long distances. They can be shot out of a flare gun, or lit manually. When shot out of a flare gun, they burn brightly so that they can be seen at night, and burst with colored chalk to be seen during the day. Lighting a flare manually is a move action, after which it immediately sheds light like a sunrod and emits a small trail of smoke the same color as the light it produces. Flares typically burn and emit smoke with a bright red color, but can be purchased in other colors, at no additional cost, that can be used to send messages over distance. Flares can also be thrown with a 10-foot range increment. Flares that land in flammable material will instantly set it alight. Flares burn for 1 minute before they burn out completely.</p>\n<p>Flare communication is a pseudo-language used to communicate over large distances. Each color has a vague meaning, and can be combined with other flares to communicate more complex messages.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Red means danger or aggression.</li>\n<li>Orange means caution.</li>\n<li>Yellow means failure.</li>\n<li>Green means safe or secure.</li>\n<li>Blue means success.</li>\n<li>Purple means important or high-value.</li>\n<li>Black means dead or death.</li>\n<li>Gray means neutral or nothing.</li>\n<li>Magenta means unusual or weird.</li>\n<li>White means peace or nonaggression.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>These flares can be sent up in one-, two-, or three-color combinations to convey increasingly complex or specific messages. Typically, the order of colors is significant: the first flare communicates the state of the party sending the flare, the second flare communicates how the intended viewing party should see the sending party, and the third flare indicates an order or provides a status update. For example, a red flare on its own indicates that the sending party is in danger, while a white flare by itself might mean, “we come in peace.” A white flare followed by a red flare could mean, “we come in peace, but are prepared to defend ourselves if necessary.” Three white flares would indicate surrender. One well-known color combination is red-red-black, known as the dreaded bloodsmoke cloud. Seeing this in the wastes means that a hunt or a war has been declared, and could mean trouble for you very, very soon.</p>\n<p> </p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"In2xLaPZGv8dRTFr":3},"flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.wYh1Tz4GglXc5QNn"}},"_id":"whSQco27BOb27Pkg"}
